<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boston Globe Publisher Named </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A senior vice president at The New York Times was  
named publisher of The Boston Globe on Monday, ending one family's 
126-year reign at the New England newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard H. Gilman succeeded publisher Benjamin B. Taylor, who  
will remain chairman of the Globe Newspaper Company Board. The New 
York Times is the Globe's parent company. 
</P>
<P>
	The change was made by the New York Times Co. because of a  
``difference in approach to management,'' said Globe spokesman 
Richard Gulla, who declined to elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
	The Globe was sold to the Times in 1993 in a $1.1 billion deal  
that guaranteed the Boston paper independence in news and 
management for at least five years. 
</P>
<P>
	Though such a move had been rumored in the industry since the  
Times bought the Globe, officials from both papers said no other 
major changes -- including layoffs -- were planned. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no other shoe to drop,'' Gilman said.  
</P>
<P>
	Arthur Sulzberger Jr., chairman of The New York Times Co., said  
Gilman will bring ``vision and leadership'' to the Globe, adding 
that, ``Under Rich, The Globe will remain the voice of New 
England.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sulzberger also praised Taylor, whose family has lead the  
publication for four generations. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ben Taylor has made many important contributions to the Globe  
during the past 27 years. His commitment to the newspaper, service 
to the community and dedication to quality journalism are 
unquestioned,'' Sulzberger said. 
</P>
<P>
	John Morton, media consultant and columnist for the American  
Journalism Review, said the Times likely wanted a Globe publisher 
with more experience on the business and management side. 
</P>
<P>
	``The paper is now controlled by the Sulzberger family, and it's  
inevitable that the Boston Globe ... is eventually going to be run 
by people who are in the New York Times culture,'' Morton said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they've been very respectful of the Taylor family,''  
he added. ``But clearly it is now a Sulzberger newspaper.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gilman, 48, has been senior vice president of operations for The  
New York Times since 1993. He has, at various times, overseen 
production, systems and technology, the development of plant 
facilities and circulation. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to his business experience, he worked as a newspaper  
reporter and editor for more than a decade, starting his career as 
a reporter at The Arizona Daily Star in Tucson. During his tenure 
there, the paper won its first Pulitzer Prize in 1981. 
</P>
<P>
	At The New York Times, Gilman is credited with overseeing the  
newspapers' largest circulation growth since 1992. He also 
introduced color printing to the newspaper's weekday editions. 
</P>
<P>
	Taylor, 52, has been with the Globe since 1972 and was named  
publisher in 1997. In between, he worked as a general assignment 
reporter, a political reporter in the paper's Washington bureau, 
assistant business editor, assistant managing editor for local news 
and executive editor. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, he was named chairman and chief executive officer of  
the Globe Newspaper Company. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a bit of a sad day, I have to admit,'' Taylor said. ``But  
I'm focused on looking forward.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
