<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cruise, Kidman Sues Newspaper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A judge has given the green light to a  
lawsuit brought against the Star newspaper after it reported Tom 
Cruise and Nicole Kidman had help from sex therapists in filming 
``Eyes Wide Shut.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The actors, who are married, are seeking unspecified damages.  
Phil Bunton, editor of the Tarrytown, N.Y.-based Star, said the 
tabloid stands behind its story. 
</P>
<P>
	The March 30 article in the weekly supermarket tabloid was  
headlined: ``We had to teach Tom and Nicole how to make love.'' It 
claimed sex therapists Tony and Wendy Duffield said they were hired 
to teach the actors how to perform in love scenes. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit said the Duffields signed affidavits saying they  
were never hired to coach Cruise or Miss Kidman for the film. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal suit, filed April 22, also claims pictures  
accompanying the article represented commercial misappropriation of 
Cruise and Miss Kidman's names and likenesses. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
