<DOCNO> APW19990712.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 17:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NYC Pressured Over Police Brutality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Pressure mounted Monday for the police  
department to revamp its disciplinary practices after a federal 
investigation confirmed what critics have long contended: brutal 
cops often go unpunished. 
</P>
<P>
	City and federal officials acknowledged that secret negotiations  
are underway to reach a settlement on what reforms the nation's 
largest police department should adopt. The talks -- aimed at 
avoiding a court battle -- stem from a two-year investigation of the 
New York Police Department by the U.S. attorney's office. 
</P>
<P>
	Zachary Carter, U.S. attorney for Brooklyn's Eastern District,  
reviewed thousands of allegations of abuse and reportedly has 
concluded the department has not properly policed its 40,000 
officers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not the usual suspects who are criticizing the department  
now; it's the federal government and that's significant,'' said 
Norman Siegel, executive director of the New York Civil Liberties 
Union. ``This is long overdue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Police Commissioner Howard Safir refused to comment on the  
federal probe, saying media reports of negotiations were 
speculative. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact is, we are cooperating with the Eastern District of  
New York in their investigation, and have been from the 
beginning,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Negotiators were believed to be focusing on a plan to create an  
independent panel that would review brutality complaints and 
oversee the department's response to them. The current Civilian 
Complaint Review Board, which is controlled by the mayor, is viewed 
by some as ineffective. 
</P>
<P>
	Carter began his investigation in 1997 after a Haitian  
immigrant, Abner Louima, was beaten in a police station bathroom 
following his arrest in a melee outside a Brooklyn nightclub. 
</P>
<P>
	Carter's office prosecuted the case, which resulted in the  
conviction last month of two officers on charges they tortured 
Louima by sodomizing him with a broken broomstick. 
</P>
<P>
	The mayor noted that the department has driven down crime at  
record rates while reducing the number of police shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYPD ``is the most restrained large-city police department  
in the country,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Police critics have repeatedly cited statistics showing that of  
the roughly 5,000 reports of police misconduct received by the CCRB 
last year, only 300 were found to be substantiated and forwarded to 
the police commissioner. Less than half of those cases resulted in 
disciplinary action. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990712.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 16:11:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Khrushchev's Son Becomes US Citizen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- Nikita Khrushchev's son became a U.S.  
citizen Monday, choosing the material advantages of captalism 40 
years after his father vowed communism would easily surpass the 
American way of life. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm feeling like a newborn. It's the beginning of a new  
life,'' the 64-year-old Sergei Khrushchev said after taking the 
oath of citizenship inside a Roman Catholic school auditorium. 
</P>
<P>
	At his side was his wife, Valentina Golenko, who also took the  
oath to defend the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	They became American citizens 40 years after Nikita Khrushchev  
told then-Vice President Richard Nixon on July 24, 1959 during the 
famous Kitchen Debate in Moscow: ``In another seven years we will 
be on the same level as America. When we catch you up, in passing 
you by, we will wave to you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another time, the Soviet leader said his country would ``bury''  
the United States. Khrushchev has said his father's ``we will bury 
you'' remark was misunderstood. The remark meant that capitalism 
would die and that the Soviet economic system would outlive it, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sergei Khrushchev, once an important missile engineer for the  
Soviets, and his wife have been living in the United States since 
he came to the United States in 1991 as a visiting instructor in 
Cold War history at Brown University in Providence, where he still 
teaches. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, Khrushchev has become American as a Buick or a  
Pontiac -- in fact, he owns one of each. Khrushchev lives in a ranch 
house in Cranston, a suburb dotted with lawn sprinklers and grills. 
The home has central air, a Jacuzzi and an entertainment center. 
</P>
<P>
	Khrushchev and his wife have grown accustomed to the American  
way of life, so they decided to make the arrangement a permanent 
one by becoming U.S. citizens. 
</P>
<P>
	Along with 242 others, Khrushchev and his wife stood up from  
their seats and said, ``I do'' when U.S. District Judge Ronald R. 
Lagueux asked if they promised to be good citizens. Then all 244 
recited the Pledge of Allegiance. Most of them, including 
Khrushchev, held miniature American flags. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if he feared that his relatives back in Russia could face  
hostility because of his decision, he replied: ``No, no! You're 
still living in the Cold War. It's a different Russia.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, there are some in Russia who see Khrushchev's decision to  
become an American as a betrayal. 
</P>
<P>
	His son Nikita, named after the Soviet leader, still lives in  
Russia and had been helping his dad gather material for books he 
writes about the Cold War era. The son said some Russian officials 
have been hindering him because of his father's move. 
</P>
<P>
	``This isn't the Cold War. But it's not normal peace, either,''  
the young Nikita wrote in a commentary published about two weeks 
ago in the liberal weekly Moscow News. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990712.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 16:11:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Khrushchev's Son Becomes US Citizen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
