<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Holland Considers Minnesota Job </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. (AP) -- Virginia athletic director Terry  
Holland has discussed the possibility of becoming Minnesota's next 
head basketball coach, according to published reports. 
</P>
<P>
	``Minnesota athletic director Mark Dienhart and I have talked on  
several occasions about his search process,'' Holland told the 
Daily Progress of Charlottesville. ``One of the many options we 
discussed was whether I was interested in a return to coaching. My 
answer was that it would take a lot more time to think through for 
both of us than I believe Mark has right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dienhart said Saturday that he hoped to hire a successor for  
Clem Haskins by Thursday, the start of the summer recruiting 
period. Another option is to hire an interim coach who likely would 
be replaced after next season. If Minnesota sticks to the Thursday 
deadline, Holland apparently would not be a factor. 
</P>
<P>
	The Star Tribune of Minneapolis reported Monday that three other  
coaches are being considered for the job: Gonzaga's Dan Monson, 
Wake Forest's Dave Odom and Northwestern's Kevin O'Neill. Dienhart 
confirmed that Monson and Odom are candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	University of Minnesota spokesman Marc Ryan, citing standard  
procedure, would neither confirm nor deny whether talks took place 
with any of the candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	Holland, Virginia's winningest coach before retiring in 1990,  
has been the Cavaliers' athletic director since 1995. As Virginia's 
coach from 1974-90, Holland led the Cavaliers to a 326-173 record 
that included two Final Four appearances, nine NCAA tournaments and 
Virginia's only ACC tournament championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Haskins coached the Gophers for 13 years before the school  
bought out his contract for $1.5 million this summer after the 
program was enmeshed in numerous charges of academic fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	Odom is in Portugal and is expected to let Dienhart know soon if  
he is interested, according to the Star Tribune. Monson and 
Dienhart have talked on the phone, and Dienhart wants the coach to 
visit, the newspaper said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
