<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 12:30:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Chinese Soccer Squad Returns Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Banging drums and singing the national anthem,  
Chinese fans gave a hero's welcome Monday to their women's soccer 
team that returned home from the World Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't lose because of spirit or strength. We lost because  
of luck,'' defender Zhao Lihong said as the team walked through 
Beijing airport to the applause of airport employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Top Chinese sports officials met the United Airlines flight  
bringing the team from San Francisco. In the receiving line was the 
top U.S. diplomat in China, William McCahill, who gave captain Sun 
Wen a bouquet of flowers. 
</P>
<P>
	``The entire Chinese people are extremely happy!'' Wu Shaozu,  
director of the state sports commission, said at a brief news 
conference for the team. 
</P>
<P>
	The arrival was featured prominently on the national evening  
television news. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States won the title at the Rose Bowl in Pasadena,  
Calif., beating the Chinese 5-4 on penalty kicks after a scoreless 
regulation and overtime. 
</P>
<P>
	The outcome was bitter for Chinese fans, many of whom regarded  
it as a grudge match with political overtones. Sun hinted at such 
sentiments but remained upbeat. 
</P>
<P>
	``Only when you are very powerful can you win respect,'' she  
said. ``Through our good performance we won the respect and love of 
American soccer fans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reporters jostled with fans and airport personnel to get  
pictures of the players. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 500 fans gathered outside the airport, some banging  
cymbals and drums, while others waved flags and sang the national 
anthem. One banner declared, ``The Chinese women's soccer team are 
national heroes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some Chinese fans had complained of a conspiracy by U.S.  
organizers, saying their team was sabotaged by too much travel, 
lack of decent Chinese food and hot weather. But others were proud 
the team had gone so far. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't feel that they lost,'' said Xin Yan, 32, who stood  
with 20 fellow employees of the Beijing Haidian Agricultural 
Research Institute. 
</P>
<P>
	Goalkeeper Gao Hong, beaten on the winning kick by Brandi  
Chastain, already was looking toward her next encounter with the 
U.S. team. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the Olympics next year, if we have this kind of  
competition, I won't let one ball in,'' she said. ``I have 
confidence in this,'' she said. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990712.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 12:30:18 </DATE_TIME>
