<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Architect Cited for Congress Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The architect of the Capitol failed to  
maintain the fire alarm system and electrical equipment in a main 
Library of Congress building, omissions that endangered lives when 
a fire broke out, congressional investigators said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress' workplace safety agency, the Office of Compliance,  
issued five ``serious'' citations against the architect after an 
April 30 fire caused evacuation of the Madison Building, parts of 
it in total darkness. Police officers who should have been aiding 
the evacuation instead had to run around the building pulling 
manual fire alarms, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	A worker was burned as the fire started, but there were no other  
injuries and no damage to the library's rare documents, which 
include a rough draft of the Declaration of Independence. 
</P>
<P>
	A ``serious'' citation is reserved for violations ``likely to  
cause serious injury or death.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Architect officials had a warning of problems two days before  
the fire, when officials in the Madison Building, a main research 
facility, had to cancel a planned fire drill because the alarm 
system failed to activate. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the citations said an important circuit breaker  
implicated in the fire had not been serviced since 1993, ``creating 
a danger of fire for employees ... and a danger of shock or 
electrocution for employees who work on the equipment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The architect's office didn't return a telephone call seeking  
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The investigators, charged with making Congress follow the same  
workplace safety rules that lawmakers have imposed on private 
businesses, previously have issued numerous citations against the 
architect for improper storage of chemicals and allowing an unsafe 
working environment, The Associated Press has reported. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the House inspector general said late last year  
that the Capitol and House offices were seriously deficient in fire 
safety and had installed a defective brand of sprinkler. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Green, general counsel for the Office of Compliance, said  
the architect's office ``does not share the same attitude that 
Fortune 500 companies share about safety.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The agency has only been obligated to follow federal safety  
rules since 1995, and trying to force compliance ``is a little bit 
like turning an ocean liner around,'' Green said. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to failing to maintain circuit breaker equipment,  
the citations said the architect: 
</P>
<P>
	--Left the alarm system in ``a mode for servicing,'' preventing  
activation of the full building alarm from the building's control 
console. It may have been left in that condition for several months 
and resulted in the canceled fire drill. 
</P>
<P>
	The system was reset the morning of the fire, but a faulty  
circuit prevented the alarm from sounding in the vicinity of the 
control room when the fire broke out. Because of that problem, 
officers were sent to activate manual alarms throughout the 
building to ensure no other areas were missed. 
</P>
<P>
	--Failed to cut power to electrical parts before employees tried  
to perform maintenance work that resulted in the fire. 
</P>
<P>
	The fire began when an electrician's tool came in contact with  
an energized conductor. Electrical distribution equipment failed, a 
nonfunctioning circuit breaker overheated and a flash fire began, 
burning and temporarily blinding the worker, who was saved by a 
colleague. 
</P>
<P>
	--Failed to train employees proper procedures for working on such  
equipment. The two electricians working in the Madison building on 
April 30 ``had received no training and were not familiar with the 
safety-related work practices required ... when performing work 
that poses a danger of electric shock,'' the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	--Did not install equipment that would have allowed a blocked  
duct to open automatically in case of fire. On April 30, the 
blocked duct prevented smoke from leaving the building, and it 
spread throughout the structure. 
</P>
<P>
	During the fire evacuation, when the faulty circuit breaker  
finally tripped, power was cut to one-fourth of the building. Some 
people were in darkness in rooms without windows. 
</P>
<P>
	Opened in 1980, the Madison building's collection includes rare  
musical instruments, one-of-a-kind maps and historic manuscripts. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990712.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 21:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Runs $6B Seafood Trade Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONOLULU (AP) -- At America's largest seafood restaurant chain,  
that red lobster probably comes from the Bahamas or Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	That shrimp cocktail? Thailand. Those crab legs? Canada.  
</P>
<P>
	Red Lobster Restaurants depends on foreign fishermen to feed its  
130 million annual customers. 
</P>
<P>
	That's because American fishermen can't meet the domestic demand  
for certain species and the strong dollar and lower wages elsewhere 
makes foreign fish less expensive. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's really become such a global market,'' said Andrew Dun,  
marketing director for the 669-outlet chain. ``There just isn't 
enough here to meet our needs. You have to go where the supply 
is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, more than ever, that supply was in foreign seas and  
foreign fish farms. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States imported nearly four times more seafood than  
it exported last year, running up a record $5.88 billion trade 
deficit, according to Seafood Market Analyst, a market research and 
forecasting group. 
</P>
<P>
	That is 16 percent -- or $800 million -- higher than 1997 and  
marks at least the 28th consecutive deficit in the seafood trade. 
</P>
<P>
	The fish shortage is so prevalent that restaurant customers  
ordering regional specialties -- lobster and cod in New England, 
crab cakes in Maryland, salmon in the Pacific Northwest and Alaska 
-- likely are served imports from Canada, Iceland, Venezuela and 
Chile, respectively. 
</P>
<P>
	``These days in mainstream restaurants, probably more than half  
of the fish on the menu is going to be imported,'' said James 
Anderson, editor of SMA's Seafood Trade Reports. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's definitely the biggest food category. We import more fish  
than we do coffee and alcohol put together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The United States imported more than $8 billion in seafood in  
1998, mostly from Canada, Thailand and China. That is 6 percent 
more than 1997 and the highest amount this decade. 
</P>
<P>
	Only Japan imports more seafood.  
</P>
<P>
	The top imports -- by value -- were shrimp and prawns at a  
combined $3.1 billion. Most of that came frozen from Mexico and 
Thailand. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, U.S. seafood exports dropped 17 percent last year to  
almost $2.2 billion, the lowest amount this decade. 
</P>
<P>
	The top individual exports were frozen Alaska pollock surimi, or  
minced pollock, at $167 million and lobster at $160 million. The 
top collective export was salmon products at about $360 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The primary destinations for U.S. fish were Japan, Canada and  
China, although exports to Japan were down 30 percent and to China 
down 39 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson said the trade gap is widening because Asia's economic  
slump makes U.S. fish more expensive, American fishermen aren't 
catching enough popular entrees like Alaska sockeye salmon and New 
England cod and flounder, and the American fleet can't produce the 
right products at the right time at the right price for American 
consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Year-round, high-quality, fresh, farmed salmon from places  
like Chile, Canada, Norway and Scotland out-competes the seasonal, 
mostly frozen, and often poorly handled salmon from Alaska,'' said 
Anderson, a visiting professor at the College of William and Mary. 
</P>
<P>
	The growing trade deficit is not bad in itself -- cheaper imports  
mean better prices for American consumers. But there are ripples 
beyond the dinner plate. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, the handling and production practices in foreign  
countries may not be up to U.S. standards. 
</P>
<P>
	``Seafood eaters should be aware that fisheries management  
practices in foreign countries may not be sustainable and that the 
U.S. demand, in some cases, is contributing to environmental 
degradation,'' Anderson said. 
</P>
<P>
	A few years ago, Red Lobster was accused of buying Honduran  
lobster from suppliers who abused divers and bleached coral reefs 
to force the crustaceans out of hiding. Red Lobster denied that. 
</P>
<P>
	Dun said recently that the chain has an office in Singapore  
making sure its seafood purchases are harvested responsibly. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our quality standards for our seafood apply globally,'' he  
said from the chain's Orlando, Fla., headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of the environmental and transportation problems often  
associated with foreign fish, many restaurants build their menus 
around locally farmed fish. 
</P>
<P>
	``As long as it's delicious, who cares?'' said Patrick  
O'Connell, chef at the upscale The Inn at Little Washington in 
Washington, Va. ``I'd rather have an impeccably fresh, farm-raised 
fish than a wild fish that's been sitting around an airport for 
three days.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990712.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 07:50:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> USDA Sees Lower Prices for Crops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Agriculture Department today predicted  
lower prices for wheat, corn and other major crops, bad news for an 
agricultural economy mired in its worst slump in over a decade. 
</P>
<P>
	USDA lowered its projected prices for wheat by 15 cents and by 5  
cents for corn and soybeans because crops are doing better than 
expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Such price declines usually have little effect on consumers, but  
the forecast is likely to intensify pressure on Congress to approve 
another bailout of the farm economy. Farm groups already are asking 
for at least $8 billion in aid. 
</P>
<P>
	``These prices are so low they're confiscatory,'' said Sen. Kent  
Conrad, D-N.D., who wants to put $9 billion in farm assistance in a 
USDA spending bill that's pending in the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican congressional leaders have said it's too early in the  
year to know how much federal aid farmers will need. 
</P>
<P>
	``Congress is going to have to act. ... I don't think they can  
wait any longer,'' said Tom Buis, a lobbyist for the National 
Farmers Union. ``The pressure is too great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While farmers will benefit from the good crops, the higher  
yields won't offset the low prices, said analyst Don Roose, 
president of U.S. Commodities Inc. Corn prices could drop another 
20 cents a bushel as the growing season progresses, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	USDA said today it expected farmers this year to harvest 1.7  
billion bushels of winter wheat, 4 percent more than was forecast a 
month ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers are getting a record 47 bushels per acre despite heavy  
rainfall last month that delayed the harvest in Kansas, the heart 
of winter wheat production. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat prices are now expected to average $2.45 to $2.95 a  
bushel. Two years ago, before a worldwide glut of grain drove 
prices down sharply, wheat was selling for an average of $3.38 a 
bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Good weather in the Midwest led USDA to raise its forecast of  
corn production to 9.7 billion bushels, up from 9.4 billion, last 
month's projection. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn prices are expected to average $1.95 a bushel this year,  
compared to $2.43 two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean prices are expected to be as low as $3.90 to $4.70 a  
bushel, the lowest level since the early 1970s and down from an 
average price of $6.47 in 1997. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
