<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Accor S.A. To Buy Red Roof Inns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- The owner of the Motel 6 chain moved to  
strengthen its hold of the low-end lodging business Monday with an 
offer to buy Red Roof Inns Inc. for $673 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Paris-based Accor S.A. plans to merge the two chains to create  
Accor Economy Lodging, a new subsidiary with about 120,000 rooms in 
more than 1,100 motels. 
</P>
<P>
	Combined, the two chains will make Accor the No. 2 player in the  
``limited services'' category of the hotel industry, said John 
Rohs, an analyst with Schroder &AMP; Co. Inc. in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Days Inn, based in Parsippany, N.J., is the industry leader with  
more than 1,800 motels and more than 160,000 rooms worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	A decision has not been made to base the new subsidiary in  
Dallas, home of Motel 6, or in the Columbus area, where Red Roof is 
based in suburban Hilliard, said Francis ``Butch'' Cash, Red Roof 
chairman, chief executive officer and president. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal will reward shareholders by providing financial  
assistance to pursue more aggressive expansion plans, said Cash, 
who said he would step down after the deal is completed. Accor is 
buying the company to boost growth more quickly, he said at a news 
conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Red Roof, which reported revenue of $375.3 million in 1998,  
operates 322 hotels with more than 37,000 rooms, mainly in the 
Midwest, East and South. Despite lower fourth-quarter earnings, the 
company posted a $38.1 million profit last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Accor said it plans to acquire all 29.6 million outstanding  
shares of Red Roof for $22.75 a share. In addition, it will assume 
about $500 million in debt. 
</P>
<P>
	The offer represents a premium of 27.5 percent over the stock's  
average price over the past 30 days. 
</P>
<P>
	The Morgan Stanley Real Estate Fund and other investors who  
together own 68.3 percent of Red Roof shares have agreed to the 
deal, the companies said. 
</P>
<P>
	In general, the two chains complement each other, Cash said. Red  
Roof charges roughly $50 a night and attracts an equal number of 
business and leisure travelers. Motel 6, which is generally in the 
under $40 category, gets about 65 percent of its business from 
leisure travelers. 
</P>
<P>
	And while Red Roof probably could have continued to operate as  
an independent entity, the takeover by Accor will allow the chain 
to grow more quickly, he added. 
</P>
<P>
	Accor also operates the Novotel and Sofitel hotel groups in the  
United States. It has 130,000 employees at hotels, travel agencies, 
car rental companies and corporate service organizations in 140 
nations. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement boosted Red Roof shares by $4.25, to $22.56 1/4,  
in trading on the New York Stock Exchange Monday. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
