<HEADLINE> Quebecor Printing Acquiring US Firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) -- Quebecor Printing Inc. plans to acquire  
World Color Press Inc., creating the world's largest commercial 
printer. 
</P>
<P>
	The $1.4 billion cash and stock deal, announced Monday, will  
create a company called Quebecor World Inc. that will serve 
customers in magazines, catalogs, books, retail inserts and 
circulars and direct mail printing. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agreement, a subsidiary of Quebecor Printing will  
acquire World Color Press through a tender offer to purchase World 
Color shares for $36.09 a share in cash or stock. 
</P>
<P>
	That represents a 30 percent premium over the average trading  
price of World Color shares since July 9. 
</P>
<P>
	Quebecor Printing said about $840 million of the purchase price  
would be for cash and the rest for stock. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Quebecor is assuming $1.3 billion in World Color  
debt. 
</P>
<P>
	The offer is subject to 50.1 percent of World Color shares being  
tendered to the offer and regulatory approvals. Both the tender 
offer and the merger are expected to be completed within four 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	Quebecor Printing, based in Montreal, is the largest printer in  
Europe and the second-largest printer in North America and South 
America, with 1998 revenues of $3.8 billion and 26,000 employees. 
</P>
<P>
	World Color, headquartered in Greenwich, is one of the leading  
commercial printers in the United States. The company has 16,000 
employees and had revenue of $2.5 billion in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of World Color rose $5.18 3/4 a share, or 17 percent, to $35  
on the New York Stock Exchange. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
