<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lott Predicts Holbrooke Will Be OKed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senate Majority leader Trent Lott says he  
expects his chamber will eventually confirm Richard Holbrooke as 
U.S. ambassador to the United Nations despite the roadblock that 
Lott and three other senators have placed on a vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott, R-Miss., said Sunday on NBC's ``Meet the Press'' that he  
didn't know when the vote on Holbrooke would occur, but ``I think 
he will'' be confirmed. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott's chief deputy, Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., agreed there  
will be a vote to confirm Holbrooke, a veteran diplomat whose 
nomination received the unanimous recommendation of the Senate 
Foreign Relations Committee two weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``My guess is we'll eventually get around to a vote, but  
certainly ... all senators have a right to discuss nominations at 
length if they want,'' Nickles said on ``Fox News Sunday.'' ``Some 
people have some problems with this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Senate procedures allow members to keep a nomination from the  
floor for unrelated reasons as a pressure tactic against the 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott and Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., have placed holds, without  
publicly acknowledging them, on the Holbrooke nomination to force 
President Clinton to nominate Bradley A. Smith, a university 
professor from Ohio, to the Federal Election Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	The other holds are by Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, who is  
trying to reverse a State Department disciplinary action against a 
former department employee at the U.N. mission; and Sen. George 
Voinovich, R-Ohio, who is protesting administration policy in the 
Balkans. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about Smith, who has said Clinton's administration is  
probably the most corrupt in American history, Lott seemed not to 
recall his name but said it ``sounds familiar.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Bradley Smith is your candidate ...,'' interviewer Tim Russert  
began. 
</P>
<P>
	``Oh. Brad Smith. Right,'' Lott said.  
</P>
<P>
	``Well, first of all, I think a little too much has been made of  
that,'' he said. ``I suspect the nomination of Holbrooke to go to 
the U.N. will be confirmed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lott said he couldn't say when, because others also had holds on  
the nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev., appearing with Nickles on Fox,  
expressed irritation with the holdup. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only thing I wanted to say is let's debate these issues in  
the light of the day, not in the back room in our cloakrooms,'' 
Reid said. ``We're the most powerful nation in the world, (and) we 
don't have a representative in the United Nations. That's not 
right.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
