<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kasich Might Be Getting Out of Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- Rep. John Kasich's latest campaign swing  
through New Hampshire could be his last, with rumblings that he may 
be ready to abandon his quest for the Republican presidential 
nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Responding to rumors that he planned to endorse another  
candidate this week, the Ohio congressman did not deny the 
possibility Sunday as he campaigned in the state for the 10th time 
since February. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked whether a decision had been made, Kasich only reiterated  
that when he wanted to talk about it, he would. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we get to the point where we've made a decision and are  
going to talk about it, we'll let you know,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	His spokesman, Todd Harris, stressed that unlike some other  
Republican hopefuls who are certain they will run, Kasich has an 
exploratory committee and he is doing just that -- exploring his 
chances. He said he didn't know how much more exploring Kasich had 
to do before announcing a decision. 
</P>
<P>
	If Kasich were to give up his shot at the nomination, he would  
be the first dropout among 12 Republicans. He has lagged far behind 
the clear GOP front-runner, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, with about 3 
percent support in a recent poll. 
</P>
<P>
	Most analysts believe that field will be reduced significantly  
following next month's straw poll in Iowa, if not before. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican analyst Tom Rath of Concord said that at a recent  
Republican National Committee meeting in Philadelphia, he heard 
that Kasich and other cash-strapped candidates may be close to 
dropping out. But he said he did not know of any final decisions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Money and political reality are going to force a lot of these  
people to take a look at where they are,'' Rath said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich met with a dozen residents at a historic carriage house  
in Concord on Sunday and portrayed himself as a down-to-earth guy, 
telling stories of speaking with voters who didn't realize they 
were talking to a candidate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
