<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Schilling To Start All-Star Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Curt Schilling's latest triumph was yet  
another tough loss for Randy Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling was officially announced today as the starter for the  
National League in Tuesday's All-Star game, with NL manager Bruce 
Bochy choosing the Philadelphia ace over Arizona's Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Randy's numbers are not indicative of how he's  
thrown,'' Bochy said today, referring to Johnson's 9-7 record. 
``Curt has had a tremendous year. Their ERAs are close. I feel that 
with Curt, with the extra day's rest he was gettting, I could count 
on two innings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling has 13 victories, one fewer than Kent Bottenfield of  
St. Louis. He is tied with Johnson for the major league lead with 
seven complete games and is second in the NL to Johnson in 
strikeouts. On Sunday, Schilling declined to confirm he was Bochy's 
choice -- although he was seen accepting congratulations in the 
clubhouse after the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know who's starting,'' said Schilling, named to his third  
straight All-Star team, on Sunday. ``I've got a pretty good idea 
who will have the ball when the game starts. The manager is going 
to announce it tomorrow, and we'll all have fun talking about it 
tomorrow. It's not my job to announce it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just more than a week ago, Bochy was leaning toward starting  
Johnson on Tuesday at Fenway Park. But the Arizona left-hander has 
been victimized by his own offense. Arizona hasn't scored a run in 
the last 34 innings Johnson has been on the mound. Johnson is 0-4 
in his last four starts despite allowing a total of five earned 
runs and striking out 54. 
</P>
<P>
	Boston's Pedro Martinez will start for the American League.  
</P>
<P>
	Schilling was selected to the All-Star team in 1997 and '98 and  
pitched two scoreless innings two years ago at Jacobs Field in 
Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	He started his career in the Red Sox organization, but was  
traded to Baltimore with Brady Anderson for Mike Boddicker in 1988. 
He was dealt to Houston with Pete Harnisch and Steve Finley for 
Glenn Davis in 1991, and then traded to Philadelphia for Jason 
Grimsley in 1992. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
