<DOCNO> APW19990712.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 07:00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Charlotte Sting Fire Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- The Charlotte Sting, expected to vie for  
the WNBA Eastern Conference title but off to a mediocre start, 
fired head coach and general manager Marynell Meadors on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Meadors was fired the day after the Sting's record fell to 5-7  
with an 82-56 loss to Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant coach Dan Hughes was named interim coach. Charlotte  
Hornets general manager Bob Bass will assume managerial 
responsibilities for the Sting. 
</P>
<P>
	``With two-thirds of our schedule left, we feel like there is  
still enough time for use to make a run at the championship,'' said 
Sting executive vice president Sam Russo. ``But given our record 
and our inconsistency over the last calendar year, we needed to 
make a change at the top to get us back on track.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the presence of several marquee players -- including  
Olympic gold medalist Dawn Staley, WNBA rookie of the year Tracy 
Reid and Stephanie White-McCarty, who led Purdue to the 1999 NCAA 
title over Duke -- the Sting is mired in third place in the Eastern 
Conference. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all believed at the beginning of the season that we had a  
team with enough talent to win the Eastern Conference championship 
and make a run for the WNBA title,'' Hughes said. ``We still 
believe that. This team can play a lot better than it has of late, 
and we need to prove that to the rest of the league, as well as to 
ourselves, beginning tomorrow night against Washington.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
