<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Canal Break Causes Utah Flooding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIVERDALE, Utah (AP) -- The earthen wall of a century-old  
irrigation canal ruptured on a hillside, flooding about 80 homes 
and spreading mud that buried mailboxes and oozed into basements. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 300 residents were evacuated yesterday after the  
canal gave way on the slope above their homes. No serious injuries 
were reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Crews worked into the night to dig out streets.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's pretty significant mud and water damage,'' said police  
Lt. Paige Ansley. ``It was up 3 and 4 feet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The cause of the collapse has not been determined. The area had  
not gotten any heavy rain. 
</P>
<P>
	An inspector examined that section of the canal 10 minutes  
before the rupture, canal manager Floyd Baham said Monday. He said 
the canal is inspected daily during irrigation season. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no immediate estimate of the cost of the damage. Most  
of the affected homes are new and were worth $200,000 to $400,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The canal, built 115 years ago, carries water to 30,000 acres of  
crops. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
