<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jockey Romero To End Career Tonight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARENCRO, La. (AP) -- Randy Romero's last day as a jockey was  
spent preparing to ride a 10-1 longshot at the southern Louisiana 
track where he won his first race in 1973, Evangeline Downs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to give something back to the people of Acadiana and  
Evangeline Downs,'' Romero said prior to Monday night's race. ``I 
think they deserve it. I just want it to be something a little 
special.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Romero, almost as well-known for an injury-marred career as for  
his 4,294 wins and more than $74 million in purses, is beginning a 
new career as a jockey agent. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven friends who also started their riding careers at  
Evangeline came back to Louisiana to compete against him in the 
$30,000 Cradle of Jockeys Invitational. Affirmed Success was to be 
his final mount at Evangeline Downs. 
</P>
<P>
	Other riders include Corey Lanerie, Shane Sellers. Marlon St.  
Julien, the rider Romero will represent as an agent, is also in the 
race, along with Mark Guidry, Ronald Ardoin, E.J. Perrodin and Ray 
Sibille. 
</P>
<P>
	The 41-year-old Romero won three Breeders' Cup races and set  
records at three separate tracks for most victories by a jockey in 
a single meet. Romero has also been the leading rider at 10 
different tracks. 
</P>
<P>
	But Romero has been one of racing's most frequently injured  
riders, suffering through countless spills, 23 operations, plus a 
series of skin grafts after a light bulb exploded in the jockey's 
``hot box'' at Oaklawn Park, setting the rubbing alcohol on his 
body on fire, nearly burning him to death. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, in 1990, Go for Wand broke down, throwing Romero during  
the Breeders' Cup Distaff at Belmont Park. He broke eight ribs and 
his right shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	Other injuries followed before a brief retirement. After that,  
Romero passed the 4,000-win mark, one of only 27 riders to achieve 
that record. He stands 26th on the all-time win list. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
