<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arson-Murder Link Stuns Community </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAPPY VALLEY, Calif. (AP) -- In this tiny, largely conservative  
farming community, Gary Matson and Winfield Mowder were accepted. 
It didn't matter that they were gay. 
</P>
<P>
	They gained respect through their community work. They helped  
create a local children's museum, and Matson helped establish the 
20-year-old Redding Farmer's Market. 
</P>
<P>
	Now two brothers who have been linked to a series of arson fires  
at Sacramento synagogues are suspected of killing the couple, 
police said. Authorities said one of the alleged gunmen, Benjamin 
Matthew Williams, sometimes sold vegetables and herbs at Matson's 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's beyond words that the farmers market may be the  
connection between the victims and the killers,'' said Margaret 
Jensen, who tends a market stall stocked with squash and onions. 
``If they burned the synagogues, too, that takes it to a level that 
is just staggering from someplace we think of as a small 
community.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neither Williams, 31, nor his brother, 29-year-old James Tyler  
Williams, has been charged in connection with the murders or the 
fires. Authorities said they hope to bring murder charges later 
this week, said Shasta County Sheriff's Capt. Ron Richardson. 
</P>
<P>
	The bodies of Matson, 50, and Mowder, 40, were discovered July 1  
at their home in Happy Valley, a small community just outside of 
Redding in northern California. They had been shot in their bed. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, after one of the victims' credit cards was used,  
police staked out a Yuba City business where the credit card 
purchase was to be delivered, and arrested the Williams brothers. 
</P>
<P>
	The brothers were both armed and one was wearing a bulletproof  
vest, police said. Yuba City is about 120 miles southeast of 
Redding. 
</P>
<P>
	Two days later, federal and local authorities said the brothers  
also were being investigated in connection with the Sacramento 
synagogue fires on June 18 that caused $1 million in damage. 
</P>
<P>
	The brothers were being held in lieu of $150,000 bail on charges  
of receiving stolen property after authorities said they found a 
wallet, credit card, driver's license and Social Security card 
belonging to Matson. 
</P>
<P>
	The Williams brothers lived in a modest, wood-frame house in  
Redding, where investigators said they found material espousing 
white supremacist beliefs. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the material found was literature from the Illinois-based  
World Church of the Creator, according to news reports. A former 
member of the church, Benjamin Smith, killed himself last week 
after a two-state shooting spree targeting minorities in Indiana 
and Illinois that killed two men and wounded nine others. 
</P>
<P>
	Also found in the house was a list of 32 prominent Jewish and  
civic leaders in Sacramento, and FBI special agent James Maddock 
said protection was ordered for those individuals. Officials also 
urged Redding's only Jewish congregation, Temple Beth Israel, to 
increase security. 
</P>
<P>
	Sacramento authorities over the weekend also began visiting  
people believed to be members or followers of white supremacy 
groups, ``just to see if we can develop a sense of what we can 
expect from them in the future,'' sheriff's Lt. John McGinness told 
the Sacramento Bee in today's editions. 
</P>
<P>
	Matson, a lifelong resident of the area, helped establish an  
arboretum as well as the museum and farmers market. Mowder, his 
companion of 16 years, worked in the plant department in the local 
hardware store. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent months, the Williams brothers had been involved in a  
landscaping business. 
</P>
<P>
	Matthew Williams knew Matson through a shared interest in  
horticulture, according to Ed Smith, owner of a Redding nursery 
where Williams worked briefly. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were acquaintances. They both sold at the farmers market.  
I don't know if they were friends, but I know that they knew each 
other,'' Smith said. 
</P>
<P>
	Carol Freitas, a retired teacher who taught 30 years at the  
elementary school, said: ``It's such a tragedy. Gary was a very 
nice fellow. Very much a community-minded person.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
