<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Extra Events Spice Up All-Star Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- One more day and then the real show begins.  
</P>
<P>
	First, though, the final prelude to the All-Star game takes  
place tonight when baseball's sluggers aim at the Green Monster, 
the 37-foot high left-field wall at Fenway Park, in the Home Run 
Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	Can Nomar Garciaparra, who missed the Red Sox's last nine games  
with a groin injury, excite the Boston fans by winning the 
long-ball contest? How about Mark McGwire or Sammy Sosa, the 
record-breakers of 1998? 
</P>
<P>
	And what will happen Tuesday night when the final All-Star game  
of the 1900s is played at 87-year-old Fenway Park? The high 
left-field wall may not be able to contain McGwire's towering 
blasts. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, he'll have to face Pedro Martinez, who has allowed  
just five homers in 132 2-3 innings. Martinez earned the start for 
the American League in his home park with a 15-3 record and 2.10 
ERA in 18 starts. 
</P>
<P>
	Curt Schilling (13-4), who began his career in Boston's farm  
system, was expected to start for the National League. 
</P>
<P>
	Three former Red Sox stars won't be there. New York's Roger  
Clemens and Anaheim's Mo Vaughn weren't selected, and Tampa Bay's 
Jose Canseco withdrew Sunday when he underwent back surgery for a 
herniated disc. He was replaced on the AL roster by Baltimore 
designated hitter Harold Baines. 
</P>
<P>
	Boston's primary free agent pickup in the offseason, second  
baseman Jose Offerman, will be there as a reserve despite a 
2-for-38 slump that has dropped his batting average to .273. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, two other locals stars took their cuts in the  
Celebrity Hitting Challenge -- actor Matt Damon of Cambridge, Mass., 
and quarterback Doug Flutie of Boston College and the Buffalo 
Bills. 
</P>
<P>
	The All-Star sidelights began Friday with FanFest, a display of  
baseball exhibits and activities, and continued Sunday with the 
celebrity competition and an All-Star Futures game featuring 
minor-league prospects. 
</P>
<P>
	All that was a substantial change from 1946 and 1961, the other  
times the All-Star game was held at Fenway. That's all there was 
then -- a game. 
</P>
<P>
	``Much of what has been added has been to the fans' benefit,''  
former Oakland general manager Sandy Alderson, now an executive in 
the commissioner's office, said Sunday. ``The Futures game is 
really a way of illustrating the international aspect of the game 
that already exists.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The World team beat the United States team 7-0 as Yankees  
infield prospect Alfonso Soriano had two homers and five RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
	He did a lot better than Damon did in the celebrity competition  
in which four teams of three players each -- a celebrity, a former 
All-Star and a former Red Sox star -- earned points depending on how 
far they hit the ball on their seven swings. 
</P>
<P>
	Damon missed the ball once, hit four fouls and put just two  
balls in play. 
</P>
<P>
	But he and fellow actor Kevin Costner still pleased the crowd.  
</P>
<P>
	``I came out to see Kevin Costner because I think he's cute and  
I wanted to see if he could play baseball,'' said Casey Levesque, 
6, of Fall River. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday's events also gave pitcher Kip Wells a chance to be part  
of the extravaganza. Wells, the Chicago White Sox' first-round 
draft pick last year, was on the United States Futures team. 
</P>
<P>
	``It gives prospects a chance to compare their talents against  
others at that point in their game,'' Wells said. ``For me, it was 
a thrill just being in the dressing room with those guys whose 
movies I have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Flutie, a star in college, the Canadian Football League, and the  
NFL, still got a kick out of trying to hit the Green Monster. He 
succeeded twice -- once on a bounce and once on a liner. 
</P>
<P>
	``We get a chance to come to Fenway for an All-Star game to rub  
shoulders with the current players and go out and be kids again for 
a day,'' he said. ``And it's just a blast.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The current players for the NL include manager Bruce Bochy's  
likely batting order of Cincinnati's Barry Larkin, Colorado's Larry 
Walker, Chicago's Sosa, St. Louis' McGwire, Arizona's Matt 
Williams, Houston's Jeff Bagwell as designated hitter, Mike Piazza 
of the New York Mets, Milwaukee's Jeromy Burnitz and Arizona's Jay 
Bell. 
</P>
<P>
	The AL lineup wasn't announced Sunday.  
</P>
<P>
	That day was reserved for activities attended by fans who might  
not be able to go to the actual game since Fenway is the smallest 
major-league park with 33,871 seats. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think that takes the spotlight off the game,'' Damon  
said before taking his cuts. ``This is just some kind of warmup 
stuff, revenue for the city, an excuse to come out to the ballpark 
on a sunny day for a lot of people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1946, the first time the All-Star game was in Fenway Park,  
Ted Williams went 4-for-4 in the AL's 12-0 win. Today, at age 80, 
even he likes the expanded format. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they don't try and squeeze too much in too few days, I  
think it's all a celebration,'' Williams said. ``It's all fun for 
baseball fans.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
