<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Japan Economy on Upswing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's economy is improving somewhat with private  
consumption recovering and government support measures sinking in, 
the Economic Planning Agency said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In its closely watched monthly report, the EPA upgraded its  
overall assessment of the economy, saying that although recovery 
remains fragile, the situation is improving somewhat. 
</P>
<P>
	``The recovery in consumption is weak, and some severe  
conditions remain, but the effects of various government policies 
are sinking in and at present the situation is improving 
somewhat,'' the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	The EPA's monthly report is considered a key indicator of  
government thinking on the state of the economy. This month's 
report is the first since the EPA announced in June that Japan's 
gross domestic product grew by an annualized 7.9 percent for the 
January-March quarter, and by 1.9 percent from the October-December 
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The overall upgrade was the second in as many months. In its  
June report, the EPA also revised its assessment to say that the 
economy ``has stopped deteriorating and is fluctuating sideways.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Briefing reporters about the July report, Takashi Omori,  
director of the national economic division at the EPA's research 
bureau, was still guarded in his assessment. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are good points and bad points, but on balance, it adds  
up to an improvement,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Private consumption is slowly recovering despite stagnant  
incomes that weigh on its strength, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	The report echoes comments made by Japan's finance minister in a  
speech to Parliament on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa said the picture remained grim,  
but government efforts to spur growth are leading to signs of a 
recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Japanese economy, as seen in the weak levels of personal  
consumption and capital expenditures and in the high unemployment 
rate, is still in a severe situation,'' he said, adding that ``some 
bright signs are beginning to be seen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, the EPA reported that overall household spending in  
May rose 2.4 percent on year. This was despite the fact that 
incomes fell 1.1 percent on year in real terms. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month's EPA monthly report said that private spending  
continued to be pressured by wage concerns as corporations 
restructure, but was showing signs of slight recovery from spring 
lows. 
</P>
<P>
	Domestic prices are showing signs of bottoming out, the agency  
said in the July report, contrasting with a previous assessment 
that they were fluctuating at low levels. 
</P>
<P>
	Corporate profits have begun to show signs of turning around,  
the July report said, after being assessed as generally in a 
downward trend last month. 
</P>
<P>
	The July report noted that housing construction also continues  
to rally. Construction starts for single family homes in Japan 
soared 17.9 percent on year in May after rising 12.5 percent in 
April, 19.1 percent in March and 9 percent in February. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts have said that these rises reflect tax incentives and  
the popularity of low-interest government housing loans more than 
any improvement in consumer sentiment. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
