<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 14:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Venator's Moves To Boost Profits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Venator Group, the former Woolworth, has spent much of the 1990s  
restructuring in an attempt to boost profits. Some highlights: 

</P>
<P>
	Jan. 8, 1992 -- Woolworth says it will close, sell or overhaul  
900 stores, including 25 percent of its Kinney shoe stores. Store 
divisions to be shut down include Susie's, Sportelle, Richman 
Brothers and Anderson- Little. 

</P>
<P>
	Oct. 13, 1993 -- Woolworth says it will close or reformat nearly  
1,000 stores and cut 13,000 jobs. 

</P>
<P>
	Jan. 14, 1994 -- Woolworth says it will sell 120 Woolco stores in  
Canada to Wal-Mart Stores Inc. 

</P>
<P>
	March 30, 1994 -- Woolworth reveals accounting irregularities  
will force it to restate earnings for the 1992 and 1993 fiscal 
years. Chairman William Lavin and chief financial officer Charles 
Young step aside temporarily. Lavin is reinstated as CEO and Young 
resigns in May, but Lavin quits later in the year in a dispute with 
the Woolworth board. 

</P>
<P>
	Dec. 12, 1994 -- Roger Farah, former chief merchandising officer  
at Federated Department Stores Inc., is named Woolworth's chairman. 

</P>
<P>
	April 3, 1995 -- Payless Shoe Source head Dale Hilpert is named  
president and chief operating officer. 

</P>
<P>
	May 31, 1995 -- Woolworth sells its Kids Mart subsidiary to  
management-led investors. The chain later closes nearly 100 stores 
and files for bankruptcy court protection. 

</P>
<P>
	April 1, 1996 -- Woolworth, which earlier sold off 24 Rx Place  
Drug Mart stores, says it will close the chain's remaining 14 
outlets. 

</P>
<P>
	May 21, 1996 -- Woolworth says it will eliminate its 109  
Accessory Lady stores, converting them to other formats or closing 
them. 

</P>
<P>
	Feb. 12, 1997 -- Woolworth says it will remodel or relocate 500  
stores. 

</P>
<P>
	July 17, 1997 -- Woolworth says it will close 400 F.W. Woolworth  
stores and lay off 9,200 workers. 

</P>
<P>
	June 12, 1998 -- Woolworth begins operating as Venator Group Inc.  

</P>
<P>
	Sept. 16, 1998 -- Venator says it will close down its 570 Kinney  
and Footquarters stores. 

</P>
<P>
	Sept. 22, 1998 -- Venator announces the sale of its 357 general  
merchandise stores in Germany for approximately $550 million. 

</P>
<P>
	July 1, 1999 -- The Equal Employment Opportunity Commission files  
an age discrimination lawsuit against Venator, alleging that 
Woolworth stores fired dozens of employees between September 1995 
and October 1997 because they were over 40. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
