<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Soccer Squad Returns Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Banging drums and singing the national anthem,  
Chinese fans gave a hero's welcome Monday to a women's soccer team 
that returned defiant from a World Cup defeat by the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't lose because of spirit or strength. We lost because  
of luck,'' defender Zhao Lihong said as the team walked through 
Beijing airport to applause. 
</P>
<P>
	Reporters jostled with fans and airport personnel to get  
pictures of China's new national heroines. 
</P>
<P>
	Top Chinese sports officials met the United Airlines flight  
bringing the team from San Francisco. In the receiving line was the 
top U.S. diplomat in China, William McCahill, who gave team captain 
Sun Wen a bouquet of flowers. 
</P>
<P>
	``The entire Chinese people are extremely happy!'' enthused Wu  
Shaozu, director of the state sports commission, at a brief news 
conference. 
</P>
<P>
	The arrival was featured prominently on the national evening  
television news. 
</P>
<P>
	The team's 5-4 loss on penalty kicks after a scoreless game at  
the Rose Bowl in Pasadena, Calif., was a bitter defeat for Chinese 
fans, many of whom regarded it as a grudge match with political 
overtones. 
</P>
<P>
	Sun, the team captain, hinted at such sentiments, but was upbeat  
about the outcome. 
</P>
<P>
	``Only when you are very powerful can you win respect,'' she  
said. ``Through our good performance, we won the respect and love 
of American soccer fans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	More than 500 fans gathered outside the airport, some banging  
cymbals and drums, while others waved flags and sang the national 
anthem. One banner declared, ``The Chinese women's soccer team are 
national heroes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some Chinese fans had complained of a conspiracy by U.S.  
organizers, saying their team was sabotaged by too much travel, 
lack of decent Chinese food and hot weather. But others were proud 
that the team had gone so far. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't feel that they lost,'' said Xin Yan, 32, who stood  
with 20 fellow employees of the Beijing Haidian Agricultural 
Research Institute. 
</P>
<P>
	Goalkeeper Gao Hong, who missed the winning shot by American  
Brandi Chastain, already was looking ahead to her next encounter 
with the U.S. team. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the Olympics next year, if we have this kind of  
competition, I won't let one ball in. I have confidence in this,'' 
she said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
