<DOCNO> APW19990712.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 17:10:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Congressional Leaders Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton and congressional leaders  
discussed tax cuts, Social Security and other budget issues Monday 
at a White House meeting that both sides described as amicable but 
that produced no evidence they had bridged any of their 
differences. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think there are some areas we can work together on to try to  
find some compromises,'' House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., said 
after the hour-long session in the Cabinet Room. 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides said Clinton stressed his willingness to work on  
Medicare overhaul this year. And they each cast the tone of the 
meeting positively, which considering the distrust many Republicans 
feel for Clinton might be a major achievement in itself. 
</P>
<P>
	But when it came to specifics over spending the $2.9 trillion in  
budget surpluses projected over the next decade, Republicans were 
still insisting on their plans for using budget surpluses to cut 
taxes by about $800 billion over the next decade. 
</P>
<P>
	And Clinton and Democrats were saying a smaller reduction might  
be in order, but only after the two sides agree to revamp Social 
Security and Medicare for the looming retirement of the baby boom 
generation. That was the point Clinton made to Republicans to open 
the meeting, said one Democrat who spoke on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the priority has to be Social Security and Medicare,''  
said House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview, Hastert said Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,  
R-Miss., used an analogy of a dog carrying too many bones to argue 
that the president and Congress consider tax cuts, spending, 
Medicare and other issues separately. 
</P>
<P>
	But Clinton responded that budget items must be linked because  
they all affect the surplus' bottom line, Hastert said. White House 
officials have argued that GOP tax-cutting plans would devour money 
needed for Medicare and Social Security revamping and for needed 
defense and domestic spending. 
</P>
<P>
	No one expected the two sides to make substantive progress over  
their differences, because Monday's meeting came months before the 
Oct. 1 start of the new fiscal year, which is when the pressure 
will be on to enact legislation. Congress has not put any of this 
year's tax and spending bills into their final form, let alone send 
any to Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, the White House sent out the president's top economic  
advisers to criticize an $864 billion House GOP proposal that would 
cut income taxes by 10 percent over the next decade, and a $792 
billion Senate Republican alternative aimed at the middle class. 
</P>
<P>
	Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said America's prosperity  
would be ``put at risk by the dangerous reversal of course that 
would be represented by huge tax cuts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP proposals would swell the national debt, erode expected  
budget surpluses and fail to provide money to meet existing 
obligations, he said. ``The tax cuts are potentially explosive, out 
beyond the 10-year window, and involve very great risks if the 
(surplus) projections that we have made do not materialize.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gene Sperling, head of the president's National Economic  
Council, said the tax cuts would absorb money needed to ensure the 
long-term solvency of Medicare, the health insurance program for 
the elderly and disabled. 
</P>
<P>
	Sperling said prominent Republicans had agreed to make fixing  
Medicare a priority. ``That's why it's puzzling, disturbing and 
disappointing that the Republicans now put forward a tax cut plan 
that leaves zero -- zero -- for Medicare over a 10-year period,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton and the Republicans both say they would use $1.9  
trillion of the expected $2.9 trillion in surpluses to reduce the 
national debt and strengthen Social Security. Republicans want to 
devote most of the remaining $1 trillion to tax cuts, while Clinton 
wants to spend it on Medicare, a prescription drug benefit, 
reducing the debt, creating federally subsidized retirement 
accounts and increasing spending for military and domestic 
programs. 
</P>
<P>
	On Capitol Hill, Lott said his message to Clinton was: ``Let's  
cooperate here and not let this year be wasted as a partisan 
fight.'' He invited Clinton to work with Republicans on their tax 
cut plans. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got to engage,'' Lott said. ``He can't just stand there  
and throw rocks at it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans also took note of a Washington Post story saying  
House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., has focused his 
attention on trying to put Democrats back in control of the House 
and has shown little inclination to compromise with Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a result, the Democrat leadership has adopted a do-nothing  
partisan agenda that is designed to produce gridlock rather than 
legislative solutions to the problems facing the country,'' House 
Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
