<DOCNO> APW19990712.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 12:10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NAACP Criticizes Gun Industry, TV  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The NAACP, calling the upcoming fall television  
lineup ``a virtual whitewash in programming,'' is pushing the four 
major television networks and advertisers to put more minorities on 
their shows. NAACP President Kweisi Mfume said the group is 
considering a lawsuit against the networks charging they violate 
the Communication Act of 1934, which mandates the airwaves belong 
to the public. The 26 new shows slated for the upcoming fall season 
have no minorities in starring or leading roles, Mfume said. The 
NAACP also said it will sue the gun industry, seeking an injunction 
to restrict the marketing of firearms. 

</P>
<P>
	Gore Outlines Anti-Crime Agenda  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore, the front-runner for the  
Democratic presidential nomination, promised today he would be a 
president who's tough on crime. Gore unveiled an anti-crime agenda 
that includes photo licenses for all new handgun owners, a ban on 
cheap handguns and a constitutional amendment for victims' rights. 
His plan also includes more federal money for the nation's court 
system and a requirement that criminal defendants pledge to get off 
drugs if they want to stay out of jail. 

</P>
<P>
	Navy Says Puerto Rican Base Needed  
</P>
<P>
	ABOARD THE USS JOHN F. KENNEDY (AP) -- Puerto Rico's government  
is demanding the Navy abandon the outlying island of Vieques, used 
for training for every military operation since Vietnam, including 
Operation Desert Fox in Iraq and this year's Kosovo campaign. But 
the Navy argues that Vieques is the only Atlantic range where it 
can conduct full-blown land, sea and air games, with real 
munitions, under conditions that are closest to the real thing. 
Without the island, Navy officials worry that battle groups won't 
be fully combat-ready. 

</P>
<P>
	Refugees in U.S. Get Free Flights  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- All refugees from Kosovo who found sanctuary  
in the United States will be offered flights home on commercial and 
charter flights, Clinton administration officials said today. The 
U.S. government will foot the bill. Some 9,700 refugees were flown 
to the United States last spring. Most of the refugees are expected 
to take the United States up on the offer. 

</P>
<P>
	Two Arrested in U.S. Embassy Bombings  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Fingerprint evidence links two Egyptians to a  
conspiracy with Osama bin Laden to kill Americans in the bombings 
of U.S. embassies in Africa, a prosecutor said today as two men 
made their first court appearance. Ibrahim Hussein Abdel Hadi 
Eidarous, 42, and Adel Mohanned Abdul Almagid Bary, 39, were 
arrested yesterday. Bin Laden is accused by the United States of 
masterminding the nearly simultaneous blasts in Nairobi, Kenya, and 
Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, on Aug. 7, 1998, that killed 224 people. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia's Computers Not Y2K-Ready  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Only one-third of Russia's vital computer systems  
are ready for the millennium, and the government probably won't 
have the money to fix the rest in time, officials said today. 
Finance Ministry officials said Russia needs at least $187 million 
to prepare its computers for the year 2000, the ITAR-Tass news 
agency reported. Russian government agencies have 28,000 vital 
computer systems, one-third of which are ready for the Year 2000 
changeover, an official said. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 15  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
up 15.20 to 11,178.50. Declining issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led advancers 1,586-1,332. The Nasdaq was up 5.59 to 
2,798.66. 

</P>
<P>
	Schnellenberger To Coach New Team  
</P>
<P>
	BOCA RATON, Fla. (AP) -- Howard Schnellenberger, who built the  
Miami Hurricanes' football program into a national powerhouse in 
the early 1980s, was appointed coach of Florida Atlantic's new 
program today. The Owls are scheduled to play their first game on 
September 8, 2001, against Cornell. Schnellenberger led the 
Hurricanes to the first of their four national championships in 
1983. He later coached at Louisville and Oklahoma. 

</P>
<P>
	Chinese Soccer Squad Returns Home  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Chinese fans gave a hero's welcome today to a  
women's soccer team that returned defiant from a World Cup defeat 
by the United States. More than 500 fans gathered outside the 
airport, some banging cymbals and drums, while others waved flags 
and sang the national anthem. The team's 5-4 loss on penalty kicks 
after a scoreless game at the Rose Bowl in Pasadena, Calif., was a 
bitter defeat for Chinese fans, many of whom regarded it as a 
grudge match with political overtones. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
