<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Dole Outlines Top Priorities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINTERSET, Iowa (AP) -- Elizabeth Dole said Monday that tax cuts  
must be a top priority for presidential hopefuls, but she also 
called for more government spending in several areas, including 
defense and crime fighting. 
</P>
<P>
	During campaign stops across central Iowa, Mrs. Dole repeatedly  
said she thinks it's wrong that 40 percent of the average American 
family's income goes to pay taxes. Mrs. Dole did not offer many 
specifics, but pledged to cut Americans' taxes if elected 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she wants to eliminate the so-called marriage penalty  
tax structure that causes some married couples to pay more in taxes 
than people who are single. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's very important that we give tax relief so our  
families can keep more of their hard-earned dollars,'' Mrs. Dole 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But she also outlined several ideas that would require more  
government spending, including a call for a missile defense system 
to guard against possible attacks from countries developing missile 
technology. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very concerned that the Clinton-Gore administration has  
reduced the Pentagon to a triangle, and we've got to build it 
back,'' Mrs. Dole said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole also took aim at Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who has  
raised more money than any other GOP hopeful and leads most polls. 
</P>
<P>
	At each stop Monday, Mrs. Dole asked those in the crowd to  
support her at a GOP straw poll Aug. 14 in Ames. While the poll 
will not determine any electoral votes, Iowa Republicans will cast 
unofficial ballots and many view the event as an early test of 
candidates' strength. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole asked people to support her at the straw poll if they  
``feel this election should be about the person who has the most 
experience rather than the one who has raised the most money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I do think when we're talking about the president of the  
United States, experience is important,'' she said, citing her work 
in two Cabinet positions and as president of the American Red 
Cross. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
