<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 07:33:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Armstrong Takes Tour de France Lead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	METZ, France (AP) -- Soon, the plane would be taking off for  
Geneva on the way to the French Alps, where the Tour de France gets 
a whole lot more grueling. First, it was time for champagne. 
</P>
<P>
	Lance Armstrong won Sunday's crucial time trial a few hours  
earlier, recapturing the yellow jersey and staking his claim as a 
clear favorite to win cycling's biggest race. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Postal Service team had a champagne toast to celebrate  
their star rider's success. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's one thing to expect it. It's another thing to see it  
happen,'' Mark Gorski, the team's general manager, said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 27-year-old rider from Texas is earning a lot of new  
admirers these days, far from home. Many see his comeback from 
testicular cancer to the very top of cycling as inspiring, not to 
mention amazing. 
</P>
<P>
	``His comeback is great!'' said 19-year-old Christian Kohl of  
Germany, waiting for an autograph before the race. ``He was so 
sick, and now he's one of the favorites.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong, wearing the red-white-and-blue jersey of the U.S.  
Postal Service team, powered through the 34-mile course in 1 hour, 
8 minutes and 36 seconds. He rode at an average speed of nearly 30 
mph. 
</P>
<P>
	He left such specialists as Spain's Abraham Olano, the world  
time-trial champion, and Britain's Chris Boardman in the dust. 
Armstrong called it ``one of the greatest victories of my life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now Armstrong, once so severely ill that almost everyone assumed  
his career was over -- at the very least -- is a decisive favorite as 
the Tour hits the Alps. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday's stage wasn't kind to all American riders. Bobby Julich,  
who came in third overall last year, fell on a steep descent during 
the time trial and is out of the race. 
</P>
<P>
	Julich, who rides for the French team Cofidis, was taken to a  
hospital, where he was found to have bruised ribs. Nothing was 
broken, except his hopes for this year's Tour. 
</P>
<P>
	The 27-year-old from Glenwood Springs, Colo., fell at the  
18.6-mile mark, on a descent where riders were traveling at about 
46 mph. He was was in 20th place overall going into Sunday's stage. 
</P>
<P>
	Things worked out better for another American, Tyler Hamilton of  
U.S. Postal, who came in fifth. 
</P>
<P>
	Alex Zulle of Switzerland was in second place, 58 seconds  
behind, followed by Frenchman Christophe Moreau, 2:05 behind. Olano 
came in fourth, at 2:22 behind. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, Moreau is second, followed by Olano and then Australian  
Stuart O'Grady. Spaniard Alvaro Gonzalez Galdeano is fifth. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside the team trailer before the race, Armstrong exuded  
confidence, joking with a teammate as he warmed up on a stationary 
bike. He even strummed a few bars of air guitar. 
</P>
<P>
	``Lance knew this was the day the Tour really began for him,''  
said Dan Osipow, operations manager for U.S. Postal. ``He's been 
waiting for this day for quite a while.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, Armstrong took great care to learn Sunday's course,  
coming to Metz on a rainy day in April to try it out. 
</P>
<P>
	In October 1996, Armstrong was diagnosed with testicular cancer  
that spread to his lungs and brain. He underwent surgery to remove 
his right testicle and lesions from his brain. 
</P>
<P>
	After long months of rehabilitation and recovery, Armstrong  
returned to racing early last year, and has been steadily 
improving. 
</P>
<P>
	He was considered a favorite for the time trial ever since he  
won the race prologue, also a time trial. He wore the yellow jersey 
for two days before losing it to Estonian Jaan Kirsipuu. 
</P>
<P>
	In public, he's appeared calm and focused all week. But after  
finishing Sunday, he admitted to a case of nerves. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm glad I won the yellow jersey a week ago,'' he said,  
``because I was really nervous while I had it. Maybe now I'll be 
less nervous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The riders were traveling to the Alps on today, a rest day.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
