<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Lower; Dow Down 23.43 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks fell today, ending a brief  
foray into record territory, as investors cautiously awaited the 
coming flood of quarterly profit reports. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 23.43 at 11,170.27, having surrendered a 36-point gain in 
earlier trading. On Friday, the Dow rose 66 points to a record 
11,193.70, extending 1999's gain to more than 2,000 points, or 
nearly 22 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mostly posting modest losses,  
although the Nasdaq composite index was still flirting with a 
record high, down just 0.73 at 2,792.34. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 
index was down 6.39 at 1,396.89. 
</P>
<P>
	With the flow of reports on the just ended second quarter  
beginning in earnest on Tuesday, traders were hesitant to make any 
big bets. Most stocks traded in a narrow range. 
</P>
<P>
	General Electric, which posted its results last week, was down 2  
3/16 at 114 15/16 to lead the Dow's retreat, offsetting gains by 
International Paper, up 1 7/8 at 53 5/8, and Eastman Kodak, up 1 15/16 at 
73 1/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Among leading Nasdaq technology names, Sun Micrososytems was up  
2 13/16 at 75 3/4. Intel, scheduled to release its earnings on 
Tuesday, was off 3/4 at 65 1/2. Dell Computer, which got a vote of 
confidence from Goldman Sachs last week, was up 15/16 at 43 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues were ahead of advancers by a 5-to-4 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, but advancers held a small lead in 
Nasdaq trading. 
</P>
<P>
	NYSE volume came to 531.50 million shares, down from Friday's  
pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was off 2.49 at 655.19, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was down 0.09 at 812.64. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
