<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Money For Ill Squandered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The former head of a non-profit home for the  
mentally disabled squandered public funds on huge raises and 
nepotism while allowing residents to live in vile conditions, 
according to a state report released Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Marie Chantal Joseph, the former executive director of Project  
Independence of Queens, Inc., ``abused the public trust placed in 
her and neglected and financially exploited the eight (resident) 
adults ... by depriving them of adequate food, services and 
shelter,'' the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 28-page report by the state Commission on Quality of Care  
for the Mentally Disabled is the result of an investigation 
prompted by anonymous tips in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the report, Joseph increased her salary from  
$47,398 to $114,615 between 1995 and 1997. Some of that money was 
used to make a down payment on her new Long Island home. 
</P>
<P>
	She also hired 15 relatives, a group that collected more than 50  
percent of the PIQ payroll, and issued several of them American 
Express cards on a PIQ account. 
</P>
<P>
	Joseph did not return a phonecall for comment on the report.  
While no longer the executive director of PIQ, she remains employed 
there. 
</P>
<P>
	PIQ interim executive director McKinley Jones declined to  
comment on Joseph's alleged improprieties, but said the living 
conditions for the residents had improved. 
</P>
<P>
	``The individuals who lived there are not in any danger,'' he  
said. ``We've made great improvements in that area ... We are 
developing policies and procedures to prevent any recurrence of 
those problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Unsanitary conditions chronicled in the report include roach  
traps, filled with live roaches, hanging above the food preparation 
area; a strong urine stench in the bathrooms and bedrooms; and a 
trash-filled entrance and backyard. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission forwarded copies of its report to the U.S.  
attorney in Brooklyn and the state attorney general for possible 
criminal charges, said spokesman Gary W. Masline. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
