<DOCNO> APW19990712.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 16:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cos. To Create Largest Drilling Co. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Schlumberger Ltd. will spin off its offshore  
drilling operations and combine them with Transocean Offshore Inc. 
to create the world's largest offshore drilling company. 
</P>
<P>
	The new company, to be based in Houston, will be called  
Transocean Sedco Forex and have about 7,500 employees, officials 
said Monday. Schlumberger stockholders will receive new shares 
valued at $3.2 billion as part of the agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	If approved by shareholders of both companies, Schlumberger  
stockholders will own 52 percent of the new company, receiving 
roughly one share of the new company for every five Schlumberger 
shares they own. 
</P>
<P>
	J. Michael Talbert, chairman and chief executive of  
Houston-based Transocean Offshore, told analysts Monday that the 
new company would have a large number of drilling rigs in all the 
major offshore fields, including the North Sea, the Gulf of Mexico, 
Brazil and West Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	Talbert said the company, as the biggest of its kind, would  
offer the broadest range of service to its customers, the world's 
largest oil companies and major independents. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the merger was partly driven by the cost of new rig  
construction and the technical difficulty of deep-water drilling. 
</P>
<P>
	Euan Baird, Schlumberger's president and chief executive, said  
the deal will let the remaining part of his company focus on 
extending its lead in technology that helps drillers tap 
hard-to-reach reserves. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts generally gave high marks to the deal, saying  
Transocean's deep-water expertise and its drilling operations in 
the Gulf of Mexico, the North Sea and off Brazil would complement 
Schlumberger's activities. They also said it could be the first of 
several consolidations in the relatively fragmented industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like the old Olympic theme, 'Let the games begin. This is  
going to foster more amalgamations in the offshore drilling 
industry,'' said George Gaspar, an oil industries analyst with 
Robert W. Baird &AMP; Co. ``Even some of the big companies are going to 
find it hard to compete with this group.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We think it's a positive, and it may trigger some other  
consolidations,'' said Allen Brooks of CIBC Oppenheimer. ``It's a 
highly fragmented business. There are just too many drilling 
contractors and the average fleet size is still fairly small.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said the deal would insulate Schlumberger from a  
volatile part of its business while giving Transocean, as part of 
the new company, a bigger fleet of drilling rigs. 
</P>
<P>
	Baird dismissed an analyst's suggestions that the company is  
spinning off its offshore operations because it is pessimistic 
about that segment of its business. 
</P>
<P>
	``This deal is not premised on earnings of the year 2000 because  
I don't think anyone has much idea about what that will be,'' Baird 
said. ``But in the next three to four years, there will be a strong 
recovery in all of the oil industry, and the offshore industry will 
be one of the beneficiaries.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sedco Forex Offshore had revenue of $1.1 billion and net income  
of $390 million last year, Schlumberger officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Transocean was formed when Sonat Offshore Drilling acquired  
Norwegian-based Transocean ASA. Its customers include big oil 
companies Exxon, BP-Amoco, Royal Dutch Shell and state-run 
companies. It earned $343 million on revenue of $1.1 billion last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Talbert will be president and chief executive of the new  
company. The chairman will be Victor E. Grijalva, Schlumberger vice 
chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	Schlumberger has 60,000 employees overall, while Transocean  
Offshore has 3,800. 
</P>
<P>
	Schlumberger's stock price rose 50 cents to $64.81 1/4.  
Transocean's stock was up 87 1/2 cents to $29.87 1/2. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990712.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 12:40:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Up on Dry Weather / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures advanced Monday on the  
Chicago Board of Trade as beneficial Midwestern rains eluded most 
spring-planted crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn, soybeans and spring wheat bounced higher as meteorologists  
predicted normal summer temperatures this week will not be 
accompanied by rain. While soil moisture remains fair, investors 
were concerned a prolonged dry spell could reduce yields. That 
likely would impact fall production, helping slash what is expected 
to be bumper supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans also were boosted by the U.S. Agriculture Department's  
report that showed a large amount crops were inspected for export 
shipment -- a sign that prices tumbling to their lowest in nearly 
three decades had spurred additional export business. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors ignored a USDA report that predicted lower cash market  
prices this fall for corn and soybeans, noting that had already 
been taken into account with a sharp decline in futures prices last 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	Gains in all the markets were limited, however, as the rally  
prompted a spate of farmer selling. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery rose 1/4 cent to $2.60 1/4 a bushel;  
December corn rose 1/4 cent to $1.96 3/4 a bushel; December oats rose 1/4 
cent to $1.09 a bushel; November soybeans rose 7 1/4 cents to $4.18 3/4 a 
bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef futures were mixed on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,  
while pork futures retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle rose .98 cent to 63.80 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle rose .35 cent to 77.47 cents a pound; August lean 
hogs fell .15 cent to 45.97 cents a pound; August pork bellies fell 
.93 cent to 32.87 cents a pound, while other contract months fell 
sharply. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
