<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 08:23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Orange Order Stages Belfast Protest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- More than 20,000 Protestant  
Orangemen and their supporters marched across Belfast today, but 
police and soldiers blocked a key bridge to keep them away from a 
hostile Catholic area on what is Northern Ireland's most 
hot-blooded day of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Parading beneath banners with such slogans as ``What we have we  
hold,'' the Orange Order rerouted its biggest annual Belfast parade 
to rally across the narrow Lagan River from Lower Ormeau, the 
Catholic area at the center of the dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	Officially, the group's mass mobilization each July 12  
commemorates Protestant King William of Orange's battlefield 
triumph over the Catholic-led forces of James II three centuries 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	In practice, it's designed to demonstrate which side of the  
community remains stronger in this Protestant-majority state. 
</P>
<P>
	At dawn, British army engineers erected tall steel walls crowned  
with barbed wire across Ormeau Bridge to prevent a few hundred 
south Belfast Orangemen from marching past Lower Ormeau en route to 
central Belfast and the start of the main parade. 
</P>
<P>
	Unwilling to accept this restriction without protest, all of  
Belfast's Orangemen marched in solidarity to the area, and rallied 
in nearby Ormeau Park as their leaders implored them not to fight 
the British security forces. 
</P>
<P>
	``Behave today and show the world that we are not the problem,''  
the Rev. William Hoey told the Orangemen at the bridge barricade. 
</P>
<P>
	``The problem lies on the other side of this bridge!'' Hoey  
proclaimed through a bullhorn, referring to a Catholic protest 
group in Lower Ormeau. 
</P>
<P>
	The Catholic demonstrators, led by a paroled IRA member, have  
tried to block Protestant parades since 1995, but today calmly 
watched the Orangemen protest across the river. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, an estimated 80,000 Orangemen marched at 18 locations  
across Northern Ireland today to mark Northern Ireland's annual 
holiday known as the Twelfth. 
</P>
<P>
	The one-sided festivities began overnight in hard-line  
Protestant parts of Northern Ireland with huge bonfires, impromptu 
concerts by so-called ``kick the pope'' bands of fife and drum, and 
fireworks displays. For the first time in several years, police 
reported no serious incidents of violence. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990712.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 08:23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
