<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 23:00:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Architect Cited for Congress Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The architect of the Capitol endangered lives  
at the Library of Congress when untrained employees working on 
poorly maintained equipment accidentally started a fire, 
congressional investigators report. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress' workplace safety agency, the Office of Compliance,  
cited the architect's office for five safety violations in the 
April episode. The citations were classified as ``serious,'' a term 
reserved for violations ``likely to cause serious injury or 
death.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The architect's office did not respond to a message seeking  
comment on the citations, which were issued Friday and announced 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The fire occurred at the library's Madison Building, which  
opened in 1980 and houses rare manuscripts, maps, books, musical 
instruments and a rough draft of the Declaration of Independence. 
</P>
<P>
	The documents escaped damage, but an architect's electrician was  
burned as the fire started. 
</P>
<P>
	The architect's office had an inkling of problems two days  
before the fire, when officials in the Madison Building had to 
cancel a planned fire drill because the alarm system failed to 
activate. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the citations said an important circuit breaker  
implicated in the fire had not been serviced since 1993, ``creating 
a danger of fire for employees ... and a danger of shock or 
electrocution for employees who work on the equipment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The investigators, charged with making Congress follow the same  
workplace safety rules that lawmakers have imposed on private 
businesses, previously have issued numerous citations against the 
architect for improper storage of chemicals and allowing an unsafe 
working environment, The Associated Press has reported. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the House inspector general said late last year  
that the Capitol and House offices were seriously deficient in fire 
safety and had installed a defective brand of sprinkler. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Green, general counsel for the Office of Compliance, said  
the architect's office ``does not share the same attitude that 
Fortune 500 companies share about safety.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The agency has only been obligated to follow federal safety  
rules since 1995, and trying to force compliance ``is a little bit 
like turning an ocean liner around,'' Green said. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to failing to maintain circuit breaker equipment,  
the citations said the architect: 
</P>
<P>
	--Left the alarm system in ``a mode for servicing,'' preventing  
activation of the full building alarm from the building's control 
console. It may have been left in that condition for several months 
and resulted in the canceled fire drill. 
</P>
<P>
	The system was reset the morning of the fire, but a faulty  
circuit prevented the alarm from sounding in the vicinity of the 
control room when the fire broke out. Because of that problem, 
officers -- who were needed for the evacuation -- were instead sent 
to activate manual alarms throughout the building to ensure no 
other areas were missed. 
</P>
<P>
	--Failed to cut power to electrical parts before employees tried  
to perform maintenance work that resulted in the fire. 
</P>
<P>
	The fire began when an electrician's tool came in contact with  
an energized conductor. Electrical distribution equipment failed, a 
nonfunctioning circuit breaker overheated and a flash fire began, 
burning and temporarily blinding the worker, who was saved by a 
colleague. 
</P>
<P>
	--Failed to train employees proper procedures for working on such  
equipment. The two electricians working in the Madison building on 
April 30 ``had received no training and were not familiar with the 
safety-related work practices required ... when performing work 
that poses a danger of electric shock,'' the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	--Did not install equipment that would have allowed a blocked  
duct to open automatically in case of fire. On April 30, the 
blocked duct prevented smoke from leaving the building, and it 
spread throughout the structure. 
</P>
<P>
	During the fire evacuation, when the faulty circuit breaker  
finally tripped, power was cut to one-fourth of the building. Some 
people were in darkness in rooms without windows. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
