<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Trial of Nurse Getting Underway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PERU, Ind. (AP) -- Hundreds of Miami County residents filled out  
questionnaires today to determine if they would be suitable jurors 
for the trial of a former nurse accused of murdering seven patients 
by injection. 
</P>
<P>
	About 700 people filed into a high school auditorium to answer  
more than 140 questions crafted by Clay Circuit Court Judge Ernest 
Yelton. Another 700 residents have been told to appear July 26. 
</P>
<P>
	All of those summoned live at least 150 miles from the former  
Vermillion County Hospital, where Orville Lynn Majors is accused of 
murdering seven elderly patients by giving them lethal injections. 
</P>
<P>
	Nurses have told investigators that Majors, 38, either gave  
injections to or stood near the victims holding a syringe when no 
injection was scheduled. 
</P>
<P>
	Police and prosecutors have said he may have killed dozens at  
the hospital between 1993 and 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Yelton took the unusual step of summoning 1,400 people as  
possible jurors because of extensive publicity about the crime. 
</P>
<P>
	He will whittle down the number of potential jurors to roughly  
100 for an Aug. 30 hearing, when prosecutors and defense attorneys 
will begin questioning them. A final panel of 18 will be selected. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
