<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sen. Smith Leaves Republican Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. Bob Smith of New Hampshire announced  
Monday night he was leaving Republican Party to become an 
independent, indicating he might seek the nomination of some other 
party in his bid for the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith characterized his much-anticipated decision as one of  
principles over party, chastising GOP lawmakers for forsaking the 
Republican platform. 
</P>
<P>
	``I came into the Republican Party on principle, and I'm leaving  
on principle,'' Smith said on CNN's ``Larry King Live.'' He decried 
leaders in his party ``who believe that electing people with an 'R' 
next to their name is more important than principle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith said he still intends to run for president and confirmed  
that he has been speaking with other political groups, such as 
members of the U.S. Taxpayers Party, about a nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm certainly interested,'' Smith said of the Taxpayers Party.  
But, he added, ``it would be very presumptuous to say that the 
nomination is mine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the days leading up to Smith's announcement, a string of GOP  
leaders have blasted his decision. Jim Nicholson, chairman of the 
Republican National Committee, called the defection a ``serious 
mistake for you personally, with only a marginal political impact -- 
and a counterproductive one at that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, New Hampshire Republican Chairman Steven Duprey  
continued the criticism, saying Smith had bailed out of the party 
because his message could not distinguish him among the field of 
GOP candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	``America has never liked a sore loser,'' Duprey said on CNN's  
``Crossfire.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Smith brushed off the attacks by the party leaders.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is the establishment. They're interested in poll numbers.  
They're interested in how much money you have. They're interested 
in your name recognition,'' he said. ``They've walked away from the 
principles.'' 
</P>
<P>
	GOP presidential contender Steve Forbes, touring Iowa on Monday,  
called Smith's decision a ``wake-up call'' for the party 
establishment. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not that Bob Smith is abandoning the Republican Party,  
it's that the Republican establishment is in the process of 
abandoning grass-roots conservatives,'' Forbes said. ``It's a bad 
omen for the GOP when a solid Reagan conservative like Bob Smith 
would even consider leaving.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another GOP contender Dan Quayle, called Smith's decision a loss  
for the GOP but added: ``We cannot cut and run and still claim to 
provide the leadership conservatives across America expect from 
us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A senator since 1990 and a House member for six years before  
that, Smith said he did not know how this would affect his standing 
on Senate committees. But he said he would accept the judgment of 
his colleagues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
