<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gannett Earnings Up 12 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- Gannett Co.'s earnings rose 12 percent in  
the second quarter due to increased advertising sales at USA Today, 
its flagship newspaper, and other papers nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Gannett, the nation's second-largest newspaper chain, earned  
$244.2 million, or 87 cents per share, in the quarter ended June 
27, up from $222.8 million, or 78 cents per share, during the same 
period a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts surveyed by First Call Corp. had projected earnings of  
86 cents per share. 
</P>
<P>
	Second-quarter revenue increased 3 percent to $1.34 billion,  
from $1.3 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Gannett publishes 74 daily newspapers. It also operates 21  
television stations and cable TV systems. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said Monday that the earnings in its newspaper  
segment reflected strong demand for classified and national 
advertising and the 9 percent decline in newsprint expense for the 
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	USA Today's paid advertising pages increased to 1,657, compared  
to 1,494 in the second quarter of 1998, and advertising revenues 
grew 20 percent. Revenues from circulation, however, dropped 1.6 
percent to $248,812, from $252,762. 
</P>
<P>
	Television cash flow decreased 4 percent to $115.1 million and  
was affected by the absence of political advertising and last 
year's ``Seinfeld'' show finale, which boosted results in the 
second quarter of 1998, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Gannett rose 56 1/4 cents to $72 in afternoon trading on  
the New York Stock Exchange. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
