<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Scripps Earnings Up 21 percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- The E.W. Scripps Co. reported a 21 percent  
increase in second-quarter earnings Monday thanks to better results 
from cable television and newspapers. 
</P>
<P>
	Scripps earned $44.2 million, or 56 cents per share, in the  
quarter ended June 30 compared with $36.4 million and 45 cents a 
year ago. Revenues rose 6 percent to $388.3 million from $366.9 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Newspapers in many of the company's markets reported revenue  
increases from classified and national advertising. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues were up at Scripps' two cable channels, Home &AMP; Garden  
Television and the Food Network, but the company plans to begin 
1,000 hours of new programming that will increase costs during the 
second half of the year, said William R. Burleigh, chairman, 
president and chief executive officer of Scripps. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sept. 30, the company plans to start a third cable channel  
called Do-It-Yourself, or DIY, designed to be used with interactive 
services. 
</P>
<P>
	The company operates 19 daily newspapers, nine  
network-affiliated television stations; the two cable channels; 
Scripps Productions; United Media, which syndicates and licenses 
news features and comics, and the Scripps Howard News Service. 
Scripps also publishes independent Yellow Pages directories. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first six months of the fiscal year, Scripps earned  
$76.2 million, or 96 cents per share, compared with $61.5 million 
and 75 cents a year earlier. Revenues rose to $761.7 million from 
$713.7 million. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
