<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coffee Falls Sharply on Forecast  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Coffee futures fell sharply on the Board of Trade of the City of  
New York amid perceptions the world's largest producing country 
will sail through the winter without a damaging frost. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, cotton also tumbled, while grains and soybeans  
moved higher. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffee futures went into sharp retreat as another threatened  
cold front in some of Brazil's major producing regions failed to 
materialize over the weekend. Brazil has been enjoying a mild 
winter that is expected to help boost production for a third year. 
</P>
<P>
	The world's largest producer of coffee is benefiting from having  
planted young trees earlier this decade; they can produce more -- 
and have. Brazil last year harvested its largest crop in 11 years 
and is on tap to surpass that this year, agronomists say. 
</P>
<P>
	That could further contribute to a world supply glut. While  
Brazil produces mainly robusta coffees not certified for New York 
contract specifications, its beans often are blended with the 
arabicas used for gourmet coffees. 
</P>
<P>
	Arabica coffee for September delivery tumbled 4.6 cents to 92.70  
cents a pound. 
</P>
<P>
	Cotton futures also finished sharply lower on the New York  
Cotton Exchange after the government predicted both world and U.S. 
inventories will swell in coming months. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Agriculture Department's latest supply and demand  
report showed this year's world production at 89.24 million bales, 
up more than 2 million bales from its June estimate. The amount of 
the crop expected to be left over before the next harvest also 
rose, by 1.8 million bales to 43.45 million bales. 
</P>
<P>
	Favorable growing weather in the United States also was expected  
to help boost production by 700,000 bales to 18.7 million bales, 
the USDA predicted. 
</P>
<P>
	October cotton fell 1.56 cents to 48.45 cents a pound.  
</P>
<P>
	Grain and soybean futures advanced on the Chicago Board of Trade  
as beneficial Midwestern rains eluded most spring-planted crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn, soybeans and spring wheat bounced higher as meteorologists  
predicted normal summer temperatures this week will not be 
accompanied by rain. While soil moisture remains fair, investors 
were concerned a prolonged dry spell could reduce yields. That 
likely would impact fall production, helping slash what is expected 
to be bumper supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	But the National Weather Service's latest 10-day forecast,  
released after trading ended, called for above-normal rainfall and 
normal temperatures in key Midwestern growing states. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans also were boosted by the U.S. Agriculture Department's  
report that showed a large amount of crops were inspected for 
export shipment -- a sign that additional export business had been 
spurred by a plunge in prices to their lowest in nearly three 
decades. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors ignored a USDA report that predicted lower cash market  
prices this fall for corn and soybeans, noting that had already 
been taken into account with a sharp decline in futures prices last 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	Gains in all the markets were limited, however, as the rally  
prompted a spate of farmer selling. 
</P>
<P>
	December wheat rose 1/4 cent to $2.60 1/4 a bushel; December corn  
rose 1/4 cent to $1.96 3/4 a bushel; December oats rose 1/4 cent to $1.09 
a bushel; November soybeans rose 7 1/4 cents to $4.18 3/4 a bushel. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990712.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 14:50:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Politics 2000 Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Donald Trump says he would ``probably run and  
probably win'' the 2000 presidential race if the Reform Party 
drafted him. 
</P>
<P>
	One problem: The Reform Party isn't asking.  
</P>
<P>
	``Is this a joke?'' Reform Party Chairman Russell Verney asked.  
``I have never once heard his name mentioned in the Reform Party. 
There is going to be no absentee candidate-drafting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Running on the Democratic or Republican tickets is out, Trump  
said, because ``the two major parties are lost when it comes to 
finding solutions to America's problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``While I have not decided to become a candidate at this time,  
if the Reform Party nominated me, I would probably run and probably 
win,'' Trump said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I won, I would ask for an immediate recount,'' he added.  
</P>
<P>
	Verney said Trump has never contacted the party or discussed his  
views of its platform. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Verney and Reform Party Vice Chair Pat Benjamin and Verney  
said Trump is welcome to compete for the nomination along with any 
other interested candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he wants to endorse our principles, our platform, then he  
can present himself to the members for nomination,'' Verney said. 
``Our process requires people to do work. There's no absentee 
draft.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trump said ``early Reform Party polls'' and urgings from ``many,  
many Americans'' had inspired him to publicize his interest in the 
nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush got a tasty  
payoff Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ben's Best delicatessen of Rego Park, N.Y., delivered sandwiches  
for 30 courtesy of New York Gov. George Pataki, who had bet Bush 
that the Knicks would beat the Spurs in the NBA finals. 
</P>
<P>
	The delivery featured matzoh balls, celery soda and a variety of  
kosher sandwiches, including pastrami and corned beef. 
</P>
<P>
	Photographers, but no reporters, were allowed into the  
reception. 
</P>
<P>
	``The deli owner delivered the sandwiches personally, so we  
thought it would be all in good spirit to have a photo opportunity 
and share in the pride that all Texans feel toward our San Antonio 
Spurs,'' said Bush spokesman Scott McClellan. 
</P>
<P>
	The Spurs won their first NBA title in the franchise's 26-year  
history last month, beating the Knicks four games to one in the 
finals. If the San Antonio team had lost, Bush had pledged to send 
Pataki a pair of Texas-style western boots -- complete with spurs. 
</P>
<P>
	This isn't the first victory for the GOP presidential  
front-runner in his sports team rivalry with Pataki. 
</P>
<P>
	The two Republican governors also had wagered on whether the  
Dallas Stars or Buffalo Sabres would win the NHL championship. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars triumphed and Pataki sent Bush buffalo wings last week  
and will dispatch an order of sandwiches Wednesday, according to 
the governor's office. 
</P>
<P>
	Had the Sabres won, Bush would have owed Pataki barbecue ribs  
and brisket if the Sabres had won. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- A Democratic county leader said Monday that  
Vice President Al Gore is a ``stuffed shirt'' and that Bill Bradley 
is ``more electable'' in the presidential race. 
</P>
<P>
	While stopping short of an outright endorsement of the former  
New Jersey senator's bid for the Democratic nomination, David 
Alpert of Westchester County said that while he could ``live with 
either ... I think Bradley is the more exciting candidate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``When you're putting together a whole package, I think he's  
more electable,'' Alpert said. ``I think Gore is a great guy, but I 
think he's -- I'm probably using the wrong word -- a stuffed shirt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alpert said he hoped to make an endorsement in the presidential  
race before the end of the summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Westchester is the state's eighth largest of 62 counties in  
terms of Democratic enrollment, with 210,000 party members. It is 
located just north of New York City and is considered one of the 
linchpins to success in the politically crucial suburbs surrounding 
the city in statewide campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for Gore, Chris Lehane, said ``we're very pleased  
with the depth and breadth of our support throughout New York and 
we'll continue working to make that support even broader and 
deeper.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the state's top Democratic Party leadership, including  
more than a half dozen of the state's most powerful county chairmen 
have already lined up behind Gore in New York. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
