<P>
	Ingram, CompUSA Sign $10B Deal  
</P>
<P>
	SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) -- Ingram Micro Inc., the world's largest  
distributor of computers, today announced an initial agreement to 
assemble and provide maintenance for machines that CompUSA Inc. 
sells directly to business, government and education customers. 
CompUSA estimates the five-year deal, which the companies hope to 
have finalized by late August, is worth about $10 billion. Under 
the deal, CompUSA will close its distribution center in Grapevine, 
Texas, and will no longer stock, configure or custom assemble 
computers for its commercial customers. Ingram Micro will take over 
these operations. Ingram Micro shares were at 17 3/4, up 1 1/4. CompUSA 
shares were at 7 5/16, down 1/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Showdown Expected at Venator Meeting  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Observers are expecting lively discussion at  
Friday's meeting in Florida of of shareholders in Venator, the 
former Woolworth. The business seems still to be limping along. 
Sales and profits are down, and its stock price -- while improved 
this year -- stands at just 10 1/4, up 3/8 today, compared to more than 
28 two years ago. Now, its biggest shareholder, Greenway Partners, 
is charging that the company's management isn't doing enough to get 
the troubled retailer back on track. A showdown is expected at 
Friday's gathering, an event that many think will be nothing less 
than downright nasty. Greenway, a New York-based investment firm, 
will try to snatch away four director seats, and also to convince 
shareholders to change the corporate name back to Woolworth and 
loosen the company's defenses against a takeover. 

</P>
<P>
	New Car Buyers Go to Internet  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- More buyers are cruising the information highway  
in search of a car, according to a study released today. Forty 
percent of consumers who recently bought a car or truck used the 
Internet to help them shop, up from 25 percent a year ago, 
according to initial results of a J.D. Power and Associates survey. 
The survey showed that the number of purchasers who used an online 
buying service doubled in this year's first quarter, from 12,500 a 
month nationwide to more than 25,000, said Chris Denove, consulting 
operations director for the research firm in Agoura Hills, Calif. 
The proportion of new-vehicle purchasers using the Internet 
increased from 1.1 percent a year ago to 2.6 percent. 

</P>
<P>
	Microsoft To Help Canada Digital TV  
</P>
<P>
	REDMOND, Wash. (AP) -- Microsoft Corp. will invest $400 million  
in Toronto-based Rogers Communications Inc. as part of an agreement 
to develop new digital television services to Canadian homes. The 
collaboration disclosed today will provide Canadian TV viewers with 
interactive services, including Internet and e-mail, operating 
through advanced set-top boxes. As part of the agreement, Rogers is 
to license Microsoft software to support at least 1 million set-top 
boxes. 

</P>
<P>
	Gannett Earnings Up 12 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- Gannett Co.'s earnings rose 12 percent in  
the second quarter due to increased advertising sales at USA Today, 
its flagship newspaper, and other papers nationwide. Gannett, the 
nation's second-largest newspaper chain, earned $244.2 million, or 
87 cents per share, in the quarter ended June 27, up from $222.8 
million, or 78 cents per share, during the same period a year 
earlier. 

</P>
<P>
	South Africa Braces for Job Losses  
</P>
<P>
	JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- South Africa is bracing for  
tens of thousands of job losses in the gold, transport and 
telecommunications industries, part of a continuing drive to make 
private and public companies more competitive. In the past week, 
numerous reports have circulated of 27,000 possible job cuts by 
national train operator Spoornet, 10,000 by telecommunications 
provider Telkom and another 11,700 in the gold mining industry. 
Last week, 5,000 miners were laid off at the East Rand Proprietary 
Mines in Johannesburg, one of the country's oldest firms forced to 
close by high production costs and low gold prices. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia's Computers Not Y2K-Ready  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Only one-third of Russia's vital computer systems  
are ready for the millennium, and the government probably won't 
have the money to fix the rest in time, officials said today. 
Finance Ministry officials told a Cabinet meeting that Russia needs 
at least $187 million to prepare its computers for the year 2000, 
the ITAR-Tass news agency reported. The new estimates were 
dramatically lower than previous figures, which said Russia would 
need $1 billion to $3 billion to fight the millennium bug. The 
Finance Ministry did not explain the discrepancy. 

</P>
<P>
	Portugal Telecom Sell-Off a Success  
</P>
<P>
	LISBON, Portugal (AP) -- The sale of a 13.5 percent stake in  
Portugal Telecom and an associated share rights issue raised some 
$1.62 billion, the government announced today. The sale of 42.1 
million shares, which began three weeks ago, reduced the 
government's stake in the company to 10 percent. The phased 
privatization of PT, which is expanding into Brazil and North 
Africa, began in 1994. The state's share of revenue from the sale 
was expected to be $960 million, an official said. 

</P>
<P>
	Societe Generale Rebuffs BNP  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- The board of directors of French banking group  
Societe Generale today rejected Banque Nationale de Paris' 
sweetened offer for its shares -- the latest installment of a 
three-way takeover battle. BNP did not immediately comment on the 
decision by Societe Generale. The third bank in the battle, 
Paribas, rejected the sweetened BNP offer on Friday. The 
18-week-old takeover fight began in March when BNP jumped into an 
agreed merger between Societe Generale and Paribas, offering $37 
billion for the two banks. Societe Generale and Paribas rejected 
BNP's offer and have spurned its advances since then. 

</P>
<P>
	Americans Eat More Seafood  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans ate more fish last year, boosting  
average consumption to 14.9 pounds, the National Oceanic and 
Atmospheric Administration reported today. Seafood consumption was 
up 3.7 percent in the United States, to 4.01 billion pounds, the 
agency said. The 14.9 pound average is up 0.3 pounds from 1997, 
NOAA said. Of the seafood consumed per person, 10.2 pounds were 
fresh or frozen fish or shellfish, 4.4 pounds were canned seafood, 
and 0.3 pounds of seafood was cured. The increase was in the fresh 
and frozen products. 

</P>
