<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Rise Sharply / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices rose sharply Monday as investors  
sought the safety of U.S.-backed notes amid a slide in Latin 
American stock markets. The rally sent bond yields to their lowest 
level in six weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the 30-year Treasury bond rose 1 1/4 point, or $12.50  
per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the opposite 
direction, fell to 5.90 percent from 6 percent late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The bond market also gained ground as some portfolio managers  
were said to have moved part of their assets out of U.S. stocks and 
into bonds, encouraged by expectations that economic indicators due 
out later this week will show a lack of inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonds rose as talk of problems in Latin America surfaced,  
including a possible debt moratorium in Argentina and talk of 
cabinet reshuffle in Brazil. The uncertainty sent Argentine and 
Brazilian stocks sharply lower and left investors hungry for the 
safety of U.S. bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader Treasury market, prices of short-term securities  
rose 5/32 point to 7/32 point higher and intermediate maturities 
rose 13/32 point to 27/32 point higher, reported Bridge Telerate. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading, yields on three-month Treasury bills rose to  
4.72 percent while the rose 0.05 percentage point to 4.60 percent. 
Six-month yields rose to 4.71 percent, as the discount fell 0.02 
percentage point to 4.54 percent. One-year yields fell to 4.96 
percent as the discount fell 0.02 percent to 4.72 percent from late 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 5 percent from 4.94 percent from late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds rose 5/16 point to 119 1/4. The average yield 
to maturity fell to 5.51 percent from 5.53 percent late Friday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
