<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 12:01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  World Cup Champs on Whirlwind Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- America's newest golden girls -- the United  
States' winning World Cup women's soccer team -- used whirlwind TV 
appearances today to spread the message that professional women 
athletes are here to stay. 
</P>
<P>
	The extraordinary attention did not surprise midfielder Julie  
Foudy. ``We've always said this team is America's best kept 
secret,'' Foudy said on NBC's ``Today'' show. ``So finally the 
secret is out!'' 
</P>
<P>
	The team, minus Michelle Akers who was injured in Saturday's  
game, also appeared on ABC's ``Good Morning America,'' with their 
World Cup trophy in tow. 
</P>
<P>
	Several young girls were in the crowd sporting replicas of Mia  
Hamm's No. 9 jersey. The team signed soccer balls and encouraged 
young fans not to give up in fulfilling their ambitions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were those girls at one time and they can be there, too,''  
Hamm said. ``Whatever they want to be, whatever they dream to be, 
they can do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Goalie Briana Scurry said she relished her position as a role  
model for young black girls and said she planned to hold some inner 
city soccer clinics to get more black boys and girls involved in 
the sport. 
</P>
<P>
	Showered with confetti and praise on Sunday in Los Angeles, the  
team took its victory laps at Disneyland and at a sweltering 
downtown rally where -- this time at least -- nobody took their shirt 
off. 
</P>
<P>
	The World Cup winners rubbed elbows with Mickey and Minnie Mouse  
and were pelted with confetti as they rode a float down 
Disneyland's Main Street. 
</P>
<P>
	Then it was on to the Los Angeles Convention Center, where  
several hundred fans in red, white and blue seemed unfazed by the 
95-degree heat. One fan held a sign that read: ``Thank You Title 
IX.'' That refers to the 1972 federal law that forced schools to 
provide females with the same sports opportunities as males. 
</P>
<P>
	At the outdoor Los Angeles rally, Foudy ran to the microphone  
and raised her arms in triumph. 
</P>
<P>
	``What's up L.A.?'' she said. ``You guys are awesome!''  
</P>
<P>
	She introduced her teammates one by one, and the cheering  
swelled when she got to Scurry and Brandi Chastain -- described by 
Foudy as ``a woman who has the uncanny knack for taking her clothes 
off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chastain shed her jersey after kicking the winning goal in  
Saturday's victory over China. She previously posed in the buff -- 
carrying a strategically placed soccer ball -- for Gear magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if you'll see any more of that,'' Chastain said.  
``But I'm glad I did it. It was fun and if it brought attention to 
soccer, that's great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She had blamed the euphoria of victory for the impromptu baring  
of her sports bra. But Foudy didn't let her off that easily. 
</P>
<P>
	``She says `temporary insanity,' but who believes that?'' Foudy  
yelled to the crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	Players strode onto the stage wearing white World Cup champion  
T-shirts, gold medals around their necks and smiles on their faces. 
</P>
<P>
	They had more than one reason to be happy -- the Women's World  
Cup Organizing Committee announced Sunday that it would make a 
$750,000 contribution to the tournament's prize money. 
</P>
<P>
	The players already have been paid between $25,000 and $45,000  
each, but their $12,500 bonuses for winning the final were 
increased between $40,000 and $50,000 each. 
</P>
<P>
	Chastain said that, when she was preparing for the final kick of  
the game, she tried ``not to look the goalkeeper in the eyes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``She has a way of making you feel uncomfortable when you do  
that,'' Chastain said. 
</P>
<P>
	And when the ball hit the net?  
</P>
<P>
	``It can't be described,'' she said. ``Everything was  
slow-motion up until then, and you feel like you're in total 
control of everything. Then it's gone and you have no control of 
anything at all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Scurry greeted fans by thanking young soccer players who  
traveled from around the country to attend the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``You guys have been watching us for years, making the drive or  
trek to come out here. We appreciate all of your support. We love 
all of you,'' said Scurry, introduced by Foudy simply as ``the 
woman on goal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The crowd peppered Scurry with good-natured boos when she ended  
her speech by quipping, ``I have to scurry off and do some more 
events.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Come on!'' she replied. ``That was a good one.''  
</P>
<P>
	Hamm did not speak, but clutched the World Cup trophy in her  
hands and occasionally snapped photos of the cheering crowd and the 
swarm of cameras and reporters behind them. 
</P>
<P>
	Akers, removed from the game after suffering heat exhaustion,  
was still recovering Sunday and did not attend the victory events. 
Coach Tony DiCicco also missed the events, returning home to spend 
time with his family. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
