<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Americans Boost Seafood Intake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans ate more fish last year, boosting  
average consumption to 14.9 pounds, the National Oceanic and 
Atmospheric Administration reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	Seafood consumption was up 3.7 percent in the United States, to  
4.01 billion pounds, the agency said. The 14.9 pound average is up 
0.3 pounds from 1997, NOAA said. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the seafood consumed per person, 10.2 pounds were fresh or  
frozen fish or shellfish, 4.4 pounds were canned seafood, and 0.3 
pounds of seafood was cured. The increase was in the fresh and 
frozen products. 
</P>
<P>
	The consumption of shrimp reached a record 2.8 pounds per  
person. Also, farm-raised catfish consumption reached 1.0 pound per 
person for the first time. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
