<DOCNO> APW19990712.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 09:00:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ga. School Shooting Hearing Delayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONYERS, Ga. (AP) -- A hearing to determine if the 15-year-old  
charged in the Heritage High School shootings should be tried as an 
adult was delayed today after his attorney asked that his client be 
hospitalized for psychiatric treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	The hearing for Anthony ``T.J.'' Solomon had been scheduled for  
Tuesday in Rockdale County Juvenile Court. It was put off until 
early August, but no definite date was set, said Lillian Sellers, a 
spokeswoman for Juvenile Court Judge William Schneider. 
</P>
<P>
	Solomon, a sophomore at the school in the Atlanta suburb, is  
charged with 21 counts including aggravated assault, cruelty to 
children and weapons violations in the gunfire that wounded six of 
his classmates May 20. 
</P>
<P>
	Jan Harris, a lawyer for the Atlanta firm that is representing  
Solomon, said today that the teen-ager ``suffers from long-term, 
untreated and major depression with psychotic features and has some 
degree of suicidal tendencies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The request to have Solomon hospitalized was made late last  
week, and the defense lawyers plan to meet with Schneider on 
Tuesday to discuss it, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Solomon has been in juvenile detention since the shooting and  
``is not doing very well emotionally,'' Ms. Harris said. 
</P>
<P>
	Another of Solomon's lawyers, Ed Garland, has previously said  
that at the time of the shooting the teen-ager was taking Ritalin, 
a drug often prescribed for children with attention-deficit 
hyperactivity disorder. 
</P>
<P>
	The shooting happened one month after the shootings at Columbine  
High School in Littleton, Colo., in which 15 people died, including 
the two shooters. 
</P>
<P>
	The charges against Solomon do not include crimes that  
automatically would transfer the case to adult court. It will be up 
to the judge to decide whether to transfer it, as District Attorney 
Richard Read has said he wants, or keep it in the juvenile system. 
</P>
<P>
	If convicted as an adult, Solomon faces a sentence of up to 351  
years. The maximum sentence he could receive in juvenile court is 
60 months in the youth prison system. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990712.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 08:24:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Blast Rattles Iranian Protest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) -- Protesters clashed with  
police in the Iranian capital today, and several people were 
arrested, as demonstrations persisted over a violent attack on a 
university dormitory. 
</P>
<P>
	Police in anti-riot gear were out in force at Vali Asr Avenue in  
central Tehran, where they arrested several protesters and threw 
them in a waiting van, witnesses said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shops in the tree-lined commercial avenue pulled down their  
shutters during the clash, according to witnesses reached by 
telephone from Dubai. They said two men on a motorcycle were beaten 
by protesters who assumed they were plainclothes intelligence 
agents. The men escaped after throwing a tear gas canister at the 
demonstrators. 
</P>
<P>
	The raid on the dormitory Friday prompted thousands of students  
to stage protests, the strongest expression of discontent in Iran 
since the 1979 Islamic revolution that overthrew the U.S.-backed 
shah. 
</P>
<P>
	Police used tear gas and fired shots into the air to disperse  
the crowds in central Tehran today. Nearby at Tehran University, 
about 5,000 people, including 2,000 university staff members, 
staged a sit-in. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities have been losing patience with the protests, which  
were sparked Thursday by the closing of a leftist newspaper and the 
passing of an anti-press bill and swelled Friday after police 
stormed the Tehran University dormitory. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier today, police intervened to control the university  
protest after a small explosion plunged the sit-in into chaos, 
Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Witnesses said the explosion was caused by a percussion hand  
grenade. A few minutes earlier, a person on motorcycle fired a 
single shot into the air as he raced past the university gate. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the managing director of the closed Salam newspaper  
asked Iranian journalists not to follow through with plans for a 
one-day strike Tuesday, IRNA reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Mohammad Musavi Khoiniha said it is important for the community  
to receive ``frank and transparent'' news reports about the current 
situation. Journalists at more than 20 newspapers had pledged to 
strike in solidarity with the banned newspaper, the Neshat daily 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	One person died and at least 20 were injured in the raid on the  
dormitory, which apparently was carried out with the backing of 
government hard-liners. 
</P>
<P>
	Iran's supreme leader, Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, who heads the  
hard-liners, called the attack ``a bitter and unacceptable 
incident'' that ``pained his heart,'' the official news agency 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	All offenders will be dealt with ``no matter in the garb of law  
enforcement forces or else,'' IRNA quoted Khamenei as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	The demonstrations have exposed a widening gulf between the  
Khamenei's hard-line faction and the allies of the reformist 
President Mohammad Khatami. Khatami is the hero of the student 
protesters, who have been chanting slogans for Khamenei, who is not 
elected, to step down and hand over control of the security forces. 
</P>
<P>
	Iran on Sunday fired two security chiefs responsible for the  
raid in response to student demands, but there has been no action 
against Brig. Gen. Hedayat Lotfian, head of the national police, 
whom the students blame for the raid. A third security chief, the 
commander of the Tehran region, has been reprimanded. 
</P>
<P>
	Witnesses said about 10,000 students demonstrated in Tehran on  
Sunday. Iranian communities in the United States also staged 
protests in Los Angeles, Houston and Dallas in support of the 
students. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990712.0143 </DOCNO>
