<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Goodrich, Coltec Complete Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHFIELD, Ohio (AP) -- BFGoodrich Co. completed its $2 billion  
merger with Coltec Industries Monday, creating the world's largest 
manufacturer of aircraft landing gear. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies' announcement came after Connecticut-based Crane  
Co. dropped its lawsuit claiming the merger violated federal 
anti-trust laws. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the deal, BFGoodrich promised Crane it would consider  
using Crane's brake control and proximity sensors when making 
integrated landing system bids over the next 10 years, the 
companies said in a joint statement. Specifics of the deal were not 
disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	BFGoodrich and Coltec struck a deal with AlliedSignal last week  
to use its wheels and brakes in bidding integrated landing systems 
in exchange for the New Jersey-based company dropping its part of 
the lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Once the settlement with Crane was reached, a judge in U.S.  
District Court in South Bend, Ind., lifted a preliminary injunction 
that had blocked the merger. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal announced in November has already passed regulatory  
muster. 
</P>
<P>
	Goodrich, which was founded in nearby Akron as a rubber company  
in 1870, will move to Coltec's headquarters in Charlotte, N.C., as 
a result of the merger, eliminating 170 positions here. About 50 of 
those jobs may be transferred to Charlotte or other Goodrich 
plants. 
</P>
<P>
	The company sold its tire business in 1987 to Michelin to focus  
on products and services for the aeronautics industry. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990712.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 08:30:21 </DATE_TIME>
