<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> European stocks fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Depressed German industrial production figures  
pushed European stocks lower today. 
</P>
<P>
	Investor confidence was hit by data for May showing industrial  
production had shrunk by 0.2 percent, instead of rising by 0.1 
percent, as markets had expected. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a blow to recent hopes that Germany will rescue Europe  
from low growth expectations. Despite that, Frankfurt's DAX stock 
index closed up 0.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's a blip. It goes to show the sluggish performance  
of the first half. We still believe growth will expand in the 
second half of 1999,'' said Jeremy Batstone, equity economist at 
NatWest Stockbrokers in London. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, oil stocks made gains, with the Dow Jones Stoxx  
Energy index closing up 2.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 594 European companies closed up  
1.20 points, or 0.4 percent, at 321.42, while the Dow Jones Euro 
Stoxx Index, which tracks 295 companies in countries that joined 
the euro single currency, finished up 0.59 points at 337.50. 
</P>
<P>
	Paris hotel chain Accor helped the CAC-40 index close up 0.3  
percent -- one of the best-performing markets Monday -- after it made 
a $1.1 billion offer for U.S. motel chain Red Roof Inns. Accor 
finished up 1.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Milan's MIBtel index fell 0.1 percent, and Madrid's IBEX-35  
index closed down 0.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	London's Financial Times Stock Exchange 100-share index was down  
0.3 percent. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
