<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 12:30:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> South Africa Braces for Job Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- South Africa is bracing for  
tens of thousands of job losses in the gold, transport and 
telecommunications industries, part of a continuing drive to make 
private and public companies more competitive. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past week, numerous reports have circulated of 27,000  
possible job cuts by national train operator Spoornet, 10,000 by 
telecommunications provider Telkom and another 11,700 in the gold 
mining industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``The impact ... on local economies is difficult to calculate,  
but the threat facing individuals and their families could spread 
to whole communities,'' wrote The Star in Johannesburg in an 
editorial on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, 5,000 miners were laid off at the East Rand  
Proprietary Mines in Johannesburg, one of the country's oldest 
firms forced to close by high production costs and low gold prices. 
</P>
<P>
	South African industry and government shed 500,000 jobs in the  
past five years, officials have said. These included 315,000 in the 
private sector and another 100,000 in the civil service, according 
to media reports. 
</P>
<P>
	With 42 percent unemployment among the country's majority black  
population, the issue was a major theme of recent elections, when 
President Thabo Mbeki pledged to attract foreign investment to 
boost jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	But at the same time, he promised to crackdown on waste in  
government, which would result in some layoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Public Enterprises Minster Jeff Radebe on Monday said the  
elimination of up to 27,000 jobs at Spoornet was only one of 
several options being considered for public-owned companies that 
were being privatized. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any reports that imminent retrenchments are on hand are  
premature to say the least, '' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Transnet, which runs Spoornet's train service and other  
transport companies, lost $68 million last year. Since 1994, 
Spoornet alone has cut 16,000 jobs; it currently employs 48,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``For a government that has promised to put job creation at the  
top of its agenda, the past few weeks look like a disaster of epic 
proportions,'' said an editorial last week in Business Day, the 
country's leading business newspaper in Johannesburg. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics charge that the ruling African National Congress waited  
until after the elections to release the bad news, in order to keep 
together the alliance of trade unions and the Communist Party 
forged during the anti-apartheid struggle. 
</P>
<P>
	``All these cutdowns are done after the elections because  
government had to keep the tripartite alliance together,'' said 
Dirk Hermann of the Mineworker's Union. 
</P>
<P>
	To add pressure on the government, three public service unions --  
representing about 500,000 teachers, health workers and police -- 
launched low-key job actions on Monday to push for 10 percent 
salary increases. 
</P>
<P>
	Government has offered only 5.7 percent, less than the 7 percent  
inflation rate. With 1 million public service employees, the 
government spends about 50 percent of its budget on salaries. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990712.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 08:30:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Die in Md. of Legionnaires Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAVRE de GRACE, Md. (AP) -- A hot-water tank at Harford Memorial  
Hospital is the likely cause of an outbreak of Legionnaires' 
disease that has killed three elderly patients and sickened two 
others, state and hospital officials say. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest fatality was a patient in the hospital June 18-28,  
before health officials discovered the bacteria there, hospital 
spokesman Robert Netherland said yesterday. 
</P>
<P>
	The man, whose name was not released, was readmitted to the  
hospital Friday and died that evening. Test results came back 
Saturday confirming he had the bacteria that causes Legionnaires' 
disease. 
</P>
<P>
	``This person was very ill with other medical conditions,''  
Netherland said, adding that the hospital suspects the disease 
contributed to the death, ``but was not the sole cause.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another unidentified patient died June 26, and Elizabeth M. Cox,  
79, died on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials believe a hot water tank at the hospital was the  
probable source of the bacteria. Water samples taken from the tank 
and pipes tested positive for the bacteria. The hospital's water 
system has since been flushed with 150-degree water and 
decontaminated with a chlorine solution. Results of new tests are 
expected this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Health officials said Friday that additional cases were possible  
because the incubation period for the disease is two to 10 days. 
</P>
<P>
	The hospital has been calling more than 400 recent patients to  
ask them about symptoms and offer free testing if needed. 
</P>
<P>
	Legionnaires' is a form of pneumonia caused by a common bacteria  
often found in air conditioning cooling towers, water tanks, 
whirlpool spas and humidifiers. The disease takes its name from a 
deadly outbreak at the Pennsylvania American Legion convention held 
in Philadelphia in July 1976. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990712.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 17:50:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 5 Hospitalized After Drinking Drug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKE CITY, Mich. (AP) -- Five teen-agers went into convulsions  
and lapsed into comas after sharing a drink that had been laced 
with the powerful party drug GHB, authorities said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The three boys and two girls, ages 13 to 17, were hospitalized  
after falling ill at a home Sunday night. They had regained 
consciousness by Monday night but were expected to remain 
hospitalized until at least Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	State police said a suspect believed to be involved in  
distributing the drug has been taken into custody on unrelated 
charges. 
</P>
<P>
	GHB acts as a powerful depressant that lasts several hours. Its  
popularity has increased in dance clubs and parties because in 
small doses, it can induce relaxation and euphoria. 
</P>
<P>
	The Drug Enforcement Administration has linked GHB to 32 deaths  
and 3,500 overdoses since 1990. It also has been associated with 
cases of sexual assault, in part because it is odorless and 
practically colorless. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
