<DOCNO> APW19990712.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 15:50:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Female Kicker's Lawsuit Reinstated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- A federal appeals court Monday reinstated  
the sex discrimination lawsuit of a female place-kicker who was cut 
from Duke's football team in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	A three-judge panel of the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals  
ruled that Heather Sue Mercer is entitled to a trial on her claim 
that Duke violated Title IX of the Education Amendments Act of 
1972, which prohibits discrimination on the basis of gender in 
educational programs receiving federal funds. 
</P>
<P>
	The unanimous decision reversed a ruling by U.S. District Judge  
N. Carlton Tilley Jr. of Durham, who said Duke and coach Fred 
Goldsmith had the right to prevent a female from participating in a 
contact sport under a Title IX subsection. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke University spokesman Al Rossiter said it would be  
inappropriate for the university to comment on the decision until 
the school's attorneys have read the opinion. 
</P>
<P>
	Mercer kicked the winning 28-yard field goal in Duke's 1995  
Blue-White intrasquad game, and Goldsmith told reporters she had 
made the team. She was listed on the team's official roster and 
pictured in the Duke football yearbook. 
</P>
<P>
	However, she never kicked in a game. She claims in her lawsuit  
that Goldsmith made offensive comments to her, including asking why 
she didn't prefer to participate in beauty pageants rather than 
football. 
</P>
<P>
	Mercer claims Goldsmith's decision to cut her from the team at  
the beginning of the 1996 season was based on gender because other, 
less qualified walk-on kickers were allowed to remain on the team. 
</P>
<P>
	The appeals court agreed that Duke had a right to bar Mercer  
from a contact sport. However, the court said that once she was 
allowed to participate, the university could not discriminate 
against her. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
