<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IBM Buys Sequent for $810 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- IBM is buying Sequent Computer Systems Inc., a  
struggling maker of powerful business computers, in a $810 million 
deal that helps fill a hole in IBM's product line for handling 
heavy duty corporate computing. 
</P>
<P>
	Sequent, though far smaller than Big Blue, is a leading seller  
of brawny machines that run on Intel computer chips, expected to be 
the next corporate computing trend. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM uses its own chips as the brains of powerful mainframe  
computers, which process everything from millions of bank 
transactions to inventories. It plans to use Sequent's technology 
to sell networked ``server'' machines that are an inexpensive and 
flexible substitute to mainframes. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Intel chips are not widely used to power these server  
machines, that will start to change next year, when the No. 1 chip 
maker releases a long-awaited next-generation chip known as Merced. 
</P>
<P>
	Merced is intended to work with high-end business machines that  
run either Unix -- the traditional operating system for such 
computers -- or Microsoft's Windows NT, which is rapidly gaining 
market share. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM and other large computer makers, including Hewlett-Packard  
Corp. and Compaq Computer Corp., are racing to adapt their machines 
to Merced. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM, which is hedging its bets, plans to simultaneously promote  
existing machines based on its own proprietary chip technology. 
Some of these machines will appeal to corporate customers seeking 
extremely powerful computers, while Intel-based computers will 
feature more flexibility. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM, based in Armonk, N.Y., hopes to greatly increase sales of  
Sequent machines by pitching them through its giant sales force. 
IBM plans to sell Sequent's computers as well as integrate 
Sequent's technology into its own machines. Beaverton, Ore.-based 
Sequent has about 2,500 employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite Sequent's leading technology, the company has succeeded  
only in attracting a handful of major corporate customers. Its 
financial results have been viewed by Wall Street as mediocre, 
losing $53 million last year on sales of $784 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Sequent's share of the server market has been declining, said  
Amir Ahari, an analyst at researcher International Data Corp. 
``They've been struggling for a while.'' 
</P>
<P>
	IBM's interest in buying Sequent was sparked by an ongoing  
alliance it has with Sequent and software maker Santa Cruz 
Operation Inc. to produce a new version of the Unix operating 
system for the Merced chip. 
</P>
<P>
	Sequent chief executive Casey Powell, who will continue to head  
up Sequent's operations under IBM, founded the company in 1983 
after heading Intel's microprocessor operations. Sequent will be 
folded into IBM's more than $12 billion server division, headed by 
IBM senior vice president Robert Stephenson. 
</P>
<P>
	``This merger allows us the clout of a very large company,''  
Powell said. ``Combined with the size and clout of IBM, we'll be a 
force to reckon with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	IBM will pay $18 cash for each of Sequent's outstanding shares,  
plus additional cash. It hopes to complete the transaction this 
summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Sequent's stock, which had been selling for about $14 in June,  
has been rising sharply since rumors of IBM's interest recently hit 
the market. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM shares rose 43 3/4 cents a share at $137.81 1/4 on the New York  
Stock Exchange. Sequent's shares fell 15 5/8 cents a share at $17.28 1/8 
on the Nasdaq Stock Market. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
