<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Sues Toyota, Seeks $58.5B Fine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government accused Toyota on Monday of  
putting faulty smog-control computers on 2.2 million 1996-1998 
vehicles and sought to have the computers repaired and the company 
fined up to $58.5 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	On behalf of the Environmental Protection Agency, the Justice  
Department filed a civil lawsuit against the automaker's U.S. 
subsidiary under the Clean Air Act in U.S. District Court here 
after Toyota rejected a government settlement offer last week that 
might have cost it $100 million in civil fines. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese-owned Toyota company is the first automaker that  
has refused to settle a Clean Air Act case with the government. 
Since 1995, Cadillac, Honda, Ford and seven heavy-duty diesel 
engine makers have reached multimillion-dollar Clean Air Act 
settlements with the government. 
</P>
<P>
	The government always seeks up to the maximum civil penalty the  
act allows but doesn't expect or get that much. ``We're asking for 
an appropriate penalty and notifying the court that the parameters 
are somewhere between zero and $58 billion,'' said Joel Gross, 
chief of Justice's environmental enforcement section. The law 
allows the judge to take into account a company's economic gain 
from the violation, its history of compliance and remedies and 
whether a fine would allow a company to stay in business. 
</P>
<P>
	In this case, the penalty is $25,000 per car sold before Jan.  
31, 1997, and $27,500 for each car sold after that date. The 
government did not know the exact dates on which the 1997 model 
vehicles were sold -- 857,620 of the 2.2 million total -- so the top 
penalty was between $56.4 billion and $58.5 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The government also did not specify what actions would be  
necessary to remedy the problem on existing cars. Justice 
officials, requesting anonymity, said they could involve extension 
of warranties so the devices could be replaced or repaired for free 
over a longer period, other repairs or even a recall of the cars 
for repairs. 
</P>
<P>
	In a June 1998 settlement with Honda, which involved  
computerized emission monitors on 1.7 million cars, the automaker 
extended the emissions systems warranty to 14 years or 150,000 
miles, offered a free tune-up after 75,000 miles and paid a $17.1 
million civil penalty. Officials said the warranty and repairs 
could cost Honda up to $267 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Estimates for the cost of repairing or replacing all the Toyota  
smog-control computers range up to $550 million. 
</P>
<P>
	At Toyota Motor Sales USA, the company's U.S. subsidiary in  
Torrance, Calif., Senior Vice President Jim Olson said Monday, 
``Toyota continues to be disappointed that despite our vehicles 
having the best in-use emission performance in the industry, this 
matter has not yet been resolved in a mutually agreeable manner.'' 
He argued that regulators had reinterpreted their rules after 
Toyota's equipment was approved. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice officials wanted to file the lawsuit early this week so  
the federal case would be available to the California. The state's 
Office of Administrative Hearings on Monday began what is expected 
to be a weeks-long hearing on California's demand that Toyota 
repair 330,000 vehicles sold there with the same computer problems, 
said California Air Resources Board spokesman Jerry Martin. 
California's air standards are tougher than the national standards. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit covered the three model years of Toyota Camrys,  
Avalons, Corollas, Tercels and Paseos; Lexus cars; Sienna minivans; 
4Runner and RAV4 sport utility vehicles, and Tacoma and T100 
trucks. 
</P>
<P>
	The government alleged that Toyota's on-board computerized  
emission monitors would allow escape of increased hydrocarbon vapor 
without setting off a dashboard warning light for the driver. These 
emissions contribute to ground-level ozone, also known as smog, 
which can cause lung and respiratory problems, especially in the 
elderly and children. Ozone near the ground also is harmful to 
crops and plants. 
</P>
<P>
	``Companies that take short cuts with their vehicle pollution  
control systems shortchange the consumer and our environment,'' 
said Assistant Attorney General Lois J. Schiffer. ``We will hold 
them accountable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When the on-board monitors don't work, ``the government's and  
the state's ability to protect the public health and the 
environment is seriously jeopardized,'' said Assistant EPA 
Administrator Steven A. Herman. 
</P>
<P>
	The system is designed to detect leaks and light a dashboard  
warning light, such as ``check engine'' or ``service engine soon.'' 
The government said the computers were not properly programmed and 
the government was not advised of the programming in certifications 
filed for the vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	The California Air Resources Board approved the computers based  
on computer simulations, but they failed to meet California or 
federal standards in field tests in the fall of 1997. Federal 
regulators joined the dispute in January. 
</P>
<P>
	Toyota claims its computers met all guidelines in place when  
they were certified but the state changed the rules afterward. 
</P>
<P>
	Last October, the seven diesel engine makers agreed to spend  
nearly $1 billion, including an $83.4 million civil penalty, to 
settle charges they installed illegal software to disable emission 
controls. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to Honda's settlement, Ford in June 1998 agreed to  
pay $7.8 million for selling vehicles with a device that defeated 
emission controls. In 1995, General Motors settled for $45 million 
over defeat devices on 500,000 Cadillacs. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
