<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Fall in Midday Trading / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar edged lower against the yen in Tuesday  
morning trading, after Japan's finance minister said the government 
will not take ``extreme'' action in foreign exchange markets. 
Japanese stocks were little changed. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 122.12 yen in late morning trading, down 0.02  
yen from late Monday in Tokyo and also below its late New York 
level of 122.23 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 17.18 points,  
or 0.09 percent, to 18,257.00 points at the end of morning trading. 
On Monday, the average closed up 336.45 points, or 1.88 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 3.04 points, or 0.20 percent, to 1,487.15 
points. The TOPIX closed up 19.71 points, or 1.35 percent, the day 
before. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar inched lower after Finance  
Minister Kiichi Miyazawa said Tokyo doesn't intend to take 
``extreme'' action. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of Japan has repeatedly intervened in recent weeks to  
weaken the yen against the dollar in an attempt to help the 
nation's economic recover from a deep recession. But traders say 
the government likely is comfortable with the current dollar-yen 
exchange rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, should the dollar fall to 121.80 yen, the Bank of Japan  
may try to push the U.S. currency back up past 123.00 yen, said one 
Tokyo trader. 
</P>
<P>
	A higher yen makes Japanese exports more expensive abroad and  
thus less competitive, reducing dollar-denominated earnings of 
export-oriented Japanese companies. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 123.86 yen, down  
from 124.10 yen late Monday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, the Nikkei average fell slightly on  
profit-taking following the previous day's surge. The biggest 
declines were in high technology sectors. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York Monday, the Dow Jones industrial average edged up  
7.28 points to 11,200.98. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese  
government bond fell to 1.6200 percent from Monday's finish of 
1.6400 percent, driving its price up to 101.57 yen from 101.39 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
