<HEADLINE> 'Dawson's Creek' Cited by Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Parents Television Council apparently has a  
love-hate relationship with the WB network. 
</P>
<P>
	The conservative watchdog group cited two shows on the WB --  
``7th Heaven'' and ``Dawson's Creek'' -- as the best and worst 
television programs for families. 
</P>
<P>
	The teen-aged soap ``Dawson's Creek,'' which stars heartthrob  
James Van Der Beek, was cited by the council as the most offensive 
show on network television for the second year in a row. 
</P>
<P>
	``The show features an almost obsessive focus on premarital  
sexual activity,'' the council said. The group also criticizes 
``Dawson's Creek'' for its storyline about a teen-aged character 
revealing his homosexuality. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other hand, the WB's ``7th Heaven'' demonstrates the  
drawing power of family-friendly programming, the organization said 
Monday. Its lead character, a minister father, offers advice that 
most viewers can relate to, the council said. 
  	   	
</P>
