<DOCNO> APW19990712.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 01:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> State of Care Eyed at Nursing-homes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Sheryl Lee Lynch considered her father  
a gentleman, a hero and her best friend -- someone far different 
from the nursing-home patient who screamed in pain and didn't 
recognize her. 
</P>
<P>
	Russell Lee's health declined so sharply during a six-week stay  
at a ManorCare Health Services nursing home that Lynch and her 
sister moved him to another facility, where he died a short time 
later. 
</P>
<P>
	Their wrongful-death lawsuit against ManorCare provides a  
glimpse into an industry that needs far tougher state oversight, 
advocates for the elderly say. 
</P>
<P>
	``The laws aren't being enforced,'' said Carole Herman,  
president of the Foundation Aiding The Elderly. 
</P>
<P>
	Lynch and her sister, Linda Braas, contended inadequate care at  
the Citrus Heights nursing home in 1996 caused weight loss, bed 
sores and blood poisoning that led to the death of their 
80-year-old father, Russell Lee. 
</P>
<P>
	During trial last month, ManorCare agreed to settle the case for  
$1 million. It did not admit any wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't really want to comment on it,'' said Julie Beckert of  
ManorCare's parent company, HCR Manor Care Inc. in Toledo, Ohio, 
said. ``Our feeling is that it's better to use our company's 
resources for quality care than prove our innocence in this case 
because it's so costly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the problems Lee's daughters cited are similar to those  
reported last summer by federal officials who reviewed 1993 
California nursing home deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 62 nursing home deaths that year, 34 involved ``care that  
was unacceptable and that sometimes endangered their health and 
safety,'' the General Accounting Office study said. 
</P>
<P>
	The GAO found problems such as ``inadequate intervention by the  
nursing home to prevent dramatic, unplanned weight loss and failure 
to properly treat pressure sores that became infected and toxic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Between 1995 and 1998, about one-third of California's nursing  
homes were cited for ``serious or potentially life-threatening care 
problems,'' but state regulators were lenient toward many, the GAO 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Most, except the worst offenders, were given a month to correct  
deficiencies, without penalties. 
</P>
<P>
	State officials defended their regulatory record.  
</P>
<P>
	Health Services Department spokeswoman Lea Brooks said about 290  
inspectors scrutinize more than 6,000 health facilities an average 
of once a year, one-fourth of them nursing homes. 
</P>
<P>
	Brenda Klutz, Health Services' deputy director of licensing and  
certification, said her unit stepped up its efforts last year, 
focusing on the most troubled of California's 1,498 nursing homes. 
About 5,500 complaints were filed against the homes, which house 
more than 150,000 patients. 
</P>
<P>
	The state issued 792 citations to 460 nursing homes last year,  
resulting in more than $2.6 million in fines. Fines range from $100 
for infractions such as cold food to $25,000 for conditions that 
lead directly to a death. 
</P>
<P>
	But due to appeals and other delays, not all fines have been  
paid, Brooks said. She did not know how many fines were owed. 
</P>
<P>
	Assemblyman Kevin Shelley believes the state's oversight needs  
an overhaul. He said he looked into nursing homes after his mother 
suffered a stroke. 
</P>
<P>
	``I visited about 20 to 30 nursing homes,'' Shelley said. ``I  
was appalled at what I found -- patients strapped into wheelchairs 
in dark hallways festering in their own urine, or immobilized in 
bed, pushing call buttons for hours and nobody responding.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shelley instead pays someone to take care of his mother at home.  
</P>
<P>
	The San Francisco Democrat has proposed a bill before the state  
Senate that would boost penalties for the most serious violations 
to $100,000, reduce the patient load for nurses' aides and require 
more training. 
</P>
<P>
	The nursing home industry opposes the bill.  
</P>
<P>
	``We'd like to see enforcement target the consistently  
problematic facilities rather than painting the entire industry 
with that brush,'' said Gary Macomber, president of the California 
Association of Health Facilities. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
