<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mark at 10-Yr Low Vs. Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The euro fell closer to parity with the dollar  
Monday, sinking to yet another low as weak industrial production 
figures from Germany indicated that Europe's stagnant economy is 
not recovering as quickly as hoped. 
</P>
<P>
	The Swiss franc and German mark both fell to 10-year lows  
against the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	But the dollar fell against the Japanese yen. Traders were  
hesitant to take the dollar higher against the yen because Japan's 
central bank -- in an attempt to further the economy's recovery from 
a deep recession -- has repeatedly intervened in recent weeks to 
weaken the yen against the dollar and the euro. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0148, down  
from $1.0176 late Friday. During trading, the euro fell to $1.0112, 
below the previous low of $1.0146, which was set during trading 
Thursday. The dollar also was quoted at 122.23 Japanese yen, down 
from 122.38. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro fell as Germany reported industrial production  
unexpectedly fell 0.2 percent in May from April. Analysts had 
expected output to rise. 
</P>
<P>
	``The euro started to sink lower'' when the disappointing  
figures were released, said Jay Bryson, an international economist 
at First Union Capital Markets in Charlotte, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	Germany has the third-largest economy in the world and is the  
engine that moves the 11 European countries using the euro to 
represent its currency. Euro-region countries are stagnating and a 
fall in German economic data brings ``into question when the 
European economies are turning the corner,'' Bryson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The question on everybody's mind is when do we hit parity,''  
with one euro equaling $1, Bryson said; the euro has fallen since 
it began trading at $1.1668 on Jan. 4. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.5830 Swiss francs, up from  
1.5793, and 1.4796 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4733. The British 
pound rose to $1.5559 from $1.5480. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on the euro rate in late New York trading, the dollar was 
worth 1.9290 German marks, up from 1.9220; and 6.4609 French 
francs, up from 6.4475. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
