<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Senate Opens HMO Debate  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate today began to debate HMO reforms  
with both sides supporting their own versions of a patients' ``bill 
of rights.'' With a final vote set for Thursday, majority 
Republicans are all but certain to pass their legislation, 
Democrats are siding with patients frustrated with restrictive HMO 
rules. Republicans are appealing to Americans bothered by rising 
health care costs. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Sues Toyota Over Smog Computers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The federal government today accused Toyota of  
putting faulty smog-controls on 2.2 million 1996-1998 vehicles and 
sought to have the computers repaired and the company fined up to 
$58.5 billion. On behalf of the Environmental Protection Agency, 
the Justice Department filed a civil lawsuit against the 
automaker's U.S. subsidiary. Toyota had rejected a settlement offer 
that might have cost it $100 million in fines. 

</P>
<P>
	Sen. Smith Set To Quit GOP  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. Bob Smith of New Hampshire is expected to  
quit the GOP and run for president under a third party's banner. 
Campaign 2000 rivals Gary Bauer and Patrick Buchanan defended 
Smith's decision to bolt the party and blamed the Republicans for 
the defection, saying the GOP has abandoned conservative ideas. 

</P>
<P>
	Gore Details Anti-Crime Plans  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore vowed today that he would  
be a president who's tough on crime. Gore, the front-runner for the 
Democratic nomination in 2000, unveiled his anti-crime agenda. It 
includes photo licenses for all new handgun owners, a ban on cheap 
handguns and a constitutional amendment for victims' rights. His 
plan also calls for more federal money for the court system and a 
requirement that criminal defendants pledge to get off drugs if 
they want to stay out of jail. 

</P>
<P>
	Seven Found Shot to Death in Atlanta  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Five adults and two children were found shot to  
death in an Atlanta house today. An 11-year-old boy survived the 
shootings. He was wounded, but hid in a closet for several hours. 
The motive for the shootings was unclear, police said. They said it 
was possible that one person killed the others and then committed 
suicide. 

</P>
<P>
	Khrushchev's Son Becomes US Citizen  
</P>
<P>
	PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- Nikita Khrushchev's son became a U.S.  
citizen today, choosing democracy 40 years after his father vowed 
as Russia's leader that communism would surpass the American way of 
life. ``I'm feeling like a newborn. It's the beginning of a new 
life,'' the 64-year-old Sergei Khrushchev said after taking the 
oath of citizenship inside a Roman Catholic school auditorium. At 
his side was his wife, Valentina Golenko, who also took the oath to 
defend the United States. 

</P>
<P>
	Two Arrested in U.S. Embassy Bombings  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- As the duo made its first British court  
appearance, a prosecutor said today that fingerprint evidence links 
two Egyptians to a conspiracy with Osama bin Laden to kill 
Americans in the bombings of U.S. embassies in Africa. Ibrahim 
Hussein Abdel Hadi Eidarous, 42, and Adel Mohanned Abdul Almagid 
Bary, 39, were arrested yesterday. Bin Laden is accused by the 
United States of masterminding the blasts in Nairobi, Kenya, and 
Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, on Aug. 7, 1998, that killed 224. 

</P>
<P>
	Disney Acquires Rest of Infoseek  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Walt Disney Co. is taking over Infoseek in  
an effort to consolidate its online operations and boost its 
entertainment brands in cyberspace. Disney is merging all of its 
Internet operations together with Infoseek to form a new company 
called go.com. ``We're taking the Disney brand and letting it 
evolve into the next century,'' said chairman Michael Eisner about 
the deal. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Up 7.28 Points  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow industrials edged to another record high  
today, but most stocks fell in cautious trading before the 
impending flood of quarterly reports. The Dow ended at 11,200.98, 
up 7.28. On the NYSE, losers led gainers 1,624-1,381. It was the 
third record high close in four sessions for the Dow, which has now 
gained more than 2,000 points, or 22 percent, in 1999. But the 
Nasdaq fell 2.63 to 2,790.44. 

</P>
<P>
	World Cup Champs on U.S. Tour  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The champion U.S. women's soccer team today  
visited New York, soaking up acclaim for their World Cup victory 
over China. They launched a tour of network TV shows from ``Good 
Morning America'' and ``Today'' to CNN and Fox News Channel. A 
midtown rally was set for tomorrow. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER  

  	   	
</P>
