<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baxter Creates Cardiovascular Unit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DEERFIELD, Ill. (AP) -- Baxter International Inc. is spinning off  
to shareholders its $1 billion cardiovascular business to focus on 
its blood, medical products and kidney systems business. 
</P>
<P>
	Details of the tax-free spinoff, including the new company's  
name, have yet to be determined, Baxter said in a statement Monday. 
The transaction is expected to close by mid-2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The news drove shares of Baxter up $3.31 1/4, or 5 percent, to  
close at $64.18 3/4 on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of Baxter's cardiovascular products, including heart-valve  
therapies, cardiac monitoring systems and mechanical cardiac-assist 
systems, have market leading positions. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am very excited about creating one of the world's largest  
companies focused on advanced cardiovascular disease,'' said Harry 
M. Jansen Kraemer, Jr., Baxter's president and chief executive. 
``As separate entities, both companies will be more competitive and 
have greater financial flexibility to invest and grow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Michael A. Mussallem, Baxter group vice president, will become  
chief executive of the new company, which will be based in Irvine, 
Calif. Mussallem has managed Baxter's cardiovascular business since 
1995. 
</P>
<P>
	With manufacturing operations in North America, Japan, Europe  
and Latin America, Baxter's cardiovascular operation generates more 
than 40 percent of its sales outside of the United States. Of 
Baxter's 42,000 employees, 6,000 work in its cardiovascular 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, some former Baxter executives will be leading a  
related company called LifeStream International LLC, First Chicago 
Equity Capital and Garrett Capital Advisors announced today. 
</P>
<P>
	The company will be formed from the acquisitions of the  
cardiopulmonary products division of C.R. Bard Inc., assets of the 
cardiosurgery business of Minntech Corp. and Surgimedics Inc. 
Details of the acquisitions were not disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert W. Kleinert Jr. will become LifeStream International's  
president and chief executive after the deal closes in August, the 
partnership said in a statement. Kleinert has been executive vice 
president of Dade Behring Inc. He held the same position at Dade 
International from 1994 to 1997 and before that held several 
executive positions with Baxter, including president of Clintec 
Nutrition, and Baxter Diagnostics in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Products in the LifeStream portfolio will include oxygenators,  
catheters and blood filters and reservoirs. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
