<HEADLINE> Chief Wants Four Chicago Cops Fired </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Chicago's police superintendent on Monday  
recommended the firing of four officers for their part in the fatal 
shooting of an unarmed black woman. 
</P>
<P>
	The officers will be suspended 30 days without pay while the  
police board takes up the recommendation. 
</P>
<P>
	LaTanya Haggerty, 26, was a passenger in a car involved in a  
police chase on June 4 when she was shot and killed. Investigators 
said an officer mistook her cellular phone for a gun. 
</P>
<P>
	Superintendent Terry Hillard said the officers ignored a  
supervisor's order to call off the chase, fired without 
justification and failed to notify a supervisor promptly that shots 
had been fired. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am convinced department rules and regulation were  
intentionally ignored and the four officers involved must be held 
accountable for those actions,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He declined to release the officers' names.  
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Monday, protesters called for criminal charges.  
</P>
<P>
	Civil rights leaders and members of the clergy have staged  
several protests since the recent fatal shootings of Ms. Haggerty 
and an unarmed black man, a 22-year-old Northwestern University 
football player. 
</P>
<P>
	The officers who fired the fatal shots in both cases are black,  
but black leaders have said that the shootings may reflect racism 
on the police force. They have argued that black officers have 
incorporated the racist attitudes of their white colleagues. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Nolan, president of the Chicago chapter of the Fraternal  
Order of Police, called Hillard's decision a ``foregone 
conclusion'' in light of public pressure to blame someone for the 
shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're disappointed in it, and we'll do whatever we can to help  
the officers ... keep their jobs,'' Nolan told CLTV in Chicago. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
