<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sen. Hatch Begins White House Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- Sen. Orrin Hatch acknowledged Monday that  
he faced long odds in his just-started presidential campaign, but 
predicted he could beat the Republican front-runner, George W. 
Bush, by raising at least $12 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no question that I've been in tougher circumstances,  
no question that I've had to fight the establishment in Washington 
and there's no question I've been able to bring people together,'' 
he said on his first campaign swing through New Hampshire, which 
holds the nation's first primary. 
</P>
<P>
	In appearances at a church daycare center and a dental insurance  
company, Hatch promoted himself as the candidate of the people. 
</P>
<P>
	Describing himself as the more experienced candidate, Hatch said  
he could beat the Texas governor with only $12 million to $15 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	The Utah senator said he hopes to match Bush's $36 million war  
chest by having 1 million people contribute $36 apiece to his 
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	With only four years as a governor, Bush would be led by party  
``elites'' if he made it to the White House, Hatch said. 
Republicans should require Bush to defend his positions instead of 
bowing to the Bush ``juggernaut,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch noted his own experience, including his past chairmanship  
of the Senate Labor Committee and his current chairmanship of the 
Judiciary Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's lack of experience would make him vulnerable in a general  
election, and a Democrat victory would cause great harm to the 
country, Hatch said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It'll take us 50 years to get this country back'' if a  
Democrat gets to nominate Supreme Court justices, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch said conservative battles on important issues -- like  
affirmative action, the death penalty and state's rights -- would be 
lost. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it'll lead to a breakdown in the economy. I think  
it'll lead to a lot of changes in the federal government -- a 
federal government triumph in this country over all the states,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Separating himself from the other contenders, Hatch said he grew  
up in poverty, unlike the privileged lives of Bush, Vice President 
Al Gore and Democrat Bill Bradley. He said his parents lost their 
home shortly after his birth, and he worked as a janitor to pay his 
way through college. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch is very respected, but is a gamble at this point because  
he is untested in this kind of race, said Republican media 
consultant Patrick Griffin. 
</P>
<P>
	``The slippery snow and ice of Iowa and New Hampshire can be  
very unkind, even to the most genteel members of the U.S. Senate,'' 
Griffin said. ``There's a a big difference running for Senate in 
Utah and being the party's nominee for president.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
