<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.Y. Killer Gets Death Penalty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIVERHEAD, N.Y. (AP) -- A former postal worker today became the  
first person to be sentenced to death under the ``serial killer'' 
provision of New York's death penalty law. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Shulman, 45, was convicted in March of bludgeoning three  
women to death. 
</P>
<P>
	A judge sentenced him under a provision in the 1995 death  
penalty law that calls for the execution of someone who kills three 
or more people within a two-year period as part of a common plan or 
in a similar fashion. 
</P>
<P>
	Only two other people have been sentenced to death in New York  
since it reinstated the death penalty. Both are appealing their 
cases. 
</P>
<P>
	Shulman, a former postal worker in the Long Island village of  
Hicksville, was convicted of killing three women whose bodies were 
found in 1994 and 1995. He is awaiting trial in the killings of two 
other women. 
</P>
<P>
	His lawyer argued that Shulman's life should be spared because  
he suffers from depression and has a weak grasp of reality. 
</P>
<P>
	``God knows I didn't do this,'' Shulman said in court Monday.  
``That gives me peace of mind.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
