<HEADLINE> Garciaparra To Play Despite Injury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Nomar Garciaparra has missed the last nine games  
with a groin injury, but he won't be a spectator for Tuesday 
night's All-Star game. 
</P>
<P>
	The Boston Red Sox shortstop plans to start for the AL team in  
order to test his injury and play in front of his hometown fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's actually good for me,'' Boston's shortstop said Monday.  
``It will help me get ready so I can play Thursday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's when the Red Sox resume their season with the opener of a  
three-game series against Philadelphia. But first Garciaparra plans 
to start for the AL. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday in Atlanta, he missed his ninth consecutive game with  
a strained left groin. He doesn't feel he's jeopardizing himself by 
playing Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've always said my team's first,'' said Garciaparra, third in  
the AL with a .366 batting average. ``I probably could have played 
yesterday (Sunday) and if we had a game today I probably would have 
played today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was unclear how long Garciaparra, batting second, would play.  
AL manager Joe Torre of the New York Yankees said he would consult 
with Boston manager Jimy Williams, one of his coaches. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't want to hurt anyone, but certainly he should get the  
recognition by playing,'' Torre said. 
</P>
<P>
	Garciaparra will play before his home fans at Fenway Park after  
winning the fan balloting with 1,089,974 votes. New York's Derek 
Jeter was second with 1,069,528. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's nice to be in any All-Star game,'' said Garciaparra, a  
backup as a rookie in 1997 but not picked last year. ``The fans 
here have always been great.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
