<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Quebecor Printing Acquiring US Firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) -- Quebecor Printing Inc., based in  
Montreal, will acquire World Color Press Inc. for $1.4 billion in 
cash and stock in a deal that will create the largest commercial 
printer in the world. World Color Press is headquartered in 
Greenwich. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined company, to be known as Quebecor World Inc., will  
serve customers in magazines, catalogs, books, retail inserts and 
circulars and direct mail printing. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the merger agreement announced today, a subsidiary of  
Quebecor Printing will acquire World Color Press through a tender 
offer to purchase World Color shares for $36.09 a share in cash or 
stock. 
</P>
<P>
	That represents a 30 percent premium over the average trading  
price of World Color shares since July 9. 
</P>
<P>
	In midday trading today on the New York Stock Exchange, World  
Color rose $4.68 3/4 a share, or 15.7 percent, to $34.50. 
</P>
<P>
	Quebecor Printing said about $840 million of the purchase price  
would be for cash and the rest for stock. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Quebecor is assuming $1.3 billion in World Color  
debt. 
</P>
<P>
	The World Color board has approved the merger by a unanimous  
vote and recommended acceptance of the offer by shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	The offer is subject to 50.1 percent of World Color shares being  
tendered to the offer and regulatory approvals. Both the tender 
offer and the merger are expected to be completed within four 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	Quebecor Printing is now the largest printer in Europe and the  
second-largest printer in North America and South America, with 
1998 annual revenues of $3.8 billion and 26,000 employees. 
</P>
<P>
	World Color is one of the leading commercial printers in the  
United States. The company has 16,000 employees and revenues of 
$2.5 billion in 1998. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
