<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Interest Rates Mixed in T-Bill Sale / T-Bills  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Interest rates on short-term Treasury  
securities were mixed in Monday's auction. 
</P>
<P>
	The Treasury Department sold $7.51 billion in three-month bills  
at a discount rate of 4.600 percent, up from 4.590 percent last 
week. An additional $7.51 billion was sold in six-month bills at a 
rate of 4.540 percent, down from 4.590 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-month rate was the highest since June 28, when the  
bills sold for 4.750 percent. The six-month rate was the lowest 
since May 10, when the rate was 4.510. 
</P>
<P>
	The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors  
-- 4.733 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling 
for $9,883.70 and 4.724 percent for a six-month bill selling for 
$9,770.50. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the  
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index 
for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, fell to 5.06 
percent last week from 5.11 percent the previous week. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
