<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	2 Arrested in U.S. Embassy Bombings  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Police have arrested two men in London in  
connection with the fatal bombings of two U.S. embassies in Africa 
last summer, authorities said. Ibrahim Hussein Abdel Hadi Eidarous, 
42, and Adel Mohanned Abdul Almagid Bary, 39, were due in court 
today to face charges they conspired with Saudi fugitive Osama bin 
Laden and his alleged terrorist network to kill Americans, Scotland 
Yard said. The men, who must appear today in Bow Street Magistrates 
Court, were arrested yesterday on an extradition warrant following 
a request from the United States. 

</P>
<P>
	Belfast Braces for Protestant March  
</P>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Protestant revelers blackened  
the sky with bonfires, played anti-Catholic tunes and set off 
booming fireworks that echoed through Belfast's otherwise empty 
streets today as Northern Ireland began its most tension-packed day 
of the year. An estimated 80,000 Protestant members of the Orange 
Order brotherhood planned to march today in several parades across 
Northern Ireland. Their official reason is to commemorate 
Protestant King William of Orange's battlefield triumph over the 
Catholic-led forces of James II three centuries ago, but in 
practice the mass mobilization is designed to demonstrate which 
side of the community is still stronger in this Protestant-majority 
state. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Troops Fired Upon in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA Yugoslavia (AP) -- U.S. Army troops have begun moving  
into Kosovo to take up peacekeeping duties from departing Marines 
who came under fire in separate incidents toward the end of their 
tour. No Americans were injured, and a spokesman for the U.S. 
forces said experience from other peacekeeping missions would stand 
the troops in good stead. Task Force 1-26, part of the Army's 1st 
Infantry Division based in Germany, is taking over from the 26th 
Marine Expeditionary Unit, initially deployed in southeastern 
Kosovo. The last Marines are expected to depart later this week. 

</P>
<P>
	Barak, Arafat Make Promise of Peace  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- With warm handshakes and peace declarations,  
Ehud Barak and Yasser Arafat postponed decisions on most of the 
outstanding Israeli-Palestinian issues until Barak completes a 
round of diplomatic forays. The Israeli prime minister and the 
Palestinian leader met yesterday at the Erez border crossing 
between Israel and the Gaza Strip -- their first summit since Barak 
won a landslide election victory in May. The whirlwind, 65-minute 
summit produced other gestures of friendship as well, accompanied 
by more mutual promises to pursue peace. 

</P>
<P>
	Gore To Unveil Anti-Crime Agenda  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore is proposing an  
anti-crime agenda that includes photo licenses for all new handgun 
owners, a ban on cheap handguns, increased spending on police 
training and a constitutional amendment for victims' rights, The 
Associated Press has learned. In one of his first major 
pronouncements since kicking off his presidential campaign last 
month, Gore will propose sweeping changes in the criminal justice 
system designed to get tough on criminals. 

</P>
<P>
	Japanese Nuclear Reactor Shut Down  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Engineers shut down a nuclear reactor in western  
Japan this morning after monitoring equipment showed it was leaking 
radioactive water, an official said. The No. 2 reactor operated by 
Japan Atomic Power Co. in Tsuruga, 200 miles west of Tokyo, was 
manually shut down, company spokesman Yoshikazu Murabe said. There 
was no danger of radioactivity escaping into the outside 
environment, he said. An estimated 50 tons of water used for 
cooling the inside of the reactor had leaked out, and the device 
was still leaking as of noon, ``but at a lower volume than 
earlier,'' Murabe said. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese Stock Prices Rise  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks closed higher today on robust gains  
in international blue-chip shares. The Nikkei gained 336.45 points 
to close at 18,274.18. 

</P>
<P>
	Marlins 3, Devil Rays 2  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Alex Fernandez pitched six scoreless innings for  
his 100th career victory, leading the Florida Marlins to a 3-2 win 
over the Tampa Bay Devil Rays, who found out earlier yesterday that 
Jose Canseco needed back surgery. Mark Kotsay, who entered the game 
in the second inning after Bruce Aven strained a hamstring, hit a 
two-run homer for the Marlins, 5-1 against their crosstate rival 
this year 

</P>
<P>
	Diamondbacks 7, Athletics 4  
</P>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Jay Bell hit his fifth career grand slam, earning  
a fan $1 million in the process, as the Arizona Diamondbacks 
overcame a three-run deficit to beat the Oakland Athletics 7-4 
yesterday. Matt Williams hit a two-run homer for Arizona, and David 
Dellucci was 2-for-3 with two doubles and an RBI. Bell's grand 
slam, on a full count with two outs in the sixth inning off Jimmy 
Haynes, broke a 3-3 tie. 

</P>
