<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coast Guard in Standoff With Cubans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- A floating standoff between a boatload of Cubans  
fleeing their country and Coast Guard vessels ended peacefully 
after four hours Monday when the Cubans willingly boarded a cutter. 
</P>
<P>
	Under U.S. policy, Cubans who reach land are allowed to stay  
while those picked up at sea are sent back. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday's standoff did not involve any forceful attempt to detain  
the refugees, Coast Guard spokesman Glenn Rosenholm said. 
</P>
<P>
	That was in contrast to a much tenser interdiction of 12 Cubans  
late Friday off an inlet in north Broward County. A Coast Guard 
cutter collided with the Cubans' boat, throwing all 12 refugees 
into the ocean. One woman drowned. The 11 survivors were taken to 
the U.S. Naval Station at Guantanamo, Cuba, on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Again Monday, the Cubans wanted to reach shore and freedom, but  
the Coast Guard said it couldn't let that happen, trying instead to 
persuade the group to board one of their ships. 
</P>
<P>
	Coast Guardsmen rode alongside the Cubans' 16-foot motorized  
wooden boat, urging them to stop. The standoff ended in 
international waters about 17 miles off Miami Beach when the 
vessel's motor stopped, possibly because of mechanical failure, and 
the boat began to drift. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubans, including 13 men and three women, then willingly  
boarded the cutter, Vachon said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
