<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990712.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 00:20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Doctor To Destroy Unclaimed Embryos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- The ad ran deep in the Sunday classifieds,  
between ``Can't Collect on a Judgment?'' and a notice seeking 
witnesses to a car accident. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you feel you have embryos or sperms stored with Arizona  
Institute of Reproductive Medicine,'' the ad began, ``please 
contact us immediately.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 12 lines of eye-straining type announced one fertility  
clinic's answer to a question with dizzying implications: What do 
you do with frozen embryos whose donors cannot be found? 
</P>
<P>
	``All unclaimed specimens will be destroyed as of July 15th,  
'99,'' the ad warned. 
</P>
<P>
	Experts say the notice, appearing in The Arizona Republic on  
June 27, may mark the first time that a fertility clinic in the 
United States has announced such plans. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Robert Tamis plans on retiring this year at age 69 and  
closing the clinic he founded. Clinic workers are contacting 
patients to offer this choice: Have the embryos implanted in the 
next six months, transferred to storage at another clinic or 
destroyed. 
</P>
<P>
	About 50 patients each have up to 16 frozen embryos at the  
clinic. Some 75 sperm samples also must be claimed. 
</P>
<P>
	Patient coordinator Kathy Fink cannot say how many of those  
patients cannot yet be located, but she hopes the ad will help 
locate all of them or lighten any potential legal liability for the 
clinic. 
</P>
<P>
	When the clinic first began freezing embryos in the mid-1980s,  
patients never even considered this dilemma. Several years ago, 
Tamis' clinic and others across the country began asking patients 
to sign contracts spelling out the ultimate fate of any unclaimed 
embryos. 
</P>
<P>
	``People don't stick around,'' Fink said. The clinic is in an  
all-out search, even for those who authorized the clinic to destroy 
their embryos under just such circumstances as these. 
</P>
<P>
	Some guidance does exist. In 1997, an ethics panel of the  
American Society for Reproductive Medicine concluded that clinics 
could destroy embryos unclaimed after five years. 
</P>
<P>
	But there's no legal precedent for Tamis' clinic. ``People keep  
saying someone has to do something about this,'' said Washington 
University law professor Rebecca Dresser, who helped develop the 
ASRM guidelines. ``It has to be resolved.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The embryos are created by fertilizing an egg with sperm in a  
laboratory and letting the fertilized egg grow for two days to 
about eight cells before being frozen and stored. When a woman 
wants to try to get pregnant, up to four embryos are thawed and 
inserted in her uterus. 
</P>
<P>
	Destroying embryos leaves some doctors, ethicists and patients  
aghast. 
</P>
<P>
	``If those were my embryos and they thawed them, I would flip  
out,'' said Denise Moreli, of New York City. She's had two 
unsuccessful embryo implantations. 
</P>
<P>
	Carmen Knaus, of Pittsburgh, has 22 embryos in cold storage.  
``Every fertility patient thinks of those embryos as their 
babies,'' she said. Like Moreli, she is a member of the online 
infertility support group called Child of My Dreams. 
</P>
<P>
	Knaus also has an agreement with her husband to donate embryos  
to other infertile couples. But other fertility patients have a 
hard time deciding what to do with frozen embryos after pregnancy 
efforts fail or a baby is born. 
</P>
<P>
	Such hesitation shows that patients instinctively know embryos  
are babies that need to be protected, said John Grabowski, a 
theologian at Catholic University in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	``Thawing them out and discarding them as if they were nothing  
more than excess lab material is morally troubling,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	To which Fink replied: ``That's why we're giving (patients) the  
choice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Patient privacy raises yet another concern. ``The patients may  
not have wished other people to be aware of those embryos,'' said 
Melvin Polkow, who heads the bioethics committee at Hackensack 
University Medical Center in Hackensack, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	The choices may be more theoretical than real. Other clinics are  
unlikely to take unclaimed embryos. In many cases, some date back 
to the 1980s and are so old that fertility experts say they have no 
chance of surviving inside a womb. 
</P>
<P>
	Though other doctors might hesitate, Dr. Jaroslav Marik of Los  
Angeles once accepted stored embryos from another retiring doctor. 
``There's always a liability issue if the freezing doesn't come out 
well,'' he said. ``It's an unfortunate consequence of the sue-happy 
population.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990712.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 10:39:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Propaganda War Heats Up in Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- With a weekend of heavy fighting between  
government troops and guerillas over, Colombia's propaganda war is 
heating up. 
</P>
<P>
	Armed services chief Gen. Fernando Tapias said today that the  
fighting -- some of the heaviest in memory -- had ended, and offered 
to show scores of dead rebels to the country's skeptical media. 
</P>
<P>
	``My information at this moment is that there are no  
(roadblocks) and no clashes in any part of the country,'' Tapias 
told Radionet Radio. 
</P>
<P>
	Television images showed police barracks, stores, banks and  
houses reduced to rubble by leftist rebels who attacked over the 
weekend with homemade explosives and armored vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	A dusk-to-dawn travel ban went into effect for the second  
straight night Sunday in nearly a third of the country's provinces. 
</P>
<P>
	And a funeral was held Sunday for dozens of soldiers killed in  
the action that touched off the weekend's bloodshed -- a guerrilla 
raid Thursday on an encampment in mountains south of Bogota. At 
least 59 soldiers and police died in the four days of fighting. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the military claimed a resounding victory.  
</P>
<P>
	In a statement faxed to the media late Sunday, the army said it  
had stiff-armed ``the biggest and most demented guerrilla offensive 
in the past 40 years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At least 202 rebels were killed in ``Operation Independence,''  
as the military labeled its response to ``terrorist'' attacks in 
two dozen locations across central and southeastern Colombia. Four 
battalions battled more than 1,000 guerrilla fighters of the 
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, known as FARC, the army 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	With few independent reports in the conflict zones, however, and  
rebel death counts notoriously difficult to verify, Colombians were 
left wondering what to make of the latest round of fighting. 
</P>
<P>
	Skeptics said tough talk from the government was no substitute  
for more convincing actions to reverse a three-year string of 
victories by the 15,000-member FARC, which now controls nearly 40 
percent of the countryside. 
</P>
<P>
	``We won't gain anything by covering our eyes and labeling them  
as terrorists,'' former national security adviser Alfredo Rangel 
wrote Sunday in El Tiempo newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Only by beefing up the military, and dealing unequivocal blows  
to the FARC on the battlefield can the rebel group be convinced to 
give up its 35-year struggle, Rangel said. 
</P>
<P>
	Peace negotiations between the FARC and President Andres  
Pastrana began in January, and many observers saw the group's 
latest onslaught as a show of force meant to influence a round of 
talks scheduled to begin July 20. 
</P>
<P>
	The heaviest of Sunday's fighting took place in Puerto Lleras, a  
town in Meta state 110 miles southeast of Bogota, where guerrillas 
attacked with armor-plated trucks. At the army's invitation, 
journalists headed in droves today to the town where the military 
claims nearly 100 FARC fighters died. 
</P>
<P>
	Rebels also targeted police stations in several regions.  
</P>
<P>
	In neighboring Caqueta state, police said two children were  
killed when a rebel bomb destroyed their house, which was next to 
the police station in the village of Valparaiso. 
</P>
<P>
	Two police died when rebels launched homemade bombs fashioned  
from gas canisters at a police barracks and a bank in Campamento, a 
town in the northwestern state of Antioquia. Television pictures 
showed houses and stores reduced to rubble by the crude but deadly 
bombs. A third officer was killed in a FARC drive-by shooting near 
Bogota. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of rebels had police pinned down Sunday night in two  
other southern towns, Puerto Rico and Doncello, with army 
reinforcements yet to arrive, said the national police commander, 
Gen. Rosso Jose Serrano. 
</P>
<P>
	About 60 travelers were reported held since early Sunday at a  
rebel roadblock on a highway near Pasto, capital of the state of 
Narino, 330 miles southwest of Bogota. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990712.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 10:39:02 </DATE_TIME>
