<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 08:20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> World Cup Champs on Whirlwind Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- America's newest golden girls -- the United  
States' winning World Cup women's soccer team -- used whirlwind TV 
appearances today to spread the message that professional women 
athletes are here to stay. 
</P>
<P>
	The extraordinary attention did not surprise midfielder Julie  
Foudy. ``We've always said this team is America's best kept 
secret,'' Foudy said on NBC's ``Today'' show. ``So finally the 
secret is out!'' 
</P>
<P>
	The team, minus Michelle Akers who was injured in Saturday's  
game, also appeared on ABC's ``Good Morning America,'' with their 
World Cup trophy in tow. 
</P>
<P>
	Several young girls were in the crowd sporting replicas of Mia  
Hamm's No. 9 jersey. The team signed soccer balls and encouraged 
young fans not to give up in fulfilling their ambitions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were those girls at one time and they can be there, too,''  
Hamm said. ``Whatever they want to be, whatever they dream to be, 
they can do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Goalie Briana Scurry said she relished her position as a role  
model for young black girls and said she planned to hold some inner 
city soccer clinics to get more black boys and girls involved in 
the sport. 
</P>
<P>
	Showered with confetti and praise on Sunday in Los Angeles, the  
team took its victory laps at Disneyland and at a sweltering 
downtown rally where -- this time at least -- nobody took their shirt 
off. 
</P>
<P>
	The World Cup winners rubbed elbows with Mickey and Minnie Mouse  
and were pelted with confetti as they rode a float down 
Disneyland's Main Street. 
</P>
<P>
	Then it was on to the Los Angeles Convention Center, where  
several hundred fans in red, white and blue seemed unfazed by the 
95-degree heat. One fan held a sign that read: ``Thank You Title 
IX.'' That refers to the 1972 federal law that forced schools to 
provide females with the same sports opportunities as males. 
</P>
<P>
	At the outdoor Los Angeles rally, Foudy ran to the microphone  
and raised her arms in triumph. 
</P>
<P>
	``What's up L.A.?'' she said. ``You guys are awesome!''  
</P>
<P>
	She introduced her teammates one by one, and the cheering  
swelled when she got to Scurry and Brandi Chastain -- described by 
Foudy as ``a woman who has the uncanny knack for taking her clothes 
off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chastain shed her jersey after kicking the winning goal in  
Saturday's victory over China. She previously posed in the buff -- 
carrying a strategically placed soccer ball -- for Gear magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if you'll see any more of that,'' Chastain said.  
``But I'm glad I did it. It was fun and if it brought attention to 
soccer, that's great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She had blamed the euphoria of victory for the impromptu baring  
of her sports bra. But Foudy didn't let her off that easily. 
</P>
<P>
	``She says `temporary insanity,' but who believes that?'' Foudy  
yelled to the crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	Players strode onto the stage wearing white World Cup champion  
T-shirts, gold medals around their necks and smiles on their faces. 
</P>
<P>
	They had more than one reason to be happy -- the Women's World  
Cup Organizing Committee announced Sunday that it would make a 
$750,000 contribution to the tournament's prize money. 
</P>
<P>
	The players already have been paid between $25,000 and $45,000  
each, but their $12,500 bonuses for winning the final were 
increased between $40,000 and $50,000 each. 
</P>
<P>
	Chastain said that, when she was preparing for the final kick of  
the game, she tried ``not to look the goalkeeper in the eyes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``She has a way of making you feel uncomfortable when you do  
that,'' Chastain said. 
</P>
<P>
	And when the ball hit the net?  
</P>
<P>
	``It can't be described,'' she said. ``Everything was  
slow-motion up until then, and you feel like you're in total 
control of everything. Then it's gone and you have no control of 
anything at all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Scurry greeted fans by thanking young soccer players who  
traveled from around the country to attend the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``You guys have been watching us for years, making the drive or  
trek to come out here. We appreciate all of your support. We love 
all of you,'' said Scurry, introduced by Foudy simply as ``the 
woman on goal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The crowd peppered Scurry with good-natured boos when she ended  
her speech by quipping, ``I have to scurry off and do some more 
events.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Come on!'' she replied. ``That was a good one.''  
</P>
<P>
	Hamm did not speak, but clutched the World Cup trophy in her  
hands and occasionally snapped photos of the cheering crowd and the 
swarm of cameras and reporters behind them. 
</P>
<P>
	Akers, removed from the game after suffering heat exhaustion,  
was still recovering Sunday and did not attend the victory events. 
Coach Tony DiCicco also missed the events, returning home to spend 
time with his family. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990712.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 15:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gov. Ventura Returns to the Ring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- Gov. Jesse Ventura wasn't saying Monday  
whether he would don his pink feather boa and return to the ring to 
wrestle or referee at next month's World Wrestling Federation 
``SummerSlam.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Be there on Wednesday for the press conference and find out.  
Charities are going to do well,'' Ventura said after touring 
storm-damaged areas of the Boundary Waters Canoe Area. 
</P>
<P>
	He and WWF officials confirmed a news conference Wednesday to  
discuss Ventura's ``return to the ring'' Aug. 22 at Target Center 
in Minneapolis. The ``SummerSlam'' event already is sold out but 
will be on pay-per-view for $29.95. 
</P>
<P>
	The governor, who turns 48 Thursday, hasn't wrestled since 1986.  
Back in his WWF days, Ventura wore a boa and played a bad guy known 
as ``The Body.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two top wrestling analysts said they expected Ventura would  
referee, mainly because of safety concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	Dave Meltzer of San Jose, Calif., who publishes the Wrestling  
Observer, one of the top weekly fan newspapers in the world, said 
wrestling was possible but not probable. ``He could wrestle, it's 
not inconceivable,'' Meltzer said. ``I would think refereeing would 
be the best for all concerned. You'd get the same amount of 
(publicity) for refereeing as the wrestling; It's just less of a 
risk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He expected Ventura would referee the main event, likely  
featuring WWF superstar Stone Cold Steve Austin. Austin is among 
those expected to be at the news conference with Ventura and WWF 
Chairman Vince McMahon. 
</P>
<P>
	Wade Keller of Bloomington, Minn., publishes the Pro Wrestling  
Torch and agreed with Meltzer's assessment. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he's not a referee, the most he will do is be in a tag team  
where like most of his career, his partner does most of the work in 
the ring,'' Keller said. 
</P>
<P>
	Both expected the paycheck to be big.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think he would do it for less than huge money because  
I don't think he particularly loves those people. He wouldn't want 
to feel that he was being ripped off by wrestling at this stage of 
his life,'' Meltzer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura once successfully sued McMahon for $1 million for  
royalties off a wrestling tape. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since I'd beaten him in court, he wasn't ever going to hire me  
again,'' Ventura wrote in his recent autobiography. ``It doesn't 
behoove promoters to have wrestlers who know what their rights 
are.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meltzer and Keller said the show could gross more than $20  
million, with the WWF keeping about half, and a paycheck of $1 
million for Ventura was not out of the question. Mike Tyson claimed 
to make $3.5 million for refereeing a WWF championship match last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Meltzer noted the WWF could use some good publicity.  
</P>
<P>
	In May, WWF wrestler Owen Hart died while performing a stunt at  
a Kansas City event. In June, champion Sable sued the WWF for $110 
million, complaining it wanted her to participate in a lesbian 
storyline, expose her breasts on TV and appear in sexually 
degrading photos. 
</P>
<P>
	A Dallas 7-year-old recently used a professional wrestling move  
on his 3-year-old brother and accidentally killed him. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura has often tried to distance himself from his wrestling  
past, saying he now wants to be called ``The Mind'' instead of 
``The Body.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The governor's staff wouldn't answer questions on the WWF plans,  
saying the governor would take vacation time for the activities. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990712.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 15:30:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Argentina's Stock Index Plunges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- Argentina's leading stock index  
plunged 8.7 percent on Monday as international investors left in 
droves amid worries over the country's still-feeble economic 
outlook. 
</P>
<P>
	The select Merval Index plunged as investors returned from a  
long holiday weekend to newspapers filled with worries about 
everything from debt payments and the recession to the course set 
by Economy Minister Roque Fernandez. The Merval dropped 43.07 
points to close at 453.86. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the broad General Index lost 1,140.48 points or 5.8  
percent to finish at 18,484.39. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's all getting a little out of hand,'' said Marcelo Simini,  
a fund manager at local bank Merchant Bankers y Asociados SA. 
``Nothing actually happened to cause such a strong decline, but an 
accumulation of crises, rumors and unhelpful comments.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the damage was blamed on damaging remarks by  
presidential hopefuls ahead of the October election. 
</P>
<P>
	Peronist presidential candidate Eduardo Duhalde said Sunday he  
would ask Pope John Paul II to mediate a one year moratorium on the 
country's debt if he is successful in the Oct. 24 elections. 
</P>
<P>
	Duhalde last week worried investors when he called for  
significant injection of foreign aid to help Argentina kickstart 
its economy and pay off debt. His main opposition rival, Fernando 
de la Rua of the Alliance, asked for ``political consideration'' of 
the country's foreign debt in other recent comments. 
</P>
<P>
	Also unnerving foreign investors is speculation about how  
Fernandez and his team will handle some $220 million in debt owed 
by the PAMI state-run health care plan for the elderly. 
</P>
<P>
	Though government officials have regularly soothed investors  
with messages of market stability and imminent economic growth, 
analysts said the underlying issue is Argentina's ongoing struggle 
to meet its 1999 fiscal targets set in tandem with the 
International Monetary Fund. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a $2.8 billion agreement with the IMF, the government  
agreed to cap its 1999 budget deficit at the equivalent of $5.1 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	A reduction in tax revenue due to a decline in imports and the  
contraction of the economy meant Argentina already has a five-month 
accumulated budget deficit of $2.85 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	But Miguel Kiguel, one of Argentina's undersecretaries for  
financial planning, said the debt is ``completely manageable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Argentina's favor is a windfall from the recent sale of the  
government's stake in oil giant YPF to Spain's energy conglomerate 
Repsol, netting the treasury $842 million. It also reaped $1.2 
billion from the sale of wireless telephone licenses. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990712.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 10:50:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fiat Marks Birthday With New Model </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TURIN, Italy (AP) -- Looking ahead to a new century, Fiat SpA  
celebrated its centennial Monday by unveiling the new version of 
one of its most successful cars, while a top executive denied 
rumors that the Italian automaker was shopping for a merger 
partner. 
</P>
<P>
	Executive officer Paolo Cantarella said Fiat plans to produce 4  
million cars a year by the second half of the next decade, without 
a partnership with another automaker. Last year Fiat produced 2.66 
million vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	Fiat has been the subject of extensive speculation that it wants  
to form an alliance or merger with another major automaker to 
better compete with larger players in the consolidating global auto 
industry. Fiat is the world's sixth-largest automaker in terms of 
production, just behind DaimlerChrysler AG and ahead of Nissan 
Motor Co. 
</P>
<P>
	It also is Italy's largest industrial group, but Cantarella said  
Fiat plans to keep cars as its core business in the new millennium. 
</P>
<P>
	Cantarella said Fiat is finding new opportunities for growth in  
manufacturing parts and in targeting special product niches. He 
cited as an example the recently announced contract with Mitsubishi 
Motors Corp. to develop and build a four-wheel-drive sport utility 
vehicle in 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	Europe is Fiat's primary market, but officials say they want to  
boost production and sales in the emerging markets of Asia, Eastern 
Europe and South America. One part of that strategy is the New 
Punto subcompact unveiled Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Fiat plans to produce 600,000 to 700,000 New Puntos a year at  
three Italian plants and plans to sell at least half outside Italy. 
It will be in most world markets by next year, except North 
America, where Fiat does not operate. 
</P>
<P>
	The car will go on sale in Europe in the fall in three- and  
five-door models. The lowest-priced version will cost about 
$10,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Roberto Testore, the chief executive of Fiat Auto, said Fiat  
expects total European sales to rise between 2 percent and 3 
percent this year, to more than 14 million units. He denied rumors 
that Fiat may sell one of its Polish plants to Ford Motor Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Fiat kicked off its centennial with a dinner Sunday night with  
honorary chairman Gianni Agnelli, the charismatic grandson of 
Fiat's founder who guided the company through turbulent times in 
the 1970s and 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the 3,000 guests were President Carlo Azeglio Ciampi,  
Premier Massimo D'Alema, former U.S. Secretary of State Henry 
Kissinger, tire magnate Leopoldo Pirelli and representatives of 
rival European automakers. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
