<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Smith Leaves Republican Party  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. Bob Smith of New Hampshire announced  
today he was leaving the Republican Party to become an independent, 
indicating he might seek the nomination of some other party in his 
bid for the White House. Smith characterized his decision as one of 
principles over party, chastising GOP lawmakers for forsaking the 
Republican platform. He decried leaders in his party ``who believe 
that electing people with an 'R' next to their name is more 
important than principle,'' Smith said on CNN's ``Larry King 
Live.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Flights Offered to Refugees in U.S.  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Refugees from Kosovo who found sanctuary in  
the United States will be offered free flights home from next week 
through next May, the State Department said today. Some 9,700 
ethnic Albanian refugees were flown to the United States last 
spring. About half went to live with relatives. And except for 78 
who remained in Fort Dix, N.J., the other half found other places 
to live in this country. Many of the refugees here are expected to 
take the United States up on the offer to go back to Kosovo through 
Macedonia, U.S. officials said, adding that younger refugees may be 
more inclined to remain here and start new lives. 

</P>
<P>
	20,000 Protestants March in Belfast  
</P>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- More than 20,000 Protestants on  
Monday celebrated Northern Ireland's most hot-blooded holiday by 
parading near a hostile Catholic neighborhood. A huge police and 
army presence kept the event peaceful -- unlike the rioting that has 
plagued Northern Ireland over Protestant marches in the last three 
years. Each July 12, the Orange Order, Northern Ireland's major 
Protestant brotherhood, parades in commemoration of a 1690 victory 
over Irish Catholics. 

</P>
<P>
	Iranian Cops Crack Down on Protests  
</P>
<P>
	DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) -- Riot police backed by  
helicopters broke up a demonstration of 1,000 people in Tehran on 
Monday, as hard-liners in the Iranian government lost patience on 
the fifth day of pro-democracy protests. The crackdown followed 
government warnings Sunday that unauthorized demonstrations would 
no longer be tolerated. The protests, which began Thursday, have 
shown the widening gulf between Iran's reformists, who support 
President Mohammad Khatami, and the hard-liners in government who 
oppose him. 

</P>
<P>
	Survey: More Feel Distant From Gov't  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- More than half of Americans say in a survey  
they feel distant and disconnected from government. Only those 65 
or older were inclined to feel a sense of connection. The survey 
was taken for the Council for Excellence in Government and released 
today. ``The disconnect is more prevalent among younger 
Americans,'' said Patricia McGinnis, council president. Voter 
turnout in the 1998 congressional elections was 36 percent, the 
lowest national turnout in more than 50 years. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Sues Toyota Over Smog Control  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government accused Toyota today of putting  
faulty smog-control computers on 2.2 million 1996-1998 vehicles and 
sought to have the computers repaired and the company fined up to 
$58.5 billion. On behalf of the Environmental Protection Agency, 
the Justice Department filed a civil lawsuit against the 
automaker's U.S. subsidiary under the Clean Air Act in U.S. 
District Court. Toyota rejected a settlement offer last week that 
might have cost it $100 million in civil fines. 

</P>
<P>
	Merrill Lynch Heir-Apparent Retires  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Herbert M. Allison Jr., the heir-apparent for  
the top job at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. surprised Wall Street today by 
announcing his early retirement. Allison, 55, president and chief 
operating officer, plans to leave the brokerage and investment bank 
by end of the month. Allison, who joined Merrill 28 years ago as an 
associate, was widely expected to succeed David Komansky, 60, 
chairman and chief executive officer. The New York-based company 
said it had no immediate plans to name a replacement for Allison. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Are Mixed  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks were mixed Tuesday after  
profit-taking. The Nikkei fell 20.90 points to 18,253.28 points in 
early trading. In New York, the Dow ended at a new high of 
11,200.98, up 7.28. 

</P>
<P>
	Griffey Wins Home Run Derby  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Ken Griffey Jr. repeated as Home Run Derby  
champion today, but Fenway Park was buzzing about Mark McGwire's 13 
home runs in the first round. McGwire's 13 homers off Tim Flannery 
broke the one-round record set by Cal Ripken in 1991 at Toronto's 
SkyDome. Big Mac's attack totaled 5,692 feet -- more than a mile -- 
and a lot more than he hit one mile up at Denver's Coors Field last 
July. Griffey hit 10 homers in the second round, including a 
460-foot shot to the back of the center-field triangle and an 
opposite-field drive over The Green Monster and into the screen. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY  

  	   	
</P>
