<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Merrill Lynch Heir-Apparent Retires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Herbert M. Allison Jr., the heir-apparent for  
the top job at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. surprised Wall Street Monday by 
announcing his early retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	Allison, 55, president and chief operating officer, plans to  
leave the brokerage and investment bank by end of the month. 
Allison, who joined Merrill 28 years ago as an associate, was 
widely expected to succeed David Komansky, 60, chairman and chief 
executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York-based company said it had no immediate plans to  
name a replacement for Allison. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this point in my life and career, I realize that this is an  
opportune time to make a change,'' Allison said in a statement. He 
could not be reached for additional comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Merrill's recent push onto the Internet reportedly caused  
friction among top officials. Last month, Merrill Lynch unveiled an 
aggressive strategy to let its clients buy and sell stock over the 
Internet at prices competitive with Charles Schwab &AMP; Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Allison had sought a presence on the Internet over the protests  
of co-vice chairman John ``Launny'' Steffens, who oversees 
Merrill's 14,000 retail stockbrokers. Allison wanted to create an 
Internet group outside Steffens' control. But in the end, Steffens 
backed the Internet plans and insisted he spearhead the effort. 
</P>
<P>
	``Big surprise,'' said James Hanbury, an analyst at Schroder &AMP;  
Co. He added, however, that he didn't think the loss of Allison 
would hurt Merrill going forward. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for Merrill Lynch declined to comment.  
</P>
<P>
	Allison's responsibilities will be divided between Steffens and  
co-vice chairman Stephen L. Hammerman. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement, Komansky said, ``Herb Allison has brought great  
intellectual energy, dedication and integrity to every stage of his 
career at Merrill Lynch. ... All of us understand and respect his 
decision and wish him every success and happiness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Allison was born in Pennsyvania in 1943 and earned an MBA from  
Stanford University in 1971. At Merrill Lynch, he spent much of his 
early years overseas, holding investment banking positions in 
Paris, Tehran, and London before moving into finance and human 
resources in the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	He spent three years as treasurer, then ran the human-resources  
department, before being promoted to chief financial officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Allison was put in charge of Merrill's investment-banking  
operations in 1993. Two years later, he was able to consolidate his 
authority over the firm's stock and bond underwriting and trading 
operations as well. 
</P>
<P>
	After several more promotions, he was named to his current post  
in April 1997. Last year, Allison was paid $7.9 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Merrill is expected to release its second-quarter financial  
results Tuesday. Analysts expect the brokerage firm to earn $1.46 a 
share, up from a $1.31 in the year-ago period. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement came after the market closed. Merrill's shares  
ended the day up 81 1/4 cents at $77.87 1/2 on the New York Stock 
Exchange. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990712.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 21:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
