<HEADLINE> Merrill Lynch Heir-Apparent Retires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The man who was heir-apparent for the top job at  
Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. is instead making an early exit. 
</P>
<P>
	Herbert M. Allison Jr., 55, surprised Wall Street Monday by  
announcing his early retirement. Allison, who is Merrill's 
president and chief operating officer, plans to leave the brokerage 
and investment bank by end of the month. 
</P>
<P>
	Allison, who joined Merrill 28 years ago as an associate, was  
widely expected to succeed David Komansky, 60, chairman and chief 
executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this point in my life and career, I realize that this is an  
