<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MetLife Buys from St. Paul Cos. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- In a move to strengthen its auto and home  
insurance businesses, Metropolitan Life Insurance Co. will purchase 
the personal insurance operations from The St. Paul Cos. for about 
$600 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition will boost MetLife Auto &AMP; Home premiums to $2.7  
billion, vaulting the company from 20th to 12th in the personal 
property and casualty insurance industry, MetLife said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	MetLife Auto &AMP; Home, a subsidiary of the Warwick, R.I.-based  
MetLife, expects to more than double its independent agency 
distribution network through the acquisition, with the potential to 
add 3,000 independent agencies and brokers to its existing 2,700 
independent agents. 
</P>
<P>
	All 1,700 St. Paul employees directly involved in the personal  
insurance business will be transferred to MetLife Auto &AMP; Homes, 
said Douglas Leatherdale, chairman and chief executive of The St. 
Paul. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the St. Paul company will cut 500 to 600 other  
employees to bring expenses in line with its smaller revenue base. 
Employees who lose their jobs will be given severance packages and 
help in finding other jobs, Leatherdale said. 
</P>
<P>
	The St. Paul-based company employs about 13,500 workers,  
including 3,300 in St. Paul. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale, subject to regulatory approval and other conditions,  
is expected to close in the third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Wall Street reacted favorably to the news, sending the St.  
Paul's shares up $1.12 1/2 to $30.25 Monday on the New York Stock 
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Met Life is a mutual company, owned by its policyholders, and  
has no publicly traded stock. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
