<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ky. Receiver Has Thumb Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- Kentucky wide receiver Jimmy Robinson,  
injured when gunfire broke out at an off-campus party over the 
weekend, underwent surgery on his left thumb Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson was shot twice in the incident, which occurred after a  
group of people crashed a party at the swimming pool of the 
University Commons apartment complex and fighting broke out. 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson, the only person shot, was hit in his upper left arm  
and at the base of his thumb. 
</P>
<P>
	A statement from the school's athletics department said Robinson  
was operated on by Dr. Phil Blazar of the UK Hospital. Pins were 
used to repair the fracture at the base of Robinson's thumb. 
According to Blazar, the surgery was successful and the pins should 
be removed in about five weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson's upper arm was placed in a cast and is not expected to  
require surgery. The fractured humerus is expected to require three 
to four months to heal. 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson was in fair condition and was being kept overnight at  
UK Hospital for observation. His playing status will depend on how 
quickly he heals, the school said. 
</P>
<P>
	No arrests have been made.  
</P>
<P>
	Robinson, of Stone Mountain, Ga., played the last two seasons  
for Kentucky after transferring from Georgia Military College in 
1997. Last season, he caught 26 passes for 285 yards and two 
touchdowns. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
