<DOCNO> APW19990712.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 03:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Schilling To Start All-Star Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Curt Schilling's latest triumph was yet  
another tough loss for Randy Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling was selected Sunday to start for the National League  
in the All-Star game, The Associated Press learned. A baseball 
source confirmed that Schilling, the Philadelphia Phillies' ace, 
was chosen by NL manager Bruce Bochy to start over Johnson of the 
Arizona Diamondbacks. 
</P>
<P>
	The source, who was familiar with the selection process,  
declined to be identified. 
</P>
<P>
	Bochy, the San Diego Padres manager, would only say he was  
leaning toward starting Schilling. Bochy will make the official 
announcement today. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be his first (All-Star game) start, and he started  
his career with the Boston organization,'' Bochy said. ``It's a 
tough call.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling has 13 victories, one fewer than Kent Bottenfield of  
St. Louis. He is tied with Johnson for the major league lead with 
seven complete games and is second in the NL to Johnson in 
strikeouts. Schilling also declined to confirm that he was Bochy's 
choice -- although he was seen accepting congratulations in the 
clubhouse after the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know who's starting,'' said Schilling, named to his third  
straight All-Star team. ``I've got a pretty good idea who will have 
the ball when the game starts. The manager is going to announce it 
tomorrow, and we'll all have fun talking about it tomorrow. It's 
not my job to announce it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just more than a week ago, Bochy was leaning toward starting  
Johnson on Tuesday at Fenway Park. But the Arizona left-hander, who 
is 9-7, has been victimized by his own offense. Arizona hasn't 
scored a run in the last 34 innings Johnson has been on the mound. 
Johnson is 0-4 in his last four starts despite allowing a total of 
five earned runs and striking out 54. 
</P>
<P>
	Boston's Pedro Martinez will start for the American League.  
</P>
<P>
	Schilling was selected to the All-Star team in 1997 and '98 and  
pitched two scoreless innings two years ago at Jacobs Field in 
Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	He started his career in the Red Sox organization, but was  
traded to Baltimore with Brady Anderson for Mike Boddicker in 1988. 
He was dealt to Houston with Pete Harnisch and Steve Finley for 
Glenn Davis in 1991, and then traded to Philadelphia for Jason 
Grimsley in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	In another All-Star game development, Bochy was told by the NL  
office that Mark McGwire has to start at first base since he voted 
in by the fans. Bochy wanted to use McGwire as his DH, but instead 
will use Houston's Jeff Bagwell. 
</P>
<P>
	Bochy's likely batting order will be Cincinnati's Barry Larkin,  
Colorado's Larry Walker, Chicago's Sammy Sosa, McGwire, Arizona's 
Matt Williams, Bagwell, Mike Piazza of the New York Mets, 
Milwaukee's Jeromy Burnitz and Arizona's Jay Bell. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990712.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 18:50:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Credit Suisse Faces Losing License </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The Financial Supervisory Agency has decided to  
recommend revoking the banking license of a unit of Credit Suisse 
Group AG because it allegedly tried to block an investigation of 
its handling of derivatives products, according to reports Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The reports in several Japanese media said the FSA will seek the  
revocation of the license of Credit Suisse Financial Products, 
invoking article 27 of Japan's banking law, and will formally 
notify Credit Suisse Group executives of the findings of its 
investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Credit Suisse will have the opportunity at a hearing to respond  
to the findings. Credit Suisse Group has declined to comment on the 
reports. 
</P>
<P>
	The FSA has reportedly concluded Credit Suisse Financial  
Products attempted to obstruct an examination launched by the 
watchdog agency on Jan. 20 by destroying documents and shipping 
others off to London. 
</P>
<P>
	The FSA also believes Credit Suisse Group violated firewall  
regulations on banking and securities operations, among other 
illegal actions. 
</P>
<P>
	The almost six-month investigation also covered three other  
group companies: Credit Suisse First Boston Tokyo branch, Credit 
Suisse Trust and Banking Co. and Credit Suisse First Boston 
Securities Japan Ltd. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
