<HEADLINE> Clinton Orders $100M for Heat Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton directed the Department of  
Health and Human Services on Monday to release $100 million in 
emergency funds for 17 states that experienced the recent heat 
wave. 
</P>
<P>
	The money comes from the Low-income Home Energy Assistance  
Program and is directed at providing relief for eligible families 
and individuals. States -- from New England to the mid-Atlantic and 
in the Midwest -- can use the money to pay cooling bills and buy air 
conditioners for low-income households. 
</P>
<P>
	``These resources will help protect the most vulnerable among us  
as the current heat wave runs its course,'' Clinton said in a 
statement, noting that soaring temperatures in the past weeks have 
claimed the lives of more than 100 people. 
</P>
<P>
	The funds were allocated to the states most affected by the  
extreme heat and the number of low-income households in the state. 
Of the $100 million, $690,380 will go directly to 15 American 
Indian tribes in Maine, Massachusetts, Michigan, New Jersey, New 
York, North Carolina and Rhode Island. 
</P>
<P>
	The amount of funds for each state:  
</P>
<P>
	Connecticut: $3,123,251  
</P>
<P>
	Delaware: $694,531  
</P>
<P>
	District of Columbia: $1,085,603  
</P>
<P>
	Maine: $782,566  
</P>
<P>
	Maryland: $3,576,484  
</P>
<P>
	Massachusetts: $7,762,254  
</P>
<P>
	Michigan: $3,950,906  
</P>
<P>
	New Hampshire: $774,056  
</P>
<P>
	New Jersey: $9,053,730  
</P>
<P>
	New York: $28,484,847  
</P>
<P>
	North Carolina: $6,536,764  
</P>
<P>
	Ohio: $8,489,614  
</P>
<P>
	Pennsylvania: $12,957,432  
</P>
<P>
	Rhode Island: $1,721,367  
</P>
<P>
	Vermont: $474,893  
</P>
<P>
	Virginia: $7,639,727  
</P>
<P>
	West Virginia: $2,891,975  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
