<DOCNO> APW19990712.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 21:04:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clashes in Colombia Subsiding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Fierce clashes in Colombia's southern  
savannahs subsided Monday, winding down a four-day guerrilla blitz 
army leaders claimed was a debacle for the country's powerful 
leftist insurgents. 
</P>
<P>
	Trying to convince a skeptical media, troops brought journalists  
to an army base where they displayed the bodies of 30 guerrillas 
allegedly killed in Puerto Lleras, a town 114 miles from the 
capital, Bogota. 
</P>
<P>
	About a third of the dead on display at the army base in  
Granada, twenty minutes by helicopter from Puerto Lleras, were 
female fighters, common in the FARC. Many still had red, yellow and 
blue banners across the chests -- national colors the rebels often 
wear into battle. 
</P>
<P>
	Army explosives experts in the isolated southern town worked to  
defuse homemade missiles left by the guerrillas, who flattened a 
police station and homes with the crude, but deadly weapons 
fashioned from gas canisters. 
</P>
<P>
	After initially declaring the hostilities over, the army  
conceded Monday afternoon that clashes continued in at least two 
locations. 
</P>
<P>
	Troops and rebels were still ``fighting in the streets'' in  
Puerto Rico, another town in Meta, armed services chief Gen. 
Fernando Tapias told reporters. Thirty-seven police officers were 
missing and feared taken prisoner by rebels who raided the town 126 
miles from Bogota. 
</P>
<P>
	Gunmen who were presumed to be rebels also fired sporadic shots  
Monday afternoon at anti-narcotics police roadblock near Florencia, 
the state capital. 
</P>
<P>
	Military leaders are saying they saved the country from one of  
the guerrillas' most ambitious offensives since taking up arms in 
the 1960s. 
</P>
<P>
	Many observers have their doubts. They feel the FARC is making  
steady progress -- even if it lost some fighters, didn't permanently 
seize territory or inflict heavy government casualties in its 
latest offensive. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've managed to show force, to intimidate (Colombia's)  
establishment, and without a doubt made it possible to push harder 
at the negotiating table,'' said former national security adviser 
Alfredo Rangel. 
</P>
<P>
	The rebels launched their offensive less than two weeks before a  
planned round of negotiations with the government of President 
Andres Pastrana to end Colombia's 35-year conflict. The FARC is 
demanding sweeping reforms to attack poverty, redistribute land and 
clean up political corruption. 
</P>
<P>
	Fighting raged over the weekend in 10 of the country's 32  
provinces, killing at least 59 police and soldiers as well as two 
children whose house was destroyed by a rebel bomb. The army claims 
it killed a fifth of an estimated 1,000 rebel fighters 
participating in the attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	The combat began Thursday, when FARC rebels overran an army  
encampment, killing 38 soldiers in mountains an hour south of the 
capital. Military leaders claimed they had beaten back a strike at 
Bogota, a city of 7 million residents, and the government imposed a 
nighttime travel ban in the affected provinces. 
</P>
<P>
	Rangel said the army was probably exaggerating the scope of the  
FARC offensive as well as rebel losses -- part of a ``propaganda 
counteroffensive'' designed to divert attention from the military's 
own shortcomings on the battlefield. 
</P>
<P>
	The 15,000-member FARC has enjoyed a nearly unbroken string of  
victories during the past three years. In a much larger offensive 
last August, the rebels killed 143 soldiers and police, took more 
than hundred captive and overran a major anti-narcotics base. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
