<DOCNO> APW19990712.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 17:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tenn. TV Station Rescinds Ad Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A Fox television affiliate in Tennessee has  
hurriedly rescinded an offer to local businesses to produce three 
``positive'' news stories about them in exchange for $15,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The advertising sales staff at WDSI in Chattanooga had told  
businesses that the stories would be broadcast on the station's 
news programs. 
</P>
<P>
	An executive who oversees the station blamed a rogue salesperson  
for the offer, which was taken off the table before any sales were 
made. The station begin broadcasting news shows this year for the 
first time. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's out of ignorance that this happened, because they don't  
understand the ethics of journalism,'' said David Janecek, vice 
president for news at Pegasus Broadcast Television, a 
Pennsylvania-based company that owns Fox-61. 
</P>
<P>
	A Fox spokesman said the network had no prior knowledge of the  
offer and had nothing to do with the conduct of its affiliate 
stations. 
</P>
<P>
	A one-page sales circular distributed by the station said that  
Fox-61 News was producing a series of news segments highlighting 
prominent businesses in the Chattanooga area. ``We want your 
company highlighted!'' said the sales pitch. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fox-61 News is the most credible programming for the image of  
your company,'' the solicitation continues. ``When an organization 
is involved with positive news coverage, that organization is 
looked upon extremely favorable (sic) in the community.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The $15,000 fee entitled companies to news segments that would  
be repeated during the morning, midday and evening news programs, 
along with 18 promotional spots drawing attention to the stories. 
</P>
<P>
	Albert Waterhouse, a public relations executive who represents  
businesses in the Chattanooga area, received the solicitation and 
was ``shocked it was so blatant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I just think there needs to be an extremely clear division  
between advertising and news,'' Waterhouse said. ``The public needs 
to understand that you can't buy favorable news stories about your 
clients or anybody else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Erlanger Health System, which owns a hospital and clinics in  
Chattanooga, also received the offer. ``Pretty much everyone agreed 
that it was not only a high price, it was somebody putting a price 
on news,'' spokeswoman Carolyn Peak said. 
</P>
<P>
	The station's general manager, Jim Wright, referred all calls to  
Janacek. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pegasus executive said the salesperson who devised and  
distributed the offer acted against policy and without permission. 
He wouldn't name the person involved or discuss what action the 
company might take. 
</P>
<P>
	Waterhouse suggested, however, that more than one person might  
have been involved: He said the offer was dropped off at his office 
by two people, including the Fox-61 sales manager. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked how this would affect the station's credibility as a news  
organization, Janacek said, ``It's not going to help.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990712.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 17:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> El Diario Publisher Ramirez Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Carlos D. Ramirez, the publisher of el diario/La  
Prensa who helped modernize and bring financial security to the 
city's largest and oldest daily Spanish-language newspaper, has 
died of pancreatic cancer. He was 52. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramirez died Sunday morning at Sloan Kettering Memorial Center,  
his business partner Peter Davidson said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a great loss to his family and to the whole Latino  
community here in New York,'' Davidson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite his illness, Ramirez continued to come into the office  
several days a week. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was working right up until last week when he was  
hospitalized,'' Davidson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramirez was hired by el diario's former owner Gannett Co. as a  
comptroller in 1981 and became publisher in 1984. The newspaper, 
founded in 1913, is believed to be the oldest Spanish-language 
daily in the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1989, when Gannett first started shopping the newspaper  
around, Ramirez, Davidson and 15 others formed an investment group 
-- El Diario Associates -- and bought the newspaper for a reported 
$20 million to $25 million to keep it under Hispanic ownership. 
</P>
<P>
	He often told employees of how he borrowed money from his  
retired father who encouraged him, saying, ``It's your generation's 
turn now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under their ownership, Ramirez remained publisher and Davidson  
became president. The investment group, now called Latin 
Communications Group Inc., owns several Spanish-language newspapers 
and 18 radio stations around the country. 
</P>
<P>
	In the last couple of years, el diario has had one of the  
fastest growing circulations in the city, along with the New York 
Post. Its Monday through Friday circulation is nearing 52,000 
daily, according to the 1999 Editor &AMP; Publisher. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990712.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 13:10:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Societe Generale Rebuffs BNP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- The board of directors of French banking group  
Societe Generale on Monday rejected Banque Nationale de Paris' 
sweetened offer for its shares -- the latest installment of a 
three-way takeover battle. 
</P>
<P>
	BNP did not immediately comment on the decision by Societe  
Generale. The third bank in the battle, Paribas, rejected the 
sweetened BNP offer on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 18-week-old takeover fight began in March when BNP jumped  
into an agreed merger between Societe Generale and Paribas, 
offering $37 billion for the two banks. Societe Generale and 
Paribas rejected BNP's offer and have spurned its advances since 
then. 
</P>
<P>
	On July 1, the BNP increased its initial bid by five percent.  
</P>
<P>
	A merger of the three banks would create the world's first $1  
trillion bank in terms of assets. 
</P>
<P>
	Societe Generale also announced Monday that its first-half  
earnings this year will be double those reported in 1998, when the 
bank earned $707.6 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Societe Generale in June sweetened its own offer to Paribas  
shareholders by adding a cash payout of as much as $1.54 billion to 
its initial all-stock offer. 
</P>
<P>
	BNP responded at the beginning of July by raising the value of  
its two bids to about $39 billion, adding a cash payout of as much 
as $900 million as well as stock to its all-stock offer. 
</P>
<P>
	The deadline for both sets of bids is July 30 unless extended.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
