<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NAACP To Sue Gun Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The NAACP announced offensives against TV  
networks and gun makers Monday, using public relations and the 
threat of lawsuits to push for more black faces on the tube and 
fewer guns on the street. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's largest civil rights group decided at its annual  
meeting to monitor and seek action on the ``virtual whitewash'' in 
fall TV programming, a lineup featuring few minority characters. 
</P>
<P>
	The group also said it will file a federal suit later this week  
in New York seeking tough limits on the gun industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Both announcements came as the National Association for the  
Advancement of Colored People held its 90th annual convention. 
</P>
<P>
	NAACP President Kweisi Mfume said the group's new NAACP  
Television &AMP; Film Industry Diversity Initiative will monitor how 
well the entertainment industry reflects America's multicultural 
base. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to calling for congressional and Federal  
Communication Commission hearings on licensing and ownership of 
networks, the campaign could lead to lawsuits and boycotts of 
advertisers, Mfume said. 
</P>
<P>
	None of the 27 new comedies and dramas premiering on the top  
four networks this fall has minorities in a leading role, and few 
have them in supporting roles either. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS President Leslie Moonves called the NAACP's concerns  
``relevant and extremely important.'' Moonves said in a statement 
that 11 of the network's 19 entertainment series broadcast this 
fall would have minority characters ``in a primary role.'' Network 
spokesman Chris Ender said one new show this fall, ``Now and 
Again,'' a drama, would feature a black actor, Dennis Haysbert. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC said in a statement that including minorities on the air  
``has been a top priority for some time and it continues to remain 
an important priority,'' but that there was still work to be done. 
</P>
<P>
	And Fox said it agreed with the NAACP that increasing racial and  
ethnic diversity on TV was an important goal. ``We welcome the 
opportunity to meet with Mr. Mfume to discuss this issue,'' the 
network said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Six weeks ago, ABC Entertainment President Jamie Tarses said the  
network was adding some black and Latino characters to its shows 
this fall in order to become more diverse. ``It is something we are 
always conscious of and (we're) disappointed we did not do a better 
job,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The NAACP will study whether the 1934 communications act  
mandating public ownership of the airwaves can be used as a basis 
for suing. 
</P>
<P>
	Blacks make up 13 percent of the population, and ``we think our  
presence should be appropriately reflected both in front the 
cameras as well as behind the cameras,'' Mfume said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This glaring omission is an outrage and a shameful display by  
network executives who are either clueless, careless or both.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On guns, the NAACP is launching a product liability suit against  
nearly 100 firearms makers, distributors and importers, seeking 
what it calls sweeping new steps to keep guns from criminals. 
</P>
<P>
	``The industry has been reckless,'' said Denise Dunleavy, an  
attorney with the New York law firm of Weitz &AMP; Luxenberg, which 
will represent the NAACP without charge. ``We want safe marketing 
practices and new distribution patterns.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The NAACP is seeking an injunction rather than monetary damages,  
Dunleavy said. 
</P>
<P>
	She said the suit would seek to end the sale of firearms at gun  
shows, mandate that all new guns be equipped with safety locks, 
tighten regulations on who could qualify as federally licensed gun 
distributors and limit customers to one gun purchase per month. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Rifle Association decried the suit.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think the NAACP is out of step with African American  
citizens around the country,'' said Wayne LaPierre, NRA executive 
vice president. Minorities value gun rights, he said, and the drive 
to limit those rights comes from ``rich white liberals who live 
behind security systems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The idea of holding a manufacturer of a legal product  
responsible for the third-party criminal misuse of their product is 
a horrible idea,'' he said. ``We won't have a manufactured product 
in America in the future if that theory of law is allowed to stand 
up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mfume suggested tougher gun standards might have headed off the  
recent murders of a black man and a Korean student by a white 
supremacist who went on a shooting rampage in Illinois and Indiana. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities say Benjamin Smith got his firearms from an  
unlicensed dealer who had purchased 65 guns from a store over two 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	``When 65 guns are sold to one person, something is wrong,''  
Mfume said. 
</P>
<P>
	LaPierre noted Smith was turned down for guns by a legitimate  
dealer earlier, when a background check showed he was under court 
order to stay away from his girlfriend. Smith should have been 
arrested then, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they'd enforced the law, Ben Smith wouldn't have killed  
anybody,'' LaPierre said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
