<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GUATEMALA CITY (AP) -- A day after a strong quake shook the  
Caribbean coast of Guatemala, life in the region is returning to 
normal, Guatemala's president said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sunday morning quake injured 38 people and was blamed for  
the death of a man who had a heart attack. Fifty houses were 
destroyed. 
</P>
<P>
	The quake was located about 20 miles east of the Guatemalan  
coast city of Puerto Barrios. Estimates of its magnitude ranged 
from 6.1 to 6.6. It was felt in parts of Honduras, El Salvador and 
Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Ecuador's president froze gasoline prices  
until the end of the year in an effort Monday to end a strike by 
taxi and bus drivers. 
</P>
<P>
	But strike leaders immediately rejected the measure, which froze  
gasoline prices at $1.16 a gallon, and said they would continue the 
week-old strike to force President Jamil Mahuad to rescind a 13 
percent increase. 
</P>
<P>
	Strikers want the government to freeze gasoline prices for two  
years at their June levels -- $1.02 a gallon. Monthly incomes in 
Ecuador hover at about $108. 
</P>
<P>
	Drivers have partially paralyzed streets and highways in  
Ecuador's major cities by forming barricades with their vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortages of foods and vegetables have started to occur in  
Quito, the capital. 
</P>
<P>
	Ecuador is locked in its worst economic crisis in decades, with  
the economy expected to shrink by 5 percent this year and annual 
inflation topping 50 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Cuba's new foreign minister praised a  
proposal by Venezuela on Monday to provide much-needed oil to Cuba 
at discount prices. 
</P>
<P>
	President Hugo Chavez has called for expanding the San Jose Pact  
-- an agreement by Mexico and Venezuela to supply oil to 11 Central 
American and Caribbean countries at a discount -- to include Cuba 
and other nations. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Cuban people will not forget this noble gesture of great  
generosity,'' Cuba Foreign Minister Felipe Perez Roque said during 
a two-day visit to Venezuela. 
</P>
<P>
	Economic difficulties in recent years have caused acute oil  
shortages in Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- High winds and waves Monday forced Mexican  
maritime authorities to close 12 eastern ports to small ships and 
two others to all sea traffic. 
</P>
<P>
	The ports on the Gulf of Mexico were shut down after a tropical  
storm churned up 6 1/2-foot waves and wind gusts of up to 35 mph, the 
government news agency Notimex reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Two ports, Coatzacoalcos in Veracruz state and Dos Bocas in  
Tabasco, were closed to all ship traffic. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
