<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Innocent Pleas in Radio Payola Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The nation's largest independent Latin music  
label and two of its executives pleaded innocent Monday to federal 
payola charges, or paying radio stations to broadcast their 
records. 
</P>
<P>
	Charges against the Van Nuys-based Fonovisa are the first since  
the scandals of the 1950s, said Thom Mrozek, a spokesman for the 
U.S. Attorney's office. 
</P>
<P>
	Jesus Gilberto Moreno, the company's promotion chief, pleaded  
innocent in Los Angeles Federal Court with making improper payments 
for radio play. Company president Guillermo Santiso pleaded 
innocent to a tax violation related to a payola charge. 
</P>
<P>
	Santiso and Moreno intend to plead guilty once their cases are  
consolidated, said Charles Kreindler, Santino's attorney. 
</P>
<P>
	Jennifer Colyer, a lawyer for Fonovisa, spoke for the record  
label and pleaded innocent to a tax offense for allegedly falsely 
reporting promotional expenses. 
</P>
<P>
	Their next court appearance is scheduled for Sept. 7.  
</P>
<P>
	Similar payola cases occurred in the 1980s, but the defendants  
then did not work for record companies, Mrozek said. They were 
outside record promoters who promised the company a hit using 
methods presumed to be legal, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In May 1997, Moreno paid $2,000 to a program director to have  
Fonovisa records added to the station's play list, court records 
allege. 
</P>
<P>
	The charges follow a two-year investigation of Fonovisa, which  
is owned by Mexican media giant Grupo Televisa. 
</P>
<P>
	Artists from the record label dominated Spanish-language  
airwaves in 1997 with songs from such singers as Enrique Iglesias 
and Marco Antonio Solis. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrozek refused to identify the radio stations involved in the  
alleged scam, but said charges may still be filed against several 
programming directors. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said he could not specify artists or songs the stations  
allegedly were paid to play. 
</P>
<P>
	Fonovisa monopolized the top three positions on Billboard  
magazine's Latin airplay chart for the first five months of 1997, 
regularly taking about 14 of the 40 slots available. 
</P>
<P>
	But when the company allegedly quit paying programmers cash to  
play its songs, its presence on the Hot Latin Tracks chart fell by 
half. 
</P>
<P>
	That year, its record sales were about 16 percent of the nearly  
$500 million in Spanish music sales in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Fonovisa was credited with developing the U.S. market for banda,  
mariachi and other regional Mexican music. 
</P>
<P>
	Grupo Televisa said last year it reported the illegal activities  
to the U.S. government and cooperated with the investigation. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
