<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets closed mixed Monday, with  
prices surging in Tokyo but slumping in Hong Kong. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average jumped  
336.45 points, or 1.88 percent, to 18,274.18, its highest level 
since September 1997. On Friday, the average fell 29.92 points, or 
0.17 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo stocks rose on robust gains in international blue-chip  
shares. Sentiment remained solid amid continued buying from foreign 
investors and Japanese individuals. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was an awful lot of foreign buying in the market today.  
It is absorbing selling (by institutional investors),'' said 
Kunihiro Hatae, general manager of the stock division at Tokyo 
Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Interest in international blue chips including Sony, Fujitsu and  
Hitachi was especially strong, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 122.14 yen in  
late afternoon trading, down 0.52 yen from late Friday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange were pushed down by a  
late selling spree in the futures market. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng Index, the Hong Kong market's key indicator of  
blue chips, fell 160.73 points, or 1.1 percent, closing at 
14,061.84. On Friday, the index slipped 3.73 points, or 0.02 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers said share prices rose for most of the session in  
reaction to Friday's record rally on Wall Street, where the Dow 
Jones industrial average gained 66.81, or 0.6 percent, to close at 
11,193.70. 
</P>
<P>
	Futures-related selling in the last 15 minutes of trading pushed  
the Hang Seng Index into negative territory. 
</P>
<P>
	Futures traders said two major European brokerages launched  
massive profit-taking sprees, erasing gains in the cash market. 
</P>
<P>
	South Korea shares closed mixed, with the main index falling 2.3  
percent as investors took profits on renewed concerns that local 
interest rates could rise later this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Korea Composite Stock Price Index fell 23.68 points to  
1,004.25. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Share prices closed lower in reaction to recent moves by  
the government to cool the market. The market's key Weighted Stock 
Price Index fell 86.37 points, or 1.0 percent, to 8,463.90. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed lower on  
profit-taking. The benchmark NZSE-40 Capital Index fell 12.75 
points, or 0.5 percent, to 2,197.24. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine shares closed mixed. The Philippine Stock  
Exchange Index of 30 selected companies rose 11.49 points, or 0.4 
percent, to 2,606.21. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: The Australian stock market closed higher on buying in  
most main banking stocks and some leading industrial stocks. The 
All Ordinaries Index rose 9.2 points, or 0.3 percent, to 3,050.2. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Shares closed mixed amid buying in index-linked  
stocks, dealers said. The key Straits Times Index rose 17.15 
points, or 0.5 percent, to 2,198.78. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian shares closed mixed. The Composite  
Index, which tracks 100 blue-chip stocks, slipped 0.18 point to 
851.49. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian shares closed higher on bargain-hunting  
following last week's losses. The Composite Index rose 1 percent, 
or 6.480 points, to 663.124. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai stock prices closed mixed as buying in banking  
stocks was negated by some profit-taking in finance and property 
stocks. The SET index rose 2.29 points, or 0.4 percent, to 511.87. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
