<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stock Market Said To Be On `Bubble' / Commentary  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                        *AP Business Analyst    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A subtle shading, a mere nuance, has begun to  
emerge in the commentary of securities analysts: They are losing 
their aversion to the use of the word ``bubble'' in describing the 
investment scene. 
</P>
<P>
	That aversion is understandable, given the tendency of bubbles  
to burst, but some analysts now use the word easily, as if to 
concede the word's relevance to the spectacular current market. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, it is rare to find an economic or financial forecaster  
willing to stake his or her reputation on a flat out bubble burst. 
Instead, they pose the possibility, just in case the worst case 
scenario unfolds. 
</P>
<P>
	``Could we get to 15,000 on the Dow before the end of the  
year?'' asks Deutsche Bank economist Edward Yardeni? He answers: 
``I said it before, I'll say it again: In a speculative bubble, 
anything is possible.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	David Wyss of Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI puts it similarly. ``DRI  
model equations suggest that this is indeed a market bubble, but we 
have never had one persist this long in the past,'' he wrote 
recently. 
</P>
<P>
	But Wyss, too, avoids any suggestion that the bubble is about to  
be pricked. ``The possibility that something fundamental has 
changed in the stock market should not be ruled out,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	Economist Stephen King, based in London for HSBC securities, is  
an exception. He is unusually explicit. Not only does a bubble 
exist, but ``the burst may come at the beginning of 2000.'' Even 
sooner, he says. 
</P>
<P>
	In a 52-page analysis, King suggests that almost all the  
symptoms associated with earlier bubbles in other nations, as in 
Japan and the United Kingdom during 1986-1989, are factors in 
today's U.S. economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Among them: above trend growth, below trend inflation, global  
commodity price collapse, faster money supply growth, falling 
private sector savings, financial innovation and ``PARADIGM 
SHIFT.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The U.S. bubble'' he says, ``is likely to burst through a  
combination of rising interest rates and a falling dollar,'' 
suggesting a significant risk of a sharp and sustained fall in 
asset prices toward year end. 
</P>
<P>
	Though not as rare as they were a few months ago, bubble  
references such as these are still far from commonplace. Most 
economists and market forecasters continue an old tradition of not 
calling for major changes. 
</P>
<P>
	Joseph McAlinden, chief investment officer for the Morgan  
Stanley Dean Witter Family of Funds, suggests that investors 
``rotate'' into undervalued stocks, such as those often found in 
mature industries. 
</P>
<P>
	Salomon Smith Barney says ``we expect previously out-of-favor  
sectors to perform well, as the market continues to move toward 
equilibrium between large-cap and small-cap stocks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Morgan Stanley Dean Witter advises clients to ``consider  
shifting into cyclical and smaller-cap stocks,'' that is, ``those 
sensitive to the ups and downs of the economy, such as autos, paper 
and chemicals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Somewhere between hope and deep concern lies another comment  
from Yardeni, as published in his global economic analysis of July 
6. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of its ``bare minimum policy response'' to economic  
conditions, the outspoken Yardeni declares, the Federal Reserve's 
open market committee has sent a clear message to stock investors: 
``Have fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	How could he justify that conclusion? Because, he says, ``if the  
market is a bubble now, the bubble will get bigger.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
