<HEADLINE> Bausch &AMP; Lomb Is Selling to Amplifon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- Looking to focus on eye care, Bausch &AMP;  
Lomb Inc. is selling its Miracle Ear hearing aid business to 
Amplifon SpA of Italy. The sales price was not disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	Bausch &AMP; Lomb will lose $17 million before taxes from the  
Miracle Ear sale, spokeswoman Holly Houston said Monday. Helping to 
offset the loss will be the $12 million profit from its recent sale 
of its sunglasses business to Luxottica Group SpA, Houston said. 
</P>
<P>
	Miracle Ear, headquartered in Golden Valley, Minn., makes and  
sells hearing aids and related products through more than 1,000 
franchises and company locations. 
</P>
<P>
	Amplifon, a privately held company, is the leading distributor  
and retailer of hearing aids in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Bausch &AMP; Lomb has been refocusing in recent years on eye care --  
contact lenses, ophthalmic drugs, eye surgery instruments. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the divestiture of our hearing aid product line, we are  
close to completing our exit from those non-core businesses which 
do not leverage our heritage, brand name and technological 
competencies in the eye care field,'' said William M. Carpenter, 
chairman and chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Bausch &AMP; Lomb hopes to sell by the end of the year its last  
non-core subsidiary, Charles River Laboratories, which breeds 
animals for medical research, Houston said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
