<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bristol Bay Salmon Feast Dimmed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) -- It's been a bittersweet season for  
Bristol Bay's fishermen and for those whose living depends on their 
harvest in the world's richest sockeye salmon fishery. 
</P>
<P>
	Before this year, residents of Dillingham, King Salmon and a  
host of tiny nearby villages struggled through two seasons so 
dismal the region was declared a federal disaster area. 
</P>
<P>
	This summer the fish have returned, but seafood processors who  
have suffered right along with the fishermen now don't have enough 
capacity to handle the harvest fishermen could deliver. Fish that 
could cover past-due bills instead are headed upstream to spawn, 
die and rot. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think there are a lot of people frustrated because they  
don't have a market for all the fish they can catch,'' said Terry 
Hefferle, chief of operations for the Bristol Bay Native 
Association in Dillingham. ``Those same folks have a feeling of 
relief that the fish came back this year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The big processing companies in Bristol Bay took in as many as  
44 million fish in the peak year of 1995, a catch that was worth 
$200 million. The average harvest during the past decade is 29 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	But farmed fish have radically cut into the market for the  
frozen and canned product that Bristol Bay processors produce. Then 
came the prolonged recession in Japan and the back-to-back seasons 
of poor Bristol Bay returns -- about 12 million salmon in 1997 and 
just 10 million last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Processors lost money, and they cut back.  
</P>
<P>
	``The bad news is the industry wasn't prepared for it based on  
the last two years of poor runs,'' said Chuck Bundrant, president 
of Trident Seafoods, one of the largest of the bay's dozen or so 
processors. ``In my case, we have half the capacity we normally 
have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Norman Van Vactor, Bristol Bay manager for Peter Pan Seafoods,  
said his operation also has cut back in the past two years. 
</P>
<P>
	``The margins aren't there to speculate on the big years,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Processors in Bristol Bay can't simply bring in more workers and  
equipment when a big run materializes. Dillingham is about 350 
miles from Anchorage by air, and there are no roads. A trip around 
the tip of the Alaska Peninsula by ship covers perhaps a thousand 
miles. And the salmon run lasts only about three weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	So workers put in long shifts on the processing line, and some  
fish are shipped hundreds of miles to distant plants. 
</P>
<P>
	With an extremely perishable product, management biologists for  
the Alaska Department of Fish and Game last week decided to cut 
fishing periods instead of building up a glut of fish that would 
spoil before they could be canned or frozen. They would rather have 
extra fish going upriver to spawn -- even though too many spawners 
actually reduces survival rates. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the capacity of the processors that will determine how  
many fish we take,'' said Jeff Regnart, the regional management 
biologist in King Salmon. 
</P>
<P>
	With the run about half over, fishermen have caught 15 million  
fish so far. That's a welcome change after the two bust years. 
</P>
<P>
	For local residents, the renewed health of the local industry  
run means renewed economic health. The region depends on its salmon 
harvests the way Iowa counties depend on the corn crop. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think people are going to make their boat payments, and pay  
down some of the credit that's been extended to them,'' said 
Hoefferle of the native association. 
</P>
<P>
	``But for some people, it's come too late.'' One fisherman lost  
his boat just a couple of weeks before the season began, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It a lot better than the last couple of years,'' said Homer  
grandmother Roseleen ``Snooks'' Moore, who has fished Bristol Bay 
for 15 years. ``At least people will go home with a paycheck.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
