<HEADLINE> Former U.S. News Editor Dies at 89 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Howard Flieger, who retired in 1976 as  
executive editor of U.S. News and World Report, died Sunday of 
cardio-respiratory failure at a health care facility in suburban 
Potomac, Md. He was 89. 
</P>
<P>
	Flieger began working at U.S. News in 1945 as a political  
writer. He later became managing editor of World Report, a separate 
publication. He was named international editor in 1948 after the 
two publications merged. 
</P>
<P>
	A native of Denver, Flieger during his journalism career also  
worked at The Associated Press in Missouri and Washington. He was 
one of three reporters allowed to attend Roosevelt's funeral in 
1945. 
</P>
<P>
	He is survived by two sons.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
