<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reno Speaks at Ind. Memorial Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BLOOMINGTON, Ind. (AP) -- Haters are cowards who must be  
confronted until they back down, a solemn Attorney General Janet 
Reno said Monday at a memorial for a South Korean student killed in 
a two-state shooting rampage. 
</P>
<P>
	``People in this community came together to speak out against  
indifference. It was the right thing to do. This nation should 
follow your examples,'' Reno told the crowd of more than 1,400 who 
came to mourn Won-Joon Yoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Yoon, an Indiana University doctoral student, died July 4  
outside his church as he entered services there. Authorities 
believe he was slain by white supremacist Benjamin Nathaniel Smith, 
an undergraduate Indiana University student who committed suicide 
later that same day. 
</P>
<P>
	Reno was one of several people who spoke at a public memorial  
service for Yoon in the university's Musical Arts Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Yoon's mother, Kang-Soon Lee, lit a candle onstage in memory of  
her son. Participants later planned to march to the Korean United 
Methodist Church where Yoon died. 
</P>
<P>
	The hall was filled to capacity. Those who couldn't find seats  
gathered around television sets in the lobby, while ushers handed 
out white ribbons at the door. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to be with my community to stand against this kind of  
tragedy. You can't have this sense of detachment anymore. You have 
to stand up and say no,'' said Debarah Galyan of Bloomington, as 
she walked into the service. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, 21, was a former member of the World Church of the  
Creator, a white-supremacist group based in East Peoria, Ill. He 
was believe responsible for shootings that left two people dead and 
nine others injured in Illinois and Indiana. All the victims were 
either black, Jewish or Asian. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith later shot and killed himself in a struggle with police on  
an Illinois highway. 
</P>
<P>
	Yoon, the only son among four children, came to Bloomington  
after earning a master's degree in economics from Southern Illinois 
University. His goal was to earn a doctorate and become a teacher. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990712.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 20:36:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kasich May Drop White House Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio weighed the fate of  
his flagging presidential hopes Monday after signaling over the 
weekend he was considering quitting the race. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said  
no final decision had been made. But a fund-raising event 
originally scheduled for Monday in Seattle -- then canceled a week 
ago because of a poor response -- stood as a symbol of his faltering 
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Several Republicans said an announcement of Kasich's plans could  
come as early as Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich pondered his future as another GOP presidential hopeful,  
Sen. Bob Smith of New Hampshire, announced he was quitting the 
party. Smith thus became the first dropout of the campaign for the 
Republican nomination, although he said he was considering running 
on a third party ticket. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not clear whether Kasich intended to endorse  
front-running Texas Gov. George W. Bush or any other rival for the 
GOP nomination in the event of a withdrawal. But officials said 
there was no indication the 47-year-old Kasich was reconsidering 
his earlier tentative decision not to seek re-election to the House 
next year. 
</P>
<P>
	While campaigning in New Hampshire over the weekend, Kasich was  
asked about reports he was considering abandoning his quest. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we get to the point where we've made a decision and are  
going to talk about it, we'll let you know,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesman Todd Harris noted that, technically, Kasich has an  
exploratory committee and is not yet an officially declared 
candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich, the chairman of the House Budget Committee, has been  
running hard for months, including several trips to Iowa and New 
Hampshire, site of next year's first caucus and primary, 
respectively. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite his efforts, including widely noted speeches dealing  
with Social Security and government subsidies to business, Kasich 
was in low single digits in support in nationwide public opinion 
polls. His fund-raising efforts, like virtually everyone else's, 
were overwhelmed by Bush, who has said he collected a record $36.6 
million in the first half of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said that if he stayed in the race, Kasich would be  
required to spend a significant portion of his remaining resources 
to compete in a non-binding straw poll in Iowa next month. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
