<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-12 12:20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Forbes Goes After Federal Reserve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALGONA, Iowa (AP) -- Publisher Steve Forbes railed against the  
Federal Reserve's ``high priests of high finance'' Monday as his 
high-tech campaign bus caravan rumbled to the Chrome Country Inn 
blaring music and seeking recruits. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is heaven on earth for a campaign,'' the Republican  
presidential candidate said as he hopped off the bus into a dusty 
parking lot. ``I wish it could happen every day.'' Over seven days, 
Forbes was headed to 26 of the state's 99 counties in a grinding 
effort to flex his campaign's organizational muscle. 
</P>
<P>
	That grass-roots network is considered crucial to success in a  
high-profile straw poll next month, and the state's leadoff 
precinct caucuses next winter. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes carefully selected a message for each day of the trip:  
the Federal Reserve on Monday, taxes on Tuesday, and abortion on 
Wednesday. His strategists created a high-tech rolling circus to 
take advantage. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes said the Fed was being too tight with monetary policy,  
harming the farm economy. He called its members the ``high priests 
of high finance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Monetary policy is a big issue in Iowa where commodity prices  
are low. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm one candidate who can take them on,'' said Forbes, a  
multimillionaire. ``I know the subject, I know the people. Bring 
them on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes drew solid crowds at stops like the Chrome Country Inn --  
a popular restaurant that served up meat loaf and mashed potatoes 
to about 150 local activists. 
</P>
<P>
	On their way into the luncheon, Forbes posed for photos with  
activists as aides clicked away with special digital cameras. 
Staffers retreated to the back of the bus, where a string of laptop 
computers and printers whirred away as Forbes spoke. 
</P>
<P>
	When the activists left, their photos with Forbes were on a  
table waiting. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, Forbes distributed pledge cards for those  
interested. Motoring between stops, aides began working the five 
telephone lines in the bus ``Victory Express II. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's so competitive,'' said Steve Grubbs, a consultant who  
designed the field operation. 
</P>
<P>
	While Forbes was hammered the last time he ran for running a  
television-only campaign, he vowed to employ the very latest 
techniques this time to build from the grassroots. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to have a field operation and we're going to have  
a television operation,'' said Grubbs. 
</P>
<P>
	That can be important because the number of people active in  
caucus politics is relatively small, and a tightly organized 
campaign can have a disproportionate impact. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes proclaimed himself delighted.  
</P>
<P>
	``Every day you get people who are genuinely interested, taking  
a real look and making up their minds,''' said Forbes. ``It's not 
something you blaze at them on TV.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ken Clark is the local county Republican Chairman and he's  
signed on to Forbes' effort. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've noticed the difference,'' he said. ``People in Iowa want  
to see you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Accompanied by wife, Sabina, and the youngest of his five  
daughters, Forbes says he's having the time of his life. 
</P>
<P>
	``I enjoy hearing the questions, hearing how people react,'' he  
said. ``You can feel the thing, it's not like going on TV where you 
have no idea how the audience is reacting. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can feel the thing, you can feel it and draw energy from  
it,'' said Forbes. 
</P>
<P>
	Bus inhabitants were not suffering. A fully stocked kitchen and  
refrigerator was complimented by bowls of candy, mints and nuts -- 
restocked, of course, after every stop. 
</P>
<P>
	Before start his day, Forbes recorded a radio blurb, and aide  
K.B. Forbes worked the phone in the back of the bus peddling it to 
local radio stations. 
</P>
<P>
	``We usually get 20 to 50 takers,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Similarly, other aides take photos of Forbes with local  
dignitaries, passing them along to local newspapers who might not 
have photographer. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will leave no stone unturned,'' said Grubbs.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
